WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:04.050
- There's three types of
fun, fun for the player,

00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:06.780
fun for the designer, and
fun for the computer.

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:07.780
- Is it PvP?

00:00:07.880 --> 00:00:15.700
- It's all PvP. In fact, Rust is
the most PvP thing in all of PvP.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:19.360
- Well, I don't know what that means, but...

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:22.770
- Rust players know what that
means. My whole career and my

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:27.900
family are thanks to EverQuest,
so I think I won the game.

00:00:28.700 --> 00:00:32.259
And we're idiots. We're reading the
forums, and the forums are just

00:00:32.299 --> 00:00:36.129
flaming us all the time. Like,
"There's lag on this server,"

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:39.980
and, "Can't log into that ser-" And
that's, that was our perspective

00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:45.520
of what was happening. And
when I showed up at that show,

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:49.540
it... One of the most emotional
things in my life. It was

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.180
nothing but an outpouring of love. I had

00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:58.240
believed I would never work
any place but Blizzard.

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:00.540
I loved it. It was a part of who I was,

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:05.480
And I felt I was a part of it,
and I literally thought I would

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:11.760
retire from the place. I never thought
the day would come, and that was it.

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:14.760
- How painful was it to say goodbye?

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:16.360
- It broke me.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:19.100
- Now, meanwhile, as far
as the outside world is

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:22.320
concerned, you've disappeared
off the face of the

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:26.160
earth, but you were
actually working on a game.

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:31.200
The following is a conversation
with Jeff Kaplan, a

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:34.820
legendary game designer
of World of Warcraft and

00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:43.080
Overwatch, which are two of the biggest,
most influential games ever made. He is

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:46.420
genuinely one of the most
amazing human beings I've ever

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:50.260
met. In the many conversations I was
fortunate enough to have with him,

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:53.840
including while playing video
games, he was always kind,

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:57.660
thoughtful, hilarious,
and still and forever a

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:01.690
legit gamer, through
and through. Of course,

00:02:01.700 --> 00:02:05.540
he's always quick to celebrate the
incredible teams of creative minds he has

00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:09.199
gotten a chance to work with over
the years, and they are truly

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:12.780
incredible. Blizzard has created
some of the greatest games ever

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:16.450
made, games that to me
personally have brought me

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:20.280
thousands of hours of fun, meaning, and

00:02:20.920 --> 00:02:24.720
happiness, from Warcraft,
to StarCraft, to Diablo,

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:28.500
WoW, Overwatch and more. So
for that, a big thank you to

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:32.340
Jeff, to the entire
Blizzard team, and to every

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:36.380
creative mind in the video game
industry, giving their heart and soul

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:42.590
to build video game worlds that we fans get
a chance to enjoy. This was a super fun,

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:46.020
inspiring, whirlwind conversation, pun

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:49.100
intended, with one of the
most beloved gamers and game

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:52.800
designers ever. Full of memes, lulz,

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:56.600
wisdom, emotional rollercoaster
moments, and of course, Blizzard

00:02:56.760 --> 00:03:00.620
video game lore. Jeff left Blizzard in

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:04.630
2021, and has been secretly
working on a new video game

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:12.700
called The Legend of California that I
got a chance to play with Jeff. It is

00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:16.620
incredibly beautiful.
Set in the 1800s Gold

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:20.670
Rush era of California, it's an
open world online multiplayer game,

00:03:21.220 --> 00:03:23.940
part adventure and action, part

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.900
survival. Sometimes creating
a feeling of loneliness and

00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:31.760
desperation, and sometimes
just awe watching the

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:35.800
sun rise over a beautiful landscape.
It's unlike any game that

00:03:35.820 --> 00:03:39.560
Jeff has ever worked on, and
it's a game that I genuinely

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:43.540
can't wait to play with all of
you. You can wishlist it on

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:51.180
Steam. Join the alpha later in March, I
think, and early access is on the way. This

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:54.720
is the Lex Fridman Podcast. To
support it, please check out our

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:58.480
sponsors in the description
where you can also find links to

00:03:58.540 --> 00:04:01.940
contact me, ask questions,
give feedback, and so

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:10.100
on. And now, dear friends, here's Jeff
Kaplan. You were first a legendary video

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:13.440
game player, in particular in EverQuest,

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:20.720
before you ever became a legendary video
game designer on World of Warcraft and on

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:26.020
Overwatch, which I think is a wild
journey to go through from gamer to

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:30.040
designer. But first, let's go way
back. When did you first fall in

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:31.980
love with video games?

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:37.640
- I was lucky. I was born in
that golden era of coin-op.

00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:41.080
So, I literally remember
the first time seeing

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:44.940
Pac-Man. I was with my Uncle
Ronnie, and he just kept

00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:48.900
feeding me quarters. I think he wanted
to play, but was too scared to,

00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:54.400
so he, you know, his little nephew, he would
just give him quarters to play Pac-Man.

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:58.320
I remember being at my
brother's graduation in

00:04:58.340 --> 00:05:01.870
Philadelphia, and they had
an Asteroids machine in the

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:05.700
lobby. That was one of the first
coin-op machines I had played as

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:09.660
well. And my brother
and I would... we would

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:13.940
try to get the high score, and we'd
finally get it. But we had to go to

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.920
bed early 'cause we were little kids.
And then in the morning somebody

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:21.860
else had like beat our high
score. And then, you know, I

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:28.860
grew up in Southern California in the '80s.
I was born in '72. So, you know, I was a

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:32.880
kid with that skateboard BMX culture where

00:05:32.980 --> 00:05:36.840
we'd ride two towns over.
We knew all the pizza

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:40.740
parlors and liquor stores
and arcades, and we

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:44.600
just lived in that coin-op
phase. That was, that

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:48.600
was where the love started.
And then you started to

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:51.600
see things like Pong. You'd go over
to a friend's house, they'd have

00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:55.320
Pong, and it was just mind blowing,
like, we're playing this thing on the

00:05:55.440 --> 00:06:03.220
TV and it was so much fun. Atari
was a big thing at that time as

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:06.060
well. But the big one for me was actually

00:06:06.070 --> 00:06:09.840
Intellivision, because
my dad was an executive

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:13.700
recruiter, and one of
his clients was Mattel.

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:18.040
And he said, "Hey, I... They gave
me this thing," and he would get

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:24.580
discounts or free games. And my brothers
and I just loved Intellivision. Like,

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:28.490
we would just play it
endlessly. And the comparison

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:32.720
was always like, "Is this game
close to what's in the arcades?"

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:36.680
And it was just such a
golden era. And I think

00:06:36.740 --> 00:06:40.660
the big moment where it really blew open

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:48.090
and kind of hit the next level was
when the NES came out. And that, like,

00:06:48.220 --> 00:06:55.040
NES with Super Mario- was kind of
gaming at the next level at that

00:06:55.060 --> 00:06:58.829
point. And I have, like,
warm, fuzzy memories

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.920
even thinking about it to
this day. I remember we

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:06.900
played Super Mario for weeks,
my brothers and I, and then

00:07:06.939 --> 00:07:10.670
I had a friend come over, and he
showed me all the secret stuff-

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:13.360
... in Super that I didn't
know existed at the

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:20.280
time. And it's... it was like suddenly, the
world opened up more and games could be

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:27.960
more. And then there was, like, a
big PC gaming push that hit me. My

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.040
parents ran their own business. Like
I said, my dad was an executive

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:37.860
recruiter, and they bought an IBM. And this
is, like, when it was DOS before MS-DOS

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:44.720
existed. And I was so disappointed,
because, like, other kids had the

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:46.450
Amiga or the Commodore-

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:53.450
... which, you know, they were better
for gaming than the IBM at the time. And

00:07:54.060 --> 00:08:00.560
my mom, she really encouraged my
brother and I. She bought a Zork.

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:05.020
You know, it was just Infocom word games,

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:08.340
and where your imagination
would take you. Like,

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:13.060
Zork holds a place in my heart I
think few games will ever touch.

00:08:13.290 --> 00:08:14.480
- It's a text-based game?

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:21.570
- Text-based game. You know, you just type
in, "Go west. Open mailbox." You know?

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:23.400
And...

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:24.440
- Okay.

00:08:24.450 --> 00:08:28.060
- But it's that power of imagination. It's
why the book is always better than the

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:29.520
movie, you know?

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:33.820
- Yeah. So, you're starting to see these
creations of worlds that you can navigate.

00:08:33.920 --> 00:08:34.450
- Yes.

00:08:35.060 --> 00:08:38.700
- You can step into this world and you
can lose yourself in that world.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:41.620
- Yeah. You're transported.
You're living there.

00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:43.020
- Was Zork popular?

00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:48.580
- Zork was insanely popular. And then
there was Zork II- ... and Zork III.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:51.690
- A trilogy. Zork trilogy. I see it. Okay.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:55.640
- A- and it was weird, and, like, the... Sometime
in the '90s, there was this, there was this

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.960
era of what they called CD-ROM
games. That's how they branded

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:05.060
them. And they made a return to
Zork, but it now had graphics.

00:09:05.940 --> 00:09:09.780
And somehow, that just shattered
everything, because the Zork you

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:13.540
knew in your head didn't
exist anymore. Yeah, Zork was

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:17.580
fantastic. I think it might be open source

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:24.720
now, which I think is fabulous. But
I highly recommend Zork. There was

00:09:24.800 --> 00:09:32.410
also, in those days, on the PC that
worked on our IBM, was Ultima-

00:09:32.420 --> 00:09:35.900
... which was the Richard Garriott series.

00:09:37.200 --> 00:09:40.940
And he was Lord British. We knew him
as Lord British. He put himself in the

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:44.920
game. And you wanna talk
about world- building. You

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:49.460
know, there was Yew Forest and
there was all the characters. And

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:54.020
the first Ultima I played was Ultima
II, 'cause Ultima I was before

00:09:54.100 --> 00:10:01.660
my time. And that series,
it was this RPG group based

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:05.340
PC game, and the worlds were just so

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:08.680
rich. Like, you could get on a rocket
ship. You're playing in this fantasy

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:12.630
world, fighting demons,
and yet somehow you could

00:10:12.740 --> 00:10:16.620
get on a rocket ship. And then
there was just all of this

00:10:16.900 --> 00:10:20.120
sort of crazy stuff that would happen in

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:25.020
games that are based in the world.
Like, there were bouncers in the towns,

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:29.020
and merchants, but if you really
wanted to, you could try to rob

00:10:29.029 --> 00:10:32.860
these people, or kill
Lord British, you know?

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:36.680
That was something that was super
hard. And when you're just a jackass

00:10:36.820 --> 00:10:40.780
kid, you spend your time
endlessly trying to do these

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:48.300
things over and over, and Ultima was really
a profound kind of experience for me.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:52.100
- And, of course, that led to Ultima
Online, which is a legendary game in

00:10:52.120 --> 00:10:54.960
itself, perhaps connected to EverQuest.

00:10:55.020 --> 00:10:55.140
- Yes.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:58.700
- Sort of starting to build these
worlds that are massively

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:02.720
multiplayer online video
games. Can you take me to

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:08.880
that journey? Like, as you
started to get online, MMO world.

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:11.700
What were influential?
What were fun for you?

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:15.580
- Well, the big one for
me was EverQuest. But,

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:19.190
Like you mentioned, Ultima
Online sort of was the

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:23.060
predecessor. It came before EverQuest.

00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:27.000
And it was, like, one of those
unfortunate times in my life where I

00:11:27.040 --> 00:11:28.370
was actually at grad school.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:29.700
- You were busy.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:33.570
- I was busy, and I missed
Ultima Online. Like, I

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:37.060
would have had that experience.
And when you hear the Ultima

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:40.140
Online stories, they're
some of the craziest,

00:11:40.180 --> 00:11:44.140
funniest... You know, I know
somebody who, they learned

00:11:44.180 --> 00:11:47.560
how to poison in the
game, and then they would

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:51.440
poison apples, then leave them on the
ground, and somebody else would be

00:11:51.480 --> 00:11:55.360
adventuring, then feed the apple to
their horse and kill their horse.

00:11:55.400 --> 00:11:59.180
Then they'd steal all their stuff
and... You know, Ultima Online was kind

00:11:59.220 --> 00:12:02.740
of... It was the earliest grief-based

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:08.580
experiment. Really, like, when you're treating
the humans like ants in the ant farm.

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:10.460
That was kind of Ultima Online.

00:12:11.132 --> 00:12:12.452
- Yeah.

00:12:12.472 --> 00:12:19.932
- My first, like, what online gaming, what
defined online gaming for me was Quake

00:12:20.532 --> 00:12:25.392
and Doom and Duke Nukem. You
know, it started with Doom

00:12:26.492 --> 00:12:30.392
and they had a ... You could
basically LAN. You could

00:12:30.492 --> 00:12:34.472
network with your friends or you could
connect with a modem and hook up with

00:12:34.532 --> 00:12:37.652
somebody. And that was like a
mind-blowing ... Just seeing

00:12:37.692 --> 00:12:41.592
another entity in a video
game and saying, "That's a

00:12:41.652 --> 00:12:44.042
person on the other side of that."

00:12:44.092 --> 00:12:48.072
That was magical, like, that that
moment happened and that person

00:12:48.112 --> 00:12:51.592
could be in another room
or across town from

00:12:51.692 --> 00:12:55.392
you. And Quake kind of took it to the next

00:12:55.452 --> 00:12:59.132
level. Like, that's where
everybody knew what they were

00:12:59.172 --> 00:13:06.232
doing. The systems were more refined.
And this Quake community formed with

00:13:06.312 --> 00:13:10.212
all of these, you know,
great websites, mods. The

00:13:10.252 --> 00:13:17.472
community was divided into ... There
were two castes of players. The low ping

00:13:17.572 --> 00:13:21.512
bastards, the LPBs- ... and
then the rest of us, you know.

00:13:21.532 --> 00:13:25.312
And I remember rolling into
Quake matches, you know, on a

00:13:25.452 --> 00:13:30.052
dial-up modem with a 300 ping connection,

00:13:30.872 --> 00:13:33.972
and I thought it was the
greatest thing ever. Um,

00:13:35.112 --> 00:13:39.012
and just, just connecting
with people. Like

00:13:39.072 --> 00:13:42.992
I said, the websites. To
this day, the only gaming

00:13:43.032 --> 00:13:49.452
website I read— I don't read any of the
news sites anymore, but I read Blue's News.

00:13:49.492 --> 00:13:53.662
Which was like, like ... Someone
actually teased me recently.

00:13:53.662 --> 00:13:57.592
I linked him a story. I'm like, "Oh, did you
hear this new thing's coming out?" And I sent

00:13:57.632 --> 00:14:01.052
the link, and they're like, "Dude,
this is from Blue's News. Like,

00:14:01.792 --> 00:14:05.712
what time machine did you just
step out of?" And guy named

00:14:05.792 --> 00:14:09.232
Stephen Heaslip... I'm probably
pronouncing his name wrong. I

00:14:09.272 --> 00:14:16.932
apologize, but it was actually through
that site that I learned about EverQuest.

00:14:16.942 --> 00:14:23.932
They had those programmer plan
updates, the .plan files. And guys

00:14:23.972 --> 00:14:27.552
like Carmack would ... You
know, they'd post about

00:14:28.112 --> 00:14:32.021
what code they were writing or
how they had optimized something,

00:14:32.032 --> 00:14:35.952
or just their personal life.
Like, you know, the Ferrari talk

00:14:35.972 --> 00:14:39.432
would always happen—
once they had achieved

00:14:39.592 --> 00:14:44.292
success. And there was an id
programmer named Brian Hook,

00:14:45.332 --> 00:14:49.192
and he said, "I'm leaving id to go work

00:14:49.232 --> 00:14:53.032
at Verant," which became
Sony Online, "to work on

00:14:53.072 --> 00:15:00.332
this game called EverQuest." And I
was like, "How does anybody leave id,

00:15:00.352 --> 00:15:04.272
the greatest institution
in all of gaming ever,

00:15:05.272 --> 00:15:08.852
to work on any other game?"
I'm like, "This guy must be

00:15:08.932 --> 00:15:12.752
crazy. Or whatever this EverQuest thing

00:15:12.872 --> 00:15:16.692
is, I need to see it. I
need to know what's going

00:15:16.772 --> 00:15:22.192
on." And if he hadn't have made that post,
I never would have checked out EverQuest.

00:15:22.232 --> 00:15:25.581
- We'll talk about EverQuest, but
since you mentioned Carmack and,

00:15:25.672 --> 00:15:29.472
uh, Quake, what can we say about
the genius of John Carmack?

00:15:29.492 --> 00:15:34.172
Why was he such an important and
influential human in the history of gaming?

00:15:34.212 --> 00:15:38.992
- Those early geniuses at id ...
Like, I wouldn't be sitting here

00:15:39.932 --> 00:15:43.912
talking to you right now if they
hadn't had the breakthroughs that they

00:15:43.972 --> 00:15:50.432
had at the time. Um, gaming engines were

00:15:50.532 --> 00:15:58.032
evolving, but the level of breakthrough
that they achieved with Wolf

00:15:58.232 --> 00:16:04.292
3D, that was the first... I remember
playing Wolfenstein when it was a 2D game.

00:16:04.332 --> 00:16:08.272
You'd run around. You'd dress up as
a German. You'd throw a grenade.

00:16:08.532 --> 00:16:12.312
Um, to see it in 3D ... And
it, it's funny. You look

00:16:12.432 --> 00:16:16.352
back at the screenshots or
videos of it now, and it

00:16:16.432 --> 00:16:20.312
seems almost childish. Like, "Oh, why, why

00:16:20.352 --> 00:16:23.492
were you so excited about
that?" And you were

00:16:23.572 --> 00:16:26.902
transported. There ... It
was the intimacy of first

00:16:26.932 --> 00:16:30.752
person. You know, putting the
hands in front of you, holding the

00:16:30.792 --> 00:16:37.042
gun, being transported to Nazi Germany,
but you're the hero fighting the Nazis.

00:16:37.932 --> 00:16:41.922
And then the evolution. Like,
when Doom came out, I'm

00:16:42.012 --> 00:16:45.292
a huge Army of Darkness fan. Like,
one of my favorite movies of all

00:16:45.352 --> 00:16:48.692
time. And I was like, "This is Army of

00:16:48.812 --> 00:16:52.272
Darkness, the video game." You
know? Like, "Give me the boom

00:16:52.372 --> 00:16:55.972
stick. Here we go." And the graphical

00:16:56.072 --> 00:17:01.842
advances ... But it, it wasn't just how
the game looked, it was how it played.

00:17:01.842 --> 00:17:07.372
The smoothness kept getting
better. The responsiveness the

00:17:07.392 --> 00:17:10.792
sharpness of the gameplay.
You have to credit

00:17:11.252 --> 00:17:14.912
id in those days and
Carmack and Romero. Um,

00:17:16.012 --> 00:17:19.662
I ... As somebody who worked on
an FPS, I ... That wouldn't have

00:17:19.712 --> 00:17:22.942
existed without them.
Credit where credit's due.

00:17:22.952 --> 00:17:26.812
- And by the way, we should say you're ...
As a gamer, your range is incredible. You

00:17:26.892 --> 00:17:30.852
are a legit first-person
shooter gamer, but you also

00:17:31.232 --> 00:17:38.632
obviously love the more MMO world,
rich, exploratory kinda game. So it's

00:17:38.692 --> 00:17:42.452
fascinating. But yeah, there is ...
On the technology stack that brought

00:17:42.492 --> 00:17:46.392
something like Quake or
Wolfenstein 3D to life,

00:17:46.622 --> 00:17:49.212
there's a threshold which
you pass of realism

00:17:50.632 --> 00:17:54.492
where you can immerse yourself into that
world. I had the same exact experience

00:17:54.552 --> 00:18:02.872
with, uh, Wolfenstein 2D taking
a step to 3D, and it was like

00:18:03.092 --> 00:18:06.872
tears in my eyes. Like,
"This is incredible."

00:18:06.972 --> 00:18:10.772
Like, my memories of Wolfenstein
3D is it was like ultra

00:18:10.852 --> 00:18:14.512
realistic. It's silly to say now. .

00:18:14.552 --> 00:18:18.380
It was the feeling like you were
there.Yeah, what an incredible

00:18:18.520 --> 00:18:22.340
age. And some of that, the
storytelling, a lot of that

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:26.340
is the- technology that brings
that kind of 3D world to life.

00:18:26.360 --> 00:18:29.400
It's incredible. But
before- we get too far

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:35.319
on that tangent you mentioned
grad school. We should

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:39.200
mention that you have a master's
degree in creative writing from

00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:45.030
NYU, and you wanted to be a writer.
You told me your main influences were

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:48.940
Kerouac, but also Hemingway,
Salinger, Bukowski,

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:52.689
Orwell. What drew you
to storytelling in that

00:18:52.740 --> 00:18:56.240
medium of writing? What
aspect of the human

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:58.670
experience were you trying
to put down on paper?

00:18:59.460 --> 00:19:03.400
- Well, it started with being a
fan first and being inspired

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:10.960
and reading, and it's the, not only being
transported to a different world or into

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:15.600
a different person, but also, you know,

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:24.650
the way that stories can touch
emotions in you and trigger feelings

00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:31.520
sometimes you didn't even know you had.
And that was very appealing for me. And

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:36.040
the big challenge with it
is, and I think this is

00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:41.440
for anybody who creates anything,
is putting yourself out there.

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:45.430
Um, to some degree,
there's a lot of ego that

00:19:45.460 --> 00:19:52.480
goes into that moment where you say,
"Well, I've been reading, you know, 1984

00:19:52.580 --> 00:20:00.320
or Green Hills of Stranglethorn, and
I think it's amazing. And now I'm

00:20:00.340 --> 00:20:05.840
gonna try to write something
that somebody is gonna read."

00:20:05.920 --> 00:20:09.780
Uh, that's a giant leap of faith. You
know, that's a moment of putting yourself

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:14.040
out there completely, and there's
gotta be some part of that

00:20:14.860 --> 00:20:19.180
that's ego. There's some part
of it that's masochistic.

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:25.020
Um, and I think for people
who want to create and build

00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:28.960
stuff, they can't help but to
do it. You don't really have an

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:32.880
option. That's just how you're
wired, and you're gonna do it

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:36.579
anyway. And, you know, I admire

00:20:37.140 --> 00:20:41.040
people like Dickinson who can just
write all the poems and leave them

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:44.340
in a drawer to be discovered
by somebody else.

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:46.360
You know, that's one way to go about it.

00:20:46.400 --> 00:20:50.060
- Yeah, Franz Kafka, you know, a lot
of the stories he wrote, never

00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:52.900
published, and he asked
for all of them to be

00:20:52.980 --> 00:20:59.900
destroyed. And then it's only because of
his friend that ignored his request that we

00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:03.900
even have many of his stories.
It's like to be that kinda... I

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:08.880
mean, clearly, there's some
masochism there, some tortured soul.

00:21:08.900 --> 00:21:12.840
But then there's also the ego like you
mentioned. I was entertained by this story of

00:21:12.900 --> 00:21:16.420
James Joyce, When he was a young man,

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:23.060
18, 19, Declared that he's going
to be the greatest writer of the

00:21:23.200 --> 00:21:26.940
20th century. And he turned out
in many, in the eyes of many

00:21:27.020 --> 00:21:30.550
to be one of the greatest writers of
the 20th century. But there's, like,

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:34.430
millions of kids just like
James Joyce, writers, they're

00:21:34.440 --> 00:21:38.360
declaring exactly that, that turn
out not to be. But that is in

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:43.389
some cases, in many cases, maybe most
cases, you have to have that ego-

00:21:43.400 --> 00:21:47.580
... to say, "I'm gonna..." Yeah, right.
"I read 1984," "and I'm going to write

00:21:48.700 --> 00:21:50.460
the next 1984."

00:21:50.520 --> 00:21:54.510
- Yeah. And I do think ego
is a big part of it.

00:21:54.540 --> 00:21:58.400
it's one of the many lessons
I've learned. Hearing your Kafka

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:04.030
story is funny, because fast-forwarding
to how my writing career ended—

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:08.160
... I literally threw away
everything, I mean, in a dumpster. I

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:12.109
used to keep copious
notes, like journals, my

00:22:12.120 --> 00:22:16.109
writing journals, everything I
ever read, every story idea.

00:22:16.500 --> 00:22:23.020
I probably had 20 volumes of just
handwritten notes. And then I also kept

00:22:23.060 --> 00:22:26.840
personal journals of just, you know,
to keep the writing habit up of

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:30.530
just, you know, what happened in
my day, how I was feeling, all of

00:22:30.580 --> 00:22:37.740
that. And then either digitally or
typed, I had all of my manuscripts, and

00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:40.160
I threw it all in the dumpster.

00:22:40.180 --> 00:22:44.100
- What was that decision? Do you remember that
decision? What was that- what was that like

00:22:44.180 --> 00:22:50.520
to just take that part of your life
and just put it in a dumpster?

00:22:50.600 --> 00:22:57.680
- Yeah. It was I think it was necessary.
It was necessary. This is like

00:22:57.720 --> 00:23:02.830
rationalizing it after the fact,
you know, which is easy to do.

00:23:02.830 --> 00:23:10.350
You know? But at the time, I think I
was so broken and so defeated with

00:23:10.400 --> 00:23:15.900
failure that I needed the moment. It
was like throwing in the towel for

00:23:15.910 --> 00:23:20.980
a boxer, you know? It's that moment of
like, "I'm not gonna win this fight,

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:25.590
and you need to move on
from it." And if there was

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:28.660
any element of that sitting around,

00:23:30.060 --> 00:23:34.940
I'd be tempted to try again or bring
it out of the drawer 10 years later.

00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:38.300
- We should mention that
you did give it a- a real

00:23:38.360 --> 00:23:42.220
try. You've mentioned receiving
over 170 rejection letters in

00:23:42.300 --> 00:23:48.070
one year when submitting your stories.
So there's a lot of rejection.

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:54.040
So it was a long chain of rejection. And
then what was that like, the rejection?

00:23:54.120 --> 00:23:57.700
- It was hard. Um, I had
moved from New York.

00:23:58.460 --> 00:24:02.360
Um, I did the most terrible dumb thing
that I knew I was doing at the time. I

00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:06.140
had a really great group of
writer friends from grad

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:09.840
school in New York, and I think
writing is a very lonely,

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:13.660
solitary thing. But weirdly,
writers kind of support each

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:17.690
other and just, "Who do you give the
story to?" You know, you don't wanna give

00:24:17.720 --> 00:24:21.100
it to your mom or dad, you know. You
kinda wanna give it to somebody who's

00:24:21.140 --> 00:24:24.420
gonna really punch you in the nose
and tell you what's wrong with

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:29.992
it. And I had left that writing
circle to move back to California.

00:24:30.032 --> 00:24:35.272
- Did you take a bunch of drugs, take
your typewriter and drove across, uh-

00:24:35.692 --> 00:24:35.962
- No.

00:24:35.962 --> 00:24:39.472
- ... across the United States and
then wrote a book about it? Or

00:24:39.832 --> 00:24:44.212
just to take Kerouac as an example.
Anyway, sorry. You went just-

00:24:44.232 --> 00:24:46.912
- I might have been more
successful had- ... I done that.

00:24:47.012 --> 00:24:48.712
- Uh, so sorry. So you went back.

00:24:48.792 --> 00:24:52.672
- So I moved back to California,
and I did it for a girl.

00:24:52.752 --> 00:24:56.532
And I think within two months of moving

00:24:56.652 --> 00:25:00.482
back, we were broken up. So... And
I knew it when I was standing in my

00:25:00.552 --> 00:25:04.492
studio apartment when it was empty in New York
and I was about to close the door for the

00:25:04.532 --> 00:25:10.272
last time. I had that like, you know,
little me on the shoulder saying,

00:25:11.592 --> 00:25:13.102
"Dude, what are you doing?"

00:25:13.102 --> 00:25:16.872
"This... You're making one of those
epic life mistakes that is gonna come

00:25:16.912 --> 00:25:24.332
back to haunt you." And I ended up alone
in California, and I think it was a good

00:25:24.372 --> 00:25:27.912
three years that I structured my

00:25:27.952 --> 00:25:31.712
life where I was gonna write
for eight hours a day, because

00:25:31.772 --> 00:25:35.712
it's that writer's habit. Like
you have to just force yourself,

00:25:35.722 --> 00:25:39.372
"This is a job. This isn't a
hobby. Whether I like it or

00:25:39.472 --> 00:25:43.392
not, rain or shine, sick or
healthy, I'm gonna write for

00:25:43.432 --> 00:25:47.112
eight hours a day." And I did. Um, I was

00:25:47.212 --> 00:25:50.932
fortunate. Like I said, my dad
had his company and he hired

00:25:50.992 --> 00:25:54.952
me as a research associate.
So I was calling up

00:25:54.972 --> 00:25:58.802
generating name lists for a recruiting
company, and I would take...

00:25:58.832 --> 00:26:02.792
Whenever there was East Coast assignments, I would
take those so I could start at like 5:00 in the

00:26:02.872 --> 00:26:06.772
morning. And I created
all this space for me to

00:26:06.792 --> 00:26:11.242
write, and I just... I
had a dog named Jack-

00:26:11.272 --> 00:26:14.952
... who was... He was a Jack Russell
Terrier. And so everybody's like, "You're a

00:26:15.032 --> 00:26:18.832
writer, you named your Jack Russell Terrier
Jack." I'm like, "Because I named him

00:26:18.912 --> 00:26:21.662
after Jack Kerouac." "It's
poetic and epic," and-

00:26:21.672 --> 00:26:22.222
- Yeah, of course

00:26:22.222 --> 00:26:25.132
- ... I just looked like a dumbass,
but- ... it was just me and this

00:26:25.152 --> 00:26:32.892
dog. And I was writing, you know, all that
time intensely. And this was mid to late

00:26:32.902 --> 00:26:36.792
'90s, so even though
internet existed, email

00:26:36.872 --> 00:26:43.372
was very primitive and you had to send
a manuscript off, like printed paper-

00:26:43.992 --> 00:26:47.732
... to all... Like, I was trying to get
short stories published in literary

00:26:47.832 --> 00:26:55.392
magazines, and you had to send envelope
with return self-address stamp. So it was

00:26:55.452 --> 00:26:58.432
expensive, too. Like if you
didn't have money, you were

00:26:58.472 --> 00:27:02.561
just... There was a cost to it-
... to every single one of them.

00:27:02.752 --> 00:27:06.932
- You had to pay for the rejection letter
that you would eventually receive.

00:27:07.032 --> 00:27:10.482
- Yeah. And the, like, big thing
that you were hoping for

00:27:11.052 --> 00:27:17.632
was that the editor would write you a
note with the rejection letter. Like, um-

00:27:17.692 --> 00:27:18.672
- Keep going.

00:27:18.732 --> 00:27:24.172
- Yeah. And you'd like cling onto
this. Like, it was like, "Oh,

00:27:24.492 --> 00:27:27.612
Glimmer Train said, you know, showing

00:27:27.752 --> 00:27:31.532
promise." You know, and you just hang
onto that for like a week, you know,

00:27:31.552 --> 00:27:35.532
pretending like that
was... But it was just

00:27:35.632 --> 00:27:39.492
soul crushing. And I really
stuck... And I became

00:27:39.632 --> 00:27:43.061
more and more isolated. Part of that was

00:27:43.132 --> 00:27:46.852
leaving that group of
writing friends in New

00:27:46.892 --> 00:27:50.561
York. I'm prone to just
introversion anyway.

00:27:50.592 --> 00:27:55.532
The type of person I am. Breaking
up with the girlfriend at the time.

00:27:56.712 --> 00:28:03.332
I just sort of fell into that world
of like all I was doing was writing.

00:28:04.092 --> 00:28:14.532
And it broke me. Like, I went into very
deep and heavy depression. I drank too

00:28:14.592 --> 00:28:18.372
much. I really had a problem
with alcohol. And all those

00:28:18.432 --> 00:28:24.722
things compounded into just
deep, deep depression. And

00:28:25.632 --> 00:28:28.492
I don't... There wasn't like a magic

00:28:29.912 --> 00:28:33.592
rejection that broke me. That
would have been epic if like-

00:28:33.692 --> 00:28:37.552
... someone out there is like, "The
dude who..." "I'm the dude who broke

00:28:37.612 --> 00:28:40.061
Jeff that one day."

00:28:40.072 --> 00:28:47.332
But I just had a moment where I
said, "This is gonna destroy me."

00:28:47.392 --> 00:28:50.792
And... Like, I don't want to be

00:28:50.892 --> 00:28:54.832
discouraging to anybody, because I
really do believe, like you hear it so

00:28:54.892 --> 00:28:58.822
much, like, "You have to work
for your dreams, never give up."

00:28:58.832 --> 00:29:03.962
Like, we're trained this way.
Like, "Never give up." The

00:29:04.112 --> 00:29:10.292
universe... Actually, maybe not
the universe. A group of editors

00:29:10.372 --> 00:29:14.232
at literary magazines
across the United States

00:29:14.272 --> 00:29:20.292
was telling me it was time to give up as
a writer, like I wasn't cut out for it.

00:29:21.212 --> 00:29:24.492
And I stopped.

00:29:24.552 --> 00:29:30.592
- Sometimes, you know, closing a door
is required for another door to open.

00:29:30.632 --> 00:29:33.232
That's one of the hardest
things to do, is to walk away.

00:29:33.312 --> 00:29:37.242
- Yeah. And I think, rightly so, our

00:29:37.392 --> 00:29:42.432
parents, our coaches, our
mentors train us not to give up.

00:29:42.472 --> 00:29:46.452
And I think a lot of us take
pride in that, "I'm never

00:29:46.532 --> 00:29:49.472
gonna give up. I'm gonna
do this come hell or high

00:29:49.512 --> 00:29:53.032
water." And sometimes there's that

00:29:53.072 --> 00:29:56.402
reality, especially when
you're now in your mid-20s,

00:29:57.072 --> 00:30:01.052
where you have that moment of like,
"Am I really gonna be this? Like, am

00:30:01.132 --> 00:30:09.032
I ever gonna sort of find the light
here?" And, maybe, and it's so hard, it's

00:30:09.112 --> 00:30:12.802
so hard to have this moment, "Maybe
this isn't my calling in life,"

00:30:12.852 --> 00:30:15.782
especially when you don't know
what the next calling is gonna be.

00:30:15.812 --> 00:30:19.722
- That's so painful. It's 'cause
you've invested so much

00:30:19.772 --> 00:30:23.642
of yourself, of who you are, of the
dreams you've had, of this just

00:30:23.672 --> 00:30:26.972
whole conception of yourself, and
you're watching yourself slide

00:30:27.012 --> 00:30:30.872
down in terms of becoming
isolated, suffering more and

00:30:30.912 --> 00:30:34.762
And then you just have to
somehow figure out how to-

00:30:34.812 --> 00:30:41.802
get out of that. And it is true. In
that situation, the way to get out

00:30:42.032 --> 00:30:47.922
is the dumpster. Is to
cut it off. Is there

00:30:47.952 --> 00:30:51.872
advice you can extract from that?
There's a lot of young folks who are

00:30:51.892 --> 00:30:54.392
in that same situation.

00:30:54.452 --> 00:30:57.932
- Yeah. This is one of
those hindsight things

00:30:57.992 --> 00:31:01.902
where, you know, having gone through
it and ended up okay on the other

00:31:01.952 --> 00:31:05.732
side, which you don't know at
the time, you know? When you're

00:31:06.572 --> 00:31:09.202
a young person in your
late teens or early 20s,

00:31:10.012 --> 00:31:13.762
there's so much pressure
on you. And I really think

00:31:13.812 --> 00:31:16.392
adults don't help. You
know? Every time you run

00:31:16.452 --> 00:31:20.432
into the younger nephew
or whoever and you start

00:31:20.452 --> 00:31:23.842
to say things like, "Oh, what's your
major? What are you gonna do with that?"

00:31:23.842 --> 00:31:29.592
"What do you wanna be?" It's such bullshit
to do to a human being. You know?

00:31:29.692 --> 00:31:33.472
- You're so lost in the world. I
mean, most of us are lost our

00:31:33.492 --> 00:31:37.232
entire lives, but especially in
your 20s, you know, like, you're

00:31:37.352 --> 00:31:41.152
lost. So the questions like, yeah, "What
are you, what are you doing? What's your

00:31:41.212 --> 00:31:44.572
major? What's the career?" And
so on, that's not the point,

00:31:44.632 --> 00:31:48.492
man. I'm trying to find,

00:31:48.552 --> 00:31:52.172
I'm trying to move through the world,
I'm trying to run through the world to

00:31:52.232 --> 00:31:56.192
find the thing that sparks my
heart, to find the passion, to

00:31:56.232 --> 00:31:58.912
find what I'm meant to
be on this earth for.

00:32:00.252 --> 00:32:03.712
And there are really, I mean,
that is a real hero's journey of

00:32:03.772 --> 00:32:07.572
searching as a young
person. That's a real,

00:32:07.612 --> 00:32:11.192
like, you know, all the
adults, with their wisdom,

00:32:11.732 --> 00:32:15.382
they've stopped searching often. They've

00:32:15.732 --> 00:32:19.572
done the lazy, the comfortable thing.
They found their thing. And so now they

00:32:19.632 --> 00:32:23.532
look back, they don't
remember how much suffering

00:32:23.572 --> 00:32:28.282
and how, how much uncertainty that
young people have to deal with.

00:32:28.312 --> 00:32:32.092
- It's, there's confusion,
there's pressure. Like, the

00:32:32.212 --> 00:32:38.622
pressure we exert on younger people for
having it figured out is, it's insane.

00:32:39.572 --> 00:32:42.192
So the advice that I always give,

00:32:43.911 --> 00:32:48.921
and it sounds so stupid, like
this sounds really trite, but

00:32:51.452 --> 00:32:58.902
focus on what you wanna do, not what
you wanna be. The, the pressure that

00:32:59.492 --> 00:33:01.902
society kind of puts on us is, you know,

00:33:02.952 --> 00:33:06.772
"Oh, do you wanna be an astronaut? Do you
wanna be a firefighter? Do you wanna be a

00:33:06.792 --> 00:33:13.592
writer? Do you wanna be a game maker?" And
I think we get lost in the trappings of,

00:33:15.372 --> 00:33:21.692
like a vision of what that role is- ...
and how to perform as a fake actor in that

00:33:22.192 --> 00:33:28.942
role. Versus when you're off the clock
and no one's asking you any questions-

00:33:29.292 --> 00:33:32.952
... you know, you're not at Thanksgiving
dinner and your uncle's pressuring you

00:33:33.032 --> 00:33:36.192
into, you know, what your future's
gonna be for the rest of your

00:33:36.252 --> 00:33:39.772
life. When you go home,
how do you spend your

00:33:39.832 --> 00:33:43.532
time? Like, what makes you happy?
What brings you fulfillment?

00:33:44.852 --> 00:33:47.772
And through those paths,
you're gonna find out

00:33:48.972 --> 00:33:55.072
what you're gonna become, not what you
wanna be. It's, "What do you wanna do?"

00:33:55.112 --> 00:33:59.092
- What do you wanna do? The thing
that brings you joy on a moment

00:33:59.192 --> 00:34:03.112
by moment basis. Yeah.
That's brilliantly put. And

00:34:03.232 --> 00:34:07.132
speaking of which, that's
where you took the pivot.

00:34:07.192 --> 00:34:13.592
You switched to video games. How did
that happen? Gradually? Suddenly?

00:34:13.632 --> 00:34:17.312
- Gradually and suddenly. So when I had that

00:34:17.352 --> 00:34:21.302
fateful moment where I just
sort of gave up with writing,

00:34:21.752 --> 00:34:25.632
I had these days where I'd
structure eight-hour chunks

00:34:25.972 --> 00:34:29.902
of just, this was writing time,
you know? I'd sit solitary

00:34:30.172 --> 00:34:34.022
typing. All that was gone.
And, you know, I could still

00:34:34.052 --> 00:34:37.872
support myself, which was
nice. And then I had this free

00:34:37.952 --> 00:34:44.772
time and I wasn't spending it with anybody,
I was just alone. Me and the dog, Jack.

00:34:44.832 --> 00:34:50.452
And I just poured it all into EverQuest.

00:34:50.472 --> 00:34:58.052
You know, I, it was 1999 when that
game came out. And I had a friend,

00:34:58.132 --> 00:35:01.882
Victor, like kind of a lifelong friend.
One of the few friends I had who

00:35:02.052 --> 00:35:05.972
played computer games, 'cause
there was a stigma to that.

00:35:06.012 --> 00:35:09.572
You know? It wasn't, you didn't walk
around telling people you played

00:35:09.612 --> 00:35:13.052
games. They thought you wasted
your time. And my friend,

00:35:13.092 --> 00:35:16.872
Vic, had bought EverQuest. I'm like,
"That's that game that that guy Brian

00:35:16.952 --> 00:35:22.672
Hook went to work on. Is it good?" And he's
like, "Yeah, you gotta play it." And the

00:35:23.012 --> 00:35:30.032
moment I logged in, I was just transported.
It was the world of Norrath. And

00:35:30.992 --> 00:35:34.502
it wasn't just the world itself and
how it looked, I thought the game was

00:35:34.552 --> 00:35:41.072
gorgeous, it was the mechanics,
you know, that I was this halfling

00:35:41.092 --> 00:35:44.602
rogue that, you know, had to go out and

00:35:44.632 --> 00:35:48.432
adventure in the world, and when I killed
stuff, I got experience, and I needed

00:35:48.552 --> 00:35:53.452
better loot to kill more stuff
to get more experience. And

00:35:54.912 --> 00:36:02.412
the sort of draw of progression in
the game it was amazing. I, and I

00:36:02.472 --> 00:36:06.372
just lived my life of, "I
can't wait 'til the next time

00:36:06.472 --> 00:36:14.142
I log in." There was a lot of escapism
going. It wasn't all healthy. When all was

00:36:14.142 --> 00:36:17.492
said and done, when I finally
had quit EverQuest three days

00:36:17.552 --> 00:36:21.472
later, you could type in
the command /played to see

00:36:21.512 --> 00:36:28.972
how much played time you had. I had, I
think it was like 272 played days in three

00:36:29.132 --> 00:36:34.432
years. So you start to do the
math on like, how much time-

00:36:35.012 --> 00:36:41.668
... in those three years I was living
in that world. It was...It was kind of

00:36:41.728 --> 00:36:42.688
insane.

00:36:42.728 --> 00:36:47.868
- Well, that's over 6,000
hours- ... of gameplay.

00:36:47.908 --> 00:36:51.788
Wow. So here going to
Perplexity, EverQuest

00:36:52.048 --> 00:36:55.848
is a long-running 3D fantasy,
massively multiplayer online

00:36:55.928 --> 00:36:59.528
role-playing game, MMORPG,
set in the world of

00:36:59.568 --> 00:37:03.728
Norrath, as you were saying.
First released in March 1999,

00:37:04.808 --> 00:37:08.508
it is an online role-playing game
where thousands of players create

00:37:08.608 --> 00:37:12.488
characters, group up, and explore
a persistent shared world.

00:37:12.508 --> 00:37:16.318
It's widely regarded as one
of the foundational MMORPGs,

00:37:16.368 --> 00:37:20.088
helping define raid content,
guild systems and 3D online

00:37:20.128 --> 00:37:23.598
worlds. That's the other component
of it. There's... It's all humans

00:37:24.228 --> 00:37:28.488
and they group up- ... and they
raid together in the game.

00:37:28.508 --> 00:37:35.268
- Yep. In the context of EverQuest, raiding
is usually around 30 people or more

00:37:36.248 --> 00:37:39.158
getting together to conquer
something that you couldn't beat

00:37:39.428 --> 00:37:42.948
otherwise. And to do successful

00:37:43.008 --> 00:37:46.888
raiding, you usually needed
to join what in EverQuest

00:37:46.968 --> 00:37:50.798
everyone referred to
as an Uber Guild. So I

00:37:50.848 --> 00:37:54.578
had this great pride in my EverQuest
journey that I... Most of the

00:37:54.668 --> 00:37:58.088
time leveling up I was
unguilded or I was in like a

00:37:58.188 --> 00:38:05.688
role-playing guild with rogues only. And
it was when I got to Level 50 in EverQuest

00:38:05.748 --> 00:38:09.738
was the top level, I got invited into this

00:38:09.808 --> 00:38:13.648
guild called Legacy of
Steel, which on our server

00:38:13.768 --> 00:38:17.958
was the top. Every server had a top guild.

00:38:18.008 --> 00:38:21.948
And I was on a server called The
Nameless Server, and the top

00:38:22.008 --> 00:38:28.988
guild was Legacy of Steel.
And that, the thrill of

00:38:29.048 --> 00:38:32.958
getting 30 people together to go
see if you could beat, you know,

00:38:33.388 --> 00:38:37.928
Nagafen, who was the fire dragon,
or Vox, who was the frost dragon,

00:38:39.088 --> 00:38:42.868
and needing perfect
coordination to pull it off,

00:38:42.988 --> 00:38:46.598
it was insane how fun. Like, you
would literally scream out. You're

00:38:46.668 --> 00:38:48.728
alone in your room at home-

00:38:49.428 --> 00:38:52.768
... but you felt like you were there
with these people and you would

00:38:52.848 --> 00:38:58.448
audibly cheer out when you won, and
you'd feel depressed when you lost, and

00:38:59.328 --> 00:39:03.238
it was a game of high highs
and low lows, and it did

00:39:03.248 --> 00:39:05.248
everything right. It was amazing.

00:39:05.308 --> 00:39:09.688
- So that was a big leap for you to
go from the proud lone warrior

00:39:10.708 --> 00:39:13.928
to a member of a guild, Uber Guild.

00:39:14.788 --> 00:39:18.577
And then there's that epic
story of you rising to the

00:39:18.668 --> 00:39:22.128
top to become the leader
of this Uber Guild.

00:39:22.148 --> 00:39:28.508
- The leader... Yeah. So organizing
people in an online game

00:39:28.768 --> 00:39:32.218
like EverQuest is like herding cats-

00:39:32.218 --> 00:39:39.548
... 'cause, you know, everyone has their
own will. Some people are loot motivated,

00:39:39.608 --> 00:39:43.598
some people want the guild to do
well, some people are just lonely

00:39:43.648 --> 00:39:47.588
and want people to hang out with. And

00:39:48.608 --> 00:39:52.448
there was also a lot of depression in the
EverQuest community. It was something I

00:39:52.488 --> 00:39:56.308
suffered with, but a lot of
people, you know, anytime you're

00:39:57.008 --> 00:40:00.748
feeling sad or down,
you're looking for escape.

00:40:00.768 --> 00:40:04.748
And one of the great things video
games brings us is escapism.

00:40:04.808 --> 00:40:10.378
And escapism isn't always bad or negative-

00:40:11.208 --> 00:40:15.028
... but when you sort of
abuse it to escape your real

00:40:15.098 --> 00:40:17.848
life problems, it's bad and negative.

00:40:18.128 --> 00:40:25.318
- So there's a mix of pain and
darkness that pain can manifest as-

00:40:25.448 --> 00:40:27.408
... all part of this community.

00:40:27.468 --> 00:40:32.868
- Yeah. And what's weird is you enter the
cycle where being with other people

00:40:32.928 --> 00:40:36.568
gives you comradery and relief and

00:40:36.948 --> 00:40:39.988
makes you feel like you're
not doing so bad in life,

00:40:40.888 --> 00:40:45.728
but you can quickly enter a cycle of...
But then you're withdrawing from life

00:40:46.608 --> 00:40:50.248
and it makes you feel that way more
to where you can only get the fix

00:40:50.528 --> 00:40:53.758
from the game at that point. So it's...

00:40:54.248 --> 00:40:57.207
Psychologically, there's
a lot going on there.

00:40:57.228 --> 00:41:01.158
- And so you had to work with all of
that. You have to get a bunch of

00:41:01.188 --> 00:41:04.878
people together to do a raid, who are all

00:41:04.928 --> 00:41:08.828
human beings going through complicated
psychological journeys of their

00:41:08.908 --> 00:41:12.768
own. Some are talking shit, some are

00:41:12.848 --> 00:41:15.758
just quietly lonely, just
looking for some loot.

00:41:16.708 --> 00:41:19.708
- In the late '90s, everyone
was talking shit.

00:41:19.748 --> 00:41:23.508
You know what I mean? Like, the gaming
culture was just a different thing

00:41:23.548 --> 00:41:27.388
back then. But it was a great

00:41:27.548 --> 00:41:31.388
group. It was super fun. It
was people from all walks of

00:41:31.448 --> 00:41:34.928
life. And to coordinate these
people, like you just had

00:41:34.968 --> 00:41:42.048
to repeat everything like 200 times.
Like, "Okay, we're gonna port from North

00:41:42.208 --> 00:41:46.048
Ro. Everybody get to North Ro." And
then you'd have to repeat that for

00:41:46.088 --> 00:41:47.928
like six hours-

00:41:47.948 --> 00:41:51.528
... to have any chance of like 20%
of the people showing up in North

00:41:51.668 --> 00:41:55.468
Ro. And I sort of like... At

00:41:55.588 --> 00:41:59.188
first I joined the guild, I was
just like the bright-eyed, bushy-

00:41:59.228 --> 00:42:03.128
tail. Like, I was like one of the few
rogues in the guild. I just wanted to

00:42:03.148 --> 00:42:06.818
be helpful. I really admired
the people running the

00:42:06.908 --> 00:42:10.308
guild. Like, we had a great guild leader.

00:42:11.288 --> 00:42:15.228
and it was just a really
fun experience. And, you

00:42:15.288 --> 00:42:18.918
know, the guild leader
one day just disappeared.

00:42:18.988 --> 00:42:22.758
Like, he quit and he was going
through, you know, his own

00:42:22.788 --> 00:42:26.728
thing, and that's what would happen in
EverQuest. Like, people would just kinda

00:42:26.788 --> 00:42:30.628
disappear all of a sudden. There
wasn't a, "Hey, in about a month, I'm

00:42:30.668 --> 00:42:34.918
gonna stop playing because
I'm starting this new job."

00:42:34.928 --> 00:42:38.876
People... people had to quit in
some dramatic way, where they

00:42:38.936 --> 00:42:43.136
just disappear, and basically,
our guild leader stopped playing.

00:42:43.396 --> 00:42:47.276
- Did you miss them when they disappeared?
Like, we should say that most

00:42:47.356 --> 00:42:50.096
of the people, maybe all of them,
were anonymous. So you just-

00:42:50.106 --> 00:42:53.776
...have a username, and you don't
really say who you are in real life.

00:42:53.896 --> 00:42:57.756
- Absolutely. In those days,
there was a great stigma to

00:42:57.776 --> 00:43:01.676
mentioning your, any
real-life info. You just kind

00:43:01.716 --> 00:43:05.556
of kept it all really close to
your chest, and you never knew

00:43:05.646 --> 00:43:10.806
who was male or female. You kind
of assumed everybody was male.

00:43:11.316 --> 00:43:11.816
- Safe assumption.

00:43:11.836 --> 00:43:15.136
- And then it was a surprise if
they were actually female.

00:43:15.236 --> 00:43:19.076
Like my wife, for example,
that's how I met her.

00:43:19.136 --> 00:43:20.176
- You met her in EverQuest?

00:43:20.236 --> 00:43:21.586
- I met her in EverQuest.

00:43:21.616 --> 00:43:23.016
- That is a true love story, right there.

00:43:23.036 --> 00:43:24.145
- Yeah. Yeah.

00:43:24.176 --> 00:43:25.256
- Wow.

00:43:25.316 --> 00:43:29.076
- The funny part for me with
EverQuest is, you know, you

00:43:29.176 --> 00:43:32.996
play a game as much as I played EverQuest,
and people are like, "You threw years of your

00:43:33.076 --> 00:43:37.036
life away." Like, "You can't win
a game like that." And I'm like,

00:43:37.396 --> 00:43:45.336
"I don't know, like, sitting here today, my
whole career and my family are thanks to

00:43:45.416 --> 00:43:49.066
EverQuest, so I think I won the game."

00:43:49.956 --> 00:43:52.226
- Yeah, yeah. You're like the,
the, "Well, actually..." guy.

00:43:52.236 --> 00:43:54.306
- Well, yeah, exactly.

00:43:54.336 --> 00:43:57.936
- Your life will be on the Wikipedia page
somewhere that says, "Well, here's an

00:43:57.956 --> 00:44:01.586
example of somebody-" "...
why video games are awesome."

00:44:02.776 --> 00:44:06.536
Yeah, I mean, some of it... I should
mention this as an aside. For me and many

00:44:06.576 --> 00:44:10.496
people I know, yes, it's hundreds
of hours, but some of the

00:44:10.576 --> 00:44:14.366
happiest hours and days of my life. Like,

00:44:14.416 --> 00:44:18.356
looking back, it all worked
out. During it, you are

00:44:18.396 --> 00:44:22.356
pretty low, and you think, "I... What am
I doing with my life?" All that kind of

00:44:22.396 --> 00:44:26.896
stuff. But, like, looking back,
just the all-nighters you pull

00:44:27.156 --> 00:44:30.236
playing a particular video game,
allowing yourself to really fully be

00:44:30.256 --> 00:44:36.876
immersed seeing the sun come up, and by
the way, many of those games, for me, were

00:44:36.956 --> 00:44:40.896
Blizzard games. It's just an incredible
thing that video games have been

00:44:40.976 --> 00:44:44.796
able to do. I think you know, it used
to be, and still is somewhat the

00:44:44.876 --> 00:44:47.886
case, that books do that
kind of same thing. They-

00:44:47.886 --> 00:44:51.006
...they take you on a journey.
But video games, for a long

00:44:51.096 --> 00:44:55.046
time, you're right, they
had a stigma. Like,

00:44:55.116 --> 00:45:00.556
I couldn't tell people. I felt like I
was doing, like, heroin or something.

00:45:00.576 --> 00:45:03.456
Like, I felt like I was doing this
secret, dark thing. It's usually in

00:45:03.476 --> 00:45:07.306
the... It's, it usually is
in the dark. There's just a

00:45:07.306 --> 00:45:10.556
secretive nature to it, like I'm doing
something really dark and shady.

00:45:10.636 --> 00:45:12.216
- It wasn't mainstream.

00:45:12.276 --> 00:45:12.816
- It wasn't.

00:45:12.876 --> 00:45:16.766
- It wasn't... There was a stigma
to it. And one of the weirdest

00:45:16.796 --> 00:45:20.186
parts of that is, you know, I
mentioned, like, you could type in the

00:45:20.236 --> 00:45:27.816
/played in EverQuest. Well, if you
did the /played on how much TV people

00:45:27.936 --> 00:45:31.176
watch, what would that
look like? It would blow-

00:45:31.296 --> 00:45:35.116
...6,000 hours out of
the water, easily. Well,

00:45:35.196 --> 00:45:38.976
it... 20 years ago it would
have. You know? Not today.

00:45:39.036 --> 00:45:47.425
- Now it's the phone, yeah. Yeah. But then
it is hard to say goodbye to that world.

00:45:47.436 --> 00:45:52.516
Those are also really painful times.
How hard was it to say goodbye for you?

00:45:52.576 --> 00:45:57.996
- To EverQuest? It was really hard. And
there were times where you try to quit.

00:45:58.036 --> 00:45:59.376
- Oh, you took a break sometimes?

00:45:59.436 --> 00:46:03.205
- Yeah. You think you're quitting for good.
You'd have those moments of, like, "I'm

00:46:03.296 --> 00:46:07.256
doing this too much. I need
to move on in life. I'm

00:46:07.276 --> 00:46:10.776
gonna put it down and walk away, and
hopefully not come back." And there were

00:46:11.396 --> 00:46:14.916
times where you did come
back. When I finally did

00:46:15.276 --> 00:46:18.816
leave EverQuest, it was
actually extremely easy,

00:46:18.856 --> 00:46:26.326
because I was psychologically done
with the game at the time. It was

00:46:27.456 --> 00:46:31.396
not shortly, but not too
long after a new expansion

00:46:31.496 --> 00:46:34.856
had come out. At the time,
it was Shadows of Luclin.

00:46:34.896 --> 00:46:38.876
Which didn't speak to me like
the expansions before. Like, the

00:46:38.936 --> 00:46:42.386
one before that was called Scars
of Velious, which was an amazing

00:46:42.436 --> 00:46:49.496
expansion. And I had gotten the job
at Blizzard, and I guess I'm just an

00:46:49.536 --> 00:46:57.216
obsessive person. So all the time and
energy that I had put into EverQuest, the

00:46:57.275 --> 00:47:01.116
second, you know, the second
my first minute started at

00:47:01.156 --> 00:47:03.716
Blizzard, that was my new obsession.

00:47:04.316 --> 00:47:10.016
- So speaking of which, you have to tell
the epic origin story of how you got

00:47:10.156 --> 00:47:17.016
the job at Blizzard. As we said, you were
this legendary gamer, and now legendary

00:47:17.116 --> 00:47:24.056
troll, on EverQuest. Username, Tigole. You
gave a lot of edgy feedback to the devs,

00:47:25.016 --> 00:47:28.956
Telling them in now famous...
There's several rants.

00:47:28.976 --> 00:47:32.936
There's a famous one where
you tell many of them to do a

00:47:32.976 --> 00:47:36.876
bunch of things, including to pull
their heads out of their asses.

00:47:36.956 --> 00:47:40.636
You were loved and respected
because you gave a lot of specific

00:47:40.736 --> 00:47:44.396
ways that the game could be improved. And that's
an important thing to say. You weren't just

00:47:44.436 --> 00:47:48.096
talking shit. You actually really
loved and cared for the game, and

00:47:48.156 --> 00:47:55.036
you gave them, in the language of
the time advice on how to improve,

00:47:55.136 --> 00:47:59.036
Their game. And it's funny,

00:47:59.056 --> 00:48:02.516
because, like, you look back to
those messages, it's inspiring to

00:48:02.556 --> 00:48:06.536
me. It should be informative and inspiring
to a lot of people, because you're

00:48:06.636 --> 00:48:09.886
really, legit, full-time talking shit. And

00:48:09.956 --> 00:48:13.536
now, and you always have
been, like, one of the

00:48:13.636 --> 00:48:17.026
kindest, most loved human
beings in the entire gaming

00:48:17.096 --> 00:48:21.896
industry. Anyway, how did that lead
to you getting a job at Blizzard?

00:48:21.996 --> 00:48:25.926
- So when the first guild leader left,
Legacy of Steel, the founder... He,

00:48:25.956 --> 00:48:29.636
he was a guy named... His online
name was Dread. That was his

00:48:29.836 --> 00:48:36.956
name. He left, and our guild was kind
of in this listless spin for a while.

00:48:37.016 --> 00:48:40.296
And eventually, somebody
stepped up and took

00:48:40.316 --> 00:48:45.744
his position as guild leader, and
that person's name was Ariel-

00:48:45.804 --> 00:48:50.654
... who was this blonde
wood elf warrior, Female,

00:48:51.584 --> 00:48:55.384
who always refused to wear a helmet
because they thought their character was

00:48:55.444 --> 00:48:59.264
so pretty, wanted to show their
face all the time. So Ariel

00:48:59.444 --> 00:49:03.184
was a great guild leader
for us, and made me

00:49:04.044 --> 00:49:10.904
like an assistant guild leader, raid
leader, officer type in the guild. And over

00:49:10.964 --> 00:49:18.204
time, Ariel got busier and busier, and,
you know, would send me messages like,

00:49:18.224 --> 00:49:21.904
"Hey, I'm not gonna be online, you
know, tomorrow," or, "I'm not gonna be

00:49:21.964 --> 00:49:25.514
online tonight. Can you run the
raid? Can you run the raid?"

00:49:25.564 --> 00:49:32.654
And running the raids was very natural for
me. And it was my first experience with

00:49:32.844 --> 00:49:38.254
leadership in my life, of like how do
you motivate people? Like, what does

00:49:38.284 --> 00:49:42.244
motivation look like? What does
discipline look like? How do

00:49:42.264 --> 00:49:46.004
you inspire people? When
do you force people versus

00:49:46.224 --> 00:49:50.144
encourage them, you know?
So it was a learning

00:49:50.204 --> 00:49:54.104
experience for me on the fly, and
I had the safety net of the real

00:49:54.204 --> 00:49:57.864
guild leader would log in eventually.

00:49:57.904 --> 00:50:01.594
- I should mention, I'm just now reading

00:50:01.604 --> 00:50:03.824
about, doing a bunch of
research on Justinian

00:50:04.664 --> 00:50:08.514
of the Roman Empire, and he rose
from being a peasant to being

00:50:08.764 --> 00:50:12.474
emperor, so I see a lot of parallels
in your life journey, from

00:50:12.504 --> 00:50:14.624
peasant to emperor, but
go ahead, I'm sorry.

00:50:14.664 --> 00:50:17.404
- At least EverQuest guild
leader, that's- that's as much-

00:50:17.414 --> 00:50:17.534
- Uber guild leader-

00:50:17.534 --> 00:50:18.134
- ... as I could say.

00:50:18.244 --> 00:50:18.454
- Uber guild leader.

00:50:18.454 --> 00:50:21.584
- Uber guild leader. Best guild
on the Nameless server.

00:50:22.304 --> 00:50:28.964
So as time went on, Ariel became
busier and busier, and then one

00:50:29.024 --> 00:50:32.884
day, they contacted me and we
were having this like whisper

00:50:32.964 --> 00:50:36.924
back and forth, and they said, "You- you're
gonna have to take over the guild. I'm just too

00:50:36.964 --> 00:50:43.134
busy." And then it came out
later ... Well, let me back up a

00:50:43.184 --> 00:50:51.064
second. I started fooling around ... Like
around this time Half-Life 1 had come out,

00:50:51.074 --> 00:50:55.024
and with both Duke Nukem
and Half-Life 1, one of the

00:50:55.084 --> 00:50:59.004
incredible things that those companies
did back in the day was when they

00:50:59.024 --> 00:51:02.124
shipped the game, they
shipped the editor on the CD.

00:51:02.134 --> 00:51:05.874
And if you were curious enough, you
could like fire up that editor and

00:51:06.004 --> 00:51:09.604
fool around with it.
So I made a Duke Nukem

00:51:09.664 --> 00:51:12.904
level, and you'd send
it off to like those UK

00:51:13.064 --> 00:51:16.884
programming magazines, and you know,
you'd get excited because your

00:51:16.964 --> 00:51:19.404
level was in, you know, some random

00:51:19.664 --> 00:51:24.804
magazine. And then I started
making like Half-Life levels. And

00:51:26.284 --> 00:51:30.644
Ariel had stepped down as guild
leader. I had become guild leader.

00:51:30.724 --> 00:51:34.534
And then at one point,
Ariel contacts me and

00:51:34.604 --> 00:51:38.504
says, "Hey, you know, you were
talking about those Half-Life

00:51:38.604 --> 00:51:42.564
levels you made. I want to
see those." I'm like, "Oh,

00:51:42.604 --> 00:51:46.584
that's cool." Like, "I didn't know you played
Half-Life." Like, "Yeah, maybe we can get

00:51:46.644 --> 00:51:50.484
a server up and I can play
them." And Ariel tells me,

00:51:50.504 --> 00:51:54.444
"No, mail them to this
address in Irvine." And-

00:51:54.484 --> 00:51:58.144
because I— again, to rewind
in the time machine for a

00:51:58.204 --> 00:52:03.314
second, to send something like a Half-Life
level over the internet would have-

00:52:03.314 --> 00:52:05.504
... taken like 12 hours.

00:52:05.544 --> 00:52:10.004
So you actually like burned it onto
a CD and stuck it in the mail.

00:52:10.044 --> 00:52:15.284
So I put my Half-Life levels,
I sent them to Ariel, and

00:52:16.544 --> 00:52:24.874
he says, "You know, my name's Rob. I'm
a designer at Blizzard Entertainment."

00:52:24.874 --> 00:52:28.664
"Um, we're— I— I hear you're in
Pasadena 'cause you mentioned

00:52:28.724 --> 00:52:32.544
it." You know, I would write about,
you know, the Rose Parade and

00:52:33.444 --> 00:52:37.204
all these things on our website. You
know, I kind of ... It was blogging

00:52:37.244 --> 00:52:41.184
before blogging existed, so he knew I lived
in Pasadena, and he's like, "Irvine's

00:52:41.224 --> 00:52:45.164
only an hour away. Why
don't you come down, see

00:52:45.204 --> 00:52:48.904
Blizzard, and you can also meet..." and he

00:52:49.004 --> 00:52:52.814
names like four people in the
guild. And I'm like, "They all

00:52:52.864 --> 00:52:55.574
work at Blizzard too?" He's
like, "Yeah, we're all

00:52:55.584 --> 00:52:59.413
Blizzard." And it was so weird because

00:52:59.484 --> 00:53:03.204
during that era, I didn't have
a lot of money. It was not

00:53:03.264 --> 00:53:07.224
like ... Kind of nowadays it feels
like everybody plays every game,

00:53:07.284 --> 00:53:11.264
but you had to be selective. So
like I never bought StarCraft

00:53:11.304 --> 00:53:14.744
or Diablo or Warcraft.
I was much more of the

00:53:14.824 --> 00:53:17.754
Half-Life, Quake, Quake
III guy around that

00:53:17.804 --> 00:53:21.684
time, and I'd never played
a Blizzard game, and I just

00:53:21.744 --> 00:53:25.244
got invited to like go to
Blizzard Entertainment.

00:53:25.344 --> 00:53:29.174
- Was Blizzard already legendary,
you know, with the Warcraft and

00:53:29.204 --> 00:53:32.324
StarCraft? Is it... Is there...
Is it... Was it building this

00:53:33.424 --> 00:53:37.584
like great legend of this game
company that seemingly doesn't miss?

00:53:37.684 --> 00:53:41.064
- It was very much on its way to

00:53:41.144 --> 00:53:46.094
enshrining itself as being one of the
legendary game... Like, it was beloved—

00:53:46.344 --> 00:53:50.064
... by gamers, but there were
still ignorant people like me who

00:53:50.104 --> 00:53:53.884
hadn't played, you know, War II or Diablo

00:53:54.004 --> 00:53:56.864
II or StarCraft, which
was shocking to people.

00:53:56.884 --> 00:53:59.484
- So you weren't like
freaking out, freaking out?

00:53:59.604 --> 00:54:03.504
- No, I— I was freaking out in a
different sense. I'm like, "Am

00:54:03.584 --> 00:54:07.134
I gonna get mugged when I-" Like,
"Who are ... Is this a scam?"

00:54:07.144 --> 00:54:10.204
Because you didn't meet
people off the internet.

00:54:10.324 --> 00:54:18.664
So I drove down there. Um, I ended
up... There was— there was Rob Pardo—

00:54:18.964 --> 00:54:22.924
... who at that time was the
lead designer on Warcraft

00:54:23.024 --> 00:54:26.794
III, and he was Ariel.
You know, so okay, it

00:54:26.864 --> 00:54:30.284
wasn't a woman after all.
It wasn't this blonde wood

00:54:30.364 --> 00:54:34.454
elf. You know, I don't know
what you expect at that point.

00:54:34.464 --> 00:54:38.444
It was Rob Pardo. To this
day, a great friend of

00:54:38.544 --> 00:54:41.934
mine named Scott Mercer
was the enchanter in our

00:54:42.024 --> 00:54:48.044
EverQuest guild, a guy named Dalomin. There
was a guy named Roman Kenny who was like

00:54:48.104 --> 00:54:55.876
this—Totally psychotic wizard who played
in our guild. And I had lunch with these

00:54:55.936 --> 00:54:59.516
guys, you know, we just went out
to Irvine to like a restaurant.

00:55:00.436 --> 00:55:04.096
And, you know, forgive
me for the misuse of

00:55:04.396 --> 00:55:08.256
the phrase, but it was like
my coming out moment. And

00:55:08.316 --> 00:55:12.296
we talked about games having that
stigma and being embarrassed about

00:55:12.356 --> 00:55:15.956
who you are and what you like. Like
I, up until that point, I would

00:55:16.096 --> 00:55:19.586
never tell- Mm-hmm ...
friends, family, like, "I love

00:55:19.716 --> 00:55:23.256
games. I'm playing this game EverQuest.
It's so cool, we just killed a

00:55:23.316 --> 00:55:27.966
dragon." And so you were hiding
this part of your identity.

00:55:28.876 --> 00:55:32.196
And I'm out to lunch with
these guys in Irvine,

00:55:33.356 --> 00:55:40.996
and we're talking about dragons and swords
and, you know, raid tactics and talking

00:55:41.136 --> 00:55:44.876
shit on all the people
in the guild. And I,

00:55:45.076 --> 00:55:48.486
literally had this moment where
I felt like myself for the first

00:55:48.516 --> 00:55:54.116
time. I just felt like so
comfortable, and that was an

00:55:54.156 --> 00:55:58.026
eye-opening moment. And
after that, after that

00:55:58.076 --> 00:56:01.856
lunch happened, he invited
me for a couple more lunches

00:56:01.976 --> 00:56:05.906
down, you know, just... Uh, I just saw
it as like, "Oh, now, I'm..." You know,

00:56:05.956 --> 00:56:09.836
I made friends with these people
online. Now, we know each other in real

00:56:09.896 --> 00:56:13.856
life, and they happen to work for
this game company. And at another one

00:56:13.896 --> 00:56:21.776
of the lunches, they invite this troll
warrior to have lunch with us, whose

00:56:21.836 --> 00:56:25.016
name in the game was
Barfa, the Troll Warrior.

00:56:25.036 --> 00:56:29.016
Mm-hmm. And Barfa, Barfa wasn't
somebody who played with

00:56:29.076 --> 00:56:32.976
us all the time, but kind of
like Ariel got into the guild

00:56:33.016 --> 00:56:36.746
kind of on the side. You know, it was
one of those like inside invites of

00:56:36.796 --> 00:56:40.746
like, "Who's Barfa?" "I don't know,
but Barfa is in the guild now." And

00:56:40.776 --> 00:56:44.596
there was at the time, it was a new
dungeon called The Hole, and we had never

00:56:44.636 --> 00:56:48.256
done it before. And we jumped down in
this hole, and we're doing this whole

00:56:48.376 --> 00:56:52.206
dungeon, and everything goes wrong,
as it's prone to do in EverQuest.

00:56:52.236 --> 00:56:56.126
And the whole guild escapes
except for Barfa, whose

00:56:56.216 --> 00:57:00.136
troll character's so big, he
can't jump out of the exit.

00:57:00.176 --> 00:57:04.116
Mm-hmm. And I had this
potion that was like

00:57:04.216 --> 00:57:07.916
a really expensive potion
that was a teleport potion

00:57:07.956 --> 00:57:11.856
that, you know, no one but someone
in the uber guild could afford

00:57:11.896 --> 00:57:15.716
at the time. And I hand
the potion to Barfa, and I

00:57:15.756 --> 00:57:19.736
say, "Here, use this. It'll teleport
you out." And I'm a rogue, I can

00:57:19.796 --> 00:57:27.396
just stealth and get out of the dungeon
on my own. So I saved Barfa, not really

00:57:27.416 --> 00:57:30.956
knowing who Barfa was, and I
did it with a very expensive

00:57:30.996 --> 00:57:38.496
potion. Mm-hmm. Having lunch, Rob introduced
me, "This is Allen Adham. He plays

00:57:38.536 --> 00:57:42.506
Barfa." Mm-hmm. I'm like, "Oh,
Barfa!" And we, you know, he has a...

00:57:42.506 --> 00:57:45.776
"You saved me in The Hole that
time." Well, it turns out Allen

00:57:45.976 --> 00:57:49.536
was the founder of
Blizzard, and he was the

00:57:49.596 --> 00:57:52.956
head... He was sort of the head of
everything at that time. It was

00:57:53.056 --> 00:58:00.536
Allen, Mike Morhaime, and Frank Pearce.
And what I didn't realize what these

00:58:00.576 --> 00:58:04.136
lunches were, like I just loved them
because I felt like I was myself. I felt

00:58:04.436 --> 00:58:08.196
true happiness being surrounded
by these, you know, people who

00:58:08.256 --> 00:58:14.976
were talkin' about video games and I felt
comfortable around. And one day, Rob

00:58:15.036 --> 00:58:18.976
logs into EverQuest. He wasn't playing
much at the time, and he said, "I want

00:58:19.056 --> 00:58:22.826
you tomorrow to check the
Blizzard job site." Mm-hmm.

00:58:23.996 --> 00:58:26.936
I'm like, "Okay, like, I'll
check the Blizzard job

00:58:26.996 --> 00:58:34.706
site." And they had announced World of
Warcraft, and posted on the job site- Mm-hmm

00:58:35.076 --> 00:58:38.816
... was the job for an
associate quest designer.

00:58:38.826 --> 00:58:42.766
And the funniest part of
it was, I forget if it was

00:58:42.856 --> 00:58:46.696
a requirement or a plus in the
job description, but they're

00:58:46.776 --> 00:58:49.796
like, "We really want somebody
with a creative writing

00:58:49.876 --> 00:58:53.716
degree." Hmm. And I'm like, "You guys set

00:58:53.776 --> 00:58:57.716
this up for me." Like, they
were just looking... And it was

00:58:57.776 --> 00:59:01.116
that hindsight moment of like,
actually, these guys were just

00:59:01.196 --> 00:59:05.135
interviewing me- Yeah ... for six
months. And they were actually friends,

00:59:05.176 --> 00:59:11.336
and they were really cool about it too. And
I just had the fuck it moment like that,

00:59:12.236 --> 00:59:13.596
that job opened up.

00:59:14.476 --> 00:59:18.236
I applied with all my heart, you
know? Like, it, they had a bunch

00:59:18.316 --> 00:59:24.816
of quest writing on it. And then I
went through like a pretty hardcore

00:59:24.876 --> 00:59:28.696
six-month recruiting
process because they never

00:59:28.736 --> 00:59:32.446
hired designers from out of
the company. Traditionally,

00:59:32.476 --> 00:59:36.376
designers were promoted from
within Blizzard. Either they would

00:59:36.436 --> 00:59:40.396
like transfer out of other
disciplines, or they would come

00:59:40.476 --> 00:59:47.376
from quality assurance, tech support. So
hiring somebody off the street was kind of

00:59:47.436 --> 00:59:51.196
a big deal for them, and
they really put me through a

00:59:51.336 --> 00:59:58.696
grilling. Um, I met with... It was the first
time I met Chris Metzen- Mm-hmm ... who

00:59:59.076 --> 01:00:04.756
is maybe the most inspirational,
creative person on

01:00:04.796 --> 01:00:08.396
the planet. And you
instantly... They paired

01:00:08.436 --> 01:00:11.896
me... They did this interview pairing.
There were these two guys. It was Kevin

01:00:11.956 --> 01:00:15.876
Jordan- Mm-hmm ... who was one of
the original designers on WoW.

01:00:15.976 --> 01:00:19.896
Really, he doesn't get enough credit for
his contributions. He was one of the

01:00:19.956 --> 01:00:22.916
earliest class designers, PvP designers.

01:00:23.916 --> 01:00:27.736
But he's a really quiet guy.
Mm-hmm. And they paired

01:00:27.816 --> 01:00:31.756
him with Chris, and Chris just owns

01:00:31.796 --> 01:00:35.536
the room, you know? Mm-hmm. Chris,
you could just sit and listen to

01:00:35.616 --> 01:00:42.836
him. He's so creative. He's so
passionate. And the way he articulates

01:00:42.936 --> 01:00:46.826
things, like you just instantly
become a fan of Chris when you're

01:00:46.896 --> 01:00:50.396
around Chris. And Chris, Kevin, and I go

01:00:50.476 --> 01:00:54.096
to lunch at, at this Italian
place that was across the street

01:00:54.136 --> 01:01:00.420
from Blizzard, and I remember...Chris
made a stop to buy cigarettes

01:01:01.600 --> 01:01:03.740
, you know, on the way to the interview.

01:01:03.780 --> 01:01:08.600
And then every other word out of Chris's
mouth was like, "Fuck," and, "Shit."

01:01:08.610 --> 01:01:12.360
And I'd come from this whole, like,
corporate culture from my dad's

01:01:12.420 --> 01:01:18.820
recruiting business, where I'd never imagined
somebody would curse in an interview,

01:01:18.860 --> 01:01:25.170
or stop to buy smokes. And again, it
was like, "I'm around my people."

01:01:25.200 --> 01:01:30.940
Like, I never smoked, but just, you know,
being around people who didn't care about-

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:34.040
... what the corporate norms were was so

01:01:34.140 --> 01:01:38.060
inspiring. And then my
last interview was with,

01:01:38.160 --> 01:01:42.080
uh, Alan and Rob, and a
great programmer named

01:01:42.100 --> 01:01:48.950
Bob Fitch. Like, I think he's one of the
first five developers at Blizzard. Uh,

01:01:49.700 --> 01:01:55.030
and they took me to an ARCO station that
had a Jack in the Box. You know, how, like-

01:01:55.100 --> 01:02:00.740
... sometimes they'll combo? It was like
ARCO Jack in the Box. And that was my

01:02:00.780 --> 01:02:03.900
final interview at Blizzard,
was at the ARCO Jack in the

01:02:03.940 --> 01:02:07.440
Box. And I remember thinking to myself,

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:13.420
"These guys just brought me to a Jack
in the Box that's in an ARCO station.

01:02:14.560 --> 01:02:17.990
I need to work here." Like, this
is... "These are my people."

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:21.920
"This is where I belong." Like,
it was the greatest thing ever.

01:02:21.940 --> 01:02:27.720
And so, yeah, that's my
crazy journey to Blizzard.

01:02:28.420 --> 01:02:33.180
- Uh, started at the bottom and end up at
the top in a Jack in the Box. Can you

01:02:34.080 --> 01:02:37.120
speak to... 'Cause you mentioned
some of the low points in the... in

01:02:37.180 --> 01:02:41.020
depression. Through that journey,
how did you find your way

01:02:41.120 --> 01:02:45.030
out? So, can you just...
A lot of people are

01:02:45.660 --> 01:02:49.500
sitting in those low points right
now listening to this. What kind of

01:02:49.540 --> 01:02:54.940
wisdom can you draw about finding
your way out, finding your people?

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:58.880
- There were a lot of really
low points. Uh, I'll give you

01:02:58.920 --> 01:03:06.260
the weirdest one. I started drinking
a lot, and alcohol was something

01:03:06.700 --> 01:03:10.660
that I really wrestled with
until my early 30s. And one

01:03:10.700 --> 01:03:14.260
of the things I'm most proud of
today is sobriety and having

01:03:14.360 --> 01:03:18.260
been sober for such a long time now. And

01:03:18.320 --> 01:03:22.890
I remember I was- I was just ha- I would
like buy a bottle of Old Grand-Dad and-

01:03:22.940 --> 01:03:25.960
... like, drink the whole thing
by myself, and then watch the

01:03:26.060 --> 01:03:29.660
Oscars. I remember I was ... Of
all things, I'm watching the

01:03:29.780 --> 01:03:35.110
Oscars, which is just such a
fake, bullshit environment.

01:03:35.140 --> 01:03:37.840
But I was like... You know,
I was really drunk and

01:03:38.960 --> 01:03:42.720
all those people seemed so
together and successful and

01:03:42.780 --> 01:03:46.629
polished, and I just...
It made me... It was

01:03:46.660 --> 01:03:53.880
that contrast that made me feel like
such a failure. And it all seems so

01:03:54.080 --> 01:04:02.140
stupid and unimportant to me now. Um, I
became... You know, I got in that constant

01:04:02.280 --> 01:04:09.100
struggle of try not to drink, but drink
to make it feel better. I was lucky,

01:04:09.200 --> 01:04:13.060
My parents were very
supportive of me, even

01:04:13.100 --> 01:04:19.740
in my 20s, even after I, you know, quote-unquote
left the house. I went into therapy

01:04:20.500 --> 01:04:24.390
and that was very helpful. You know,

01:04:24.440 --> 01:04:28.320
know, extremely helpful. And
one thing I learned is that you

01:04:28.380 --> 01:04:32.070
have to find the right
therapist for you. It's not

01:04:32.160 --> 01:04:35.840
just checking a checkbox of, "I
went to therapy." It's about

01:04:36.600 --> 01:04:39.720
finding somebody who sort of

01:04:40.860 --> 01:04:47.210
helps you get out of whatever rut you're
in, in a way that's healthy for you. And,

01:04:47.300 --> 01:04:53.700
um, I tried antidepressants,
but I hated... I just hated

01:04:53.710 --> 01:04:57.340
taking pills and feeling
like something was in

01:04:57.400 --> 01:05:04.380
me, and making me feel different. I never
responded to it. And then the hardest

01:05:04.390 --> 01:05:08.240
thing, you know, which
I've never mentioned to

01:05:08.320 --> 01:05:16.219
anyone, and is hard for me to talk about,
but eventually I went through ECT,

01:05:16.280 --> 01:05:22.720
which is electroconvulsive
therapy, shock therapy. And that

01:05:23.500 --> 01:05:31.260
broke me out. And I would never endorse that
as a miracle. That was... I was at such

01:05:31.340 --> 01:05:37.580
a low point that people were very
worried about me and my wellbeing-

01:05:37.700 --> 01:05:40.620
... and what was gonna happen,
and that was sort of an

01:05:40.700 --> 01:05:47.620
extreme pull-the-rip-cord, like
there's-nothing-else-to-lose moment.

01:05:47.640 --> 01:05:56.900
And I think that was the difference
maker. That, and starting at Blizzard.

01:05:56.920 --> 01:06:00.520
- To find... I mean, there is a- there
is a deep loneliness there when

01:06:00.540 --> 01:06:04.290
before you met those guys at lunch, you're

01:06:04.400 --> 01:06:07.950
alone, like in a really
deep fundamental way.

01:06:08.220 --> 01:06:11.580
Like, in the way you weren't in New York
with the writing- with the writer's group,

01:06:11.620 --> 01:06:16.540
right? And so that must've been an
incredible experience just to see the guild.

01:06:16.620 --> 01:06:23.640
- Yes. It was everything I nee- I... As such
an introvert, you- you think that there

01:06:23.680 --> 01:06:27.200
are extroverts and introverts,
and introverts don't need

01:06:27.220 --> 01:06:33.440
anybody, but weirdly, I think
introverts almost need people more.

01:06:33.500 --> 01:06:37.960
And we don't always know how to engage-

01:06:38.300 --> 01:06:42.220
... in the right, healthy ways, and
how to find people and how to connect

01:06:42.300 --> 01:06:48.210
with people. And it was- it was great. Um,

01:06:48.840 --> 01:06:52.720
one... The thing that had attracted
me to creative writing was

01:06:52.780 --> 01:06:56.140
the solitude of it, and the
fact that you didn't have to

01:06:56.180 --> 01:07:00.140
collaborate, and you could just write
what you wanted to write and it

01:07:00.180 --> 01:07:04.040
was all you. You would succeed
on your own or you would fail

01:07:04.100 --> 01:07:08.048
on your own, and that was very
attractive to me. And the thought

01:07:08.088 --> 01:07:14.508
of creative collaboration was actually
off-putting. I'd spent all four years

01:07:14.548 --> 01:07:20.848
of undergrad interning at Universal
Pictures, 'cause I thought I wanted to be in

01:07:20.908 --> 01:07:24.788
film, and it was such
an unhealthy creative

01:07:24.848 --> 01:07:28.108
collaboration in the film
industry. It's a very,

01:07:30.128 --> 01:07:33.688
you know, I look up unhealthily
to the film industry

01:07:34.128 --> 01:07:36.268
and admire it and, you know, grew up

01:07:37.308 --> 01:07:44.168
with all these legends who had come from
there. But it's like a caste system.

01:07:44.248 --> 01:07:49.297
And I was on the bottom of the caste
system as an intern, and I was

01:07:49.388 --> 01:07:53.088
seeing how the other people who were low

01:07:53.248 --> 01:07:57.178
caste in the film industry were
treated, and it was just horrible,

01:07:57.228 --> 01:08:05.068
you know. But games was different. Games
was very flat. It didn't matter if you

01:08:05.128 --> 01:08:09.978
were the CEO or the boss, like,
the way Mike and Allen carried

01:08:10.008 --> 01:08:17.148
themselves with, you know, me, who was an
associate game designer, you felt like an

01:08:17.228 --> 01:08:24.528
equal. And I think it... Not just the
comradery, but the part that shouldn't be

01:08:24.628 --> 01:08:32.288
overlooked is the work itself and the work
ethic. That's what really pulled me out.

01:08:33.148 --> 01:08:36.148
- Hard work on a thing you love.

01:08:36.228 --> 01:08:37.248
- Yeah.

01:08:38.308 --> 01:08:41.968
- I have to, if you may allow
me, read the prophetic one of

01:08:42.028 --> 01:08:45.778
us, quote, "one of us" post
you made on April 18th,

01:08:45.888 --> 01:08:49.488
2002. Because in some
deep sense, you, I think,

01:08:49.548 --> 01:08:53.528
remained one of us. The...
I apologize to bring

01:08:53.588 --> 01:08:57.708
up Justinian the emperor, but
remained a kind of peasant

01:08:59.368 --> 01:09:02.848
gamer, a true gamer, who
happens to be also be

01:09:02.888 --> 01:09:06.788
designing the games. And so
this post kind of speaks

01:09:06.828 --> 01:09:10.568
to that. It's fascinating to read,
because that was at the very

01:09:10.608 --> 01:09:14.268
beginning, right? You didn't know
anything. You didn't know the

01:09:14.308 --> 01:09:18.148
games you would end up creating.
Title of the post, "If you want

01:09:18.188 --> 01:09:21.668
something done right."
He wrote, "This week, I

01:09:21.728 --> 01:09:24.828
accepted a position as associate
game designer with Blizzard

01:09:24.888 --> 01:09:28.818
Entertainment. Specifically, I will
be designing quests for World of

01:09:28.888 --> 01:09:32.558
Warcraft, Blizzard's MMORPG
based on the popular

01:09:32.668 --> 01:09:36.608
Warcraft series. In addition to my
duties as quest designer, I will

01:09:36.668 --> 01:09:40.528
also be expected to contribute
to helping design the end

01:09:40.608 --> 01:09:43.968
game content for World of Warcraft.
The reason I'm sharing this

01:09:43.988 --> 01:09:47.808
information, besides the fact
that I have a masochistic love of

01:09:47.848 --> 01:09:51.768
reading rants and flames about myself,
is because I know that the fans of

01:09:51.828 --> 01:09:55.728
this site are hardcore
MMORPG players. The readers

01:09:55.788 --> 01:09:59.768
of the site have also come to
know my personal opinions on

01:09:59.788 --> 01:10:03.688
what constitutes a fun gaming
experience versus what feels like

01:10:03.768 --> 01:10:07.548
a complete waste of time or poorly
designed encounter." Wow, you're

01:10:07.568 --> 01:10:10.588
very eloquent in this post and
without too much shit talking.

01:10:11.588 --> 01:10:15.148
"You've all read my opinions
on such things as tedious key

01:10:15.268 --> 01:10:18.808
camps, obvious time sinks,
devoid of any story or linear

01:10:18.848 --> 01:10:22.658
narrative, quests which reward
the lucky over the skilled and

01:10:22.828 --> 01:10:26.768
quest rewards which are out of sync
with the amount of time and effort

01:10:26.788 --> 01:10:30.488
required to complete them. I
hope that my association with

01:10:30.568 --> 01:10:37.348
World of Warcraft will serve to
comfort MMORPG fans that one of us

01:10:38.368 --> 01:10:42.188
is on the other side of the fence,
looking out for the interest of the

01:10:42.228 --> 01:10:45.978
player." And you go on to describe some
of the high hopes you have for World of

01:10:46.048 --> 01:10:49.948
Warcraft, which is really fun to
read because you don't realize-

01:10:50.028 --> 01:10:50.188
- Now-

01:10:50.198 --> 01:10:53.688
- ... it's gonna be, like, one of
the greatest games of all time

01:10:54.028 --> 01:10:57.868
played by millions of human beings, just
where those millions of human beings are

01:10:57.888 --> 01:11:01.738
playing for hundreds of hours, thousands
of hours. It's crazy. It's funny that

01:11:01.768 --> 01:11:05.568
this... one of us is writing
at the dawn of a new

01:11:05.668 --> 01:11:09.568
age. The final paragraph is, "So with all

01:11:09.708 --> 01:11:13.388
that is going on with me,
you'll have to excuse any

01:11:13.448 --> 01:11:17.348
lapse in updates to the site
here. I will try my hardest

01:11:17.628 --> 01:11:20.688
to give you slack or something
to read while you should be

01:11:20.808 --> 01:11:24.357
working. But in the meantime,
there's a whole world of

01:11:24.448 --> 01:11:30.728
NPCs. They need to learn
the words kaksagur and

01:11:30.788 --> 01:11:34.428
mo'fucker, in quotes,
and the like. Although

01:11:34.488 --> 01:11:36.448
something tells me I'm
already in trouble with the

01:11:36.468 --> 01:11:40.388
boss." One of us, Jeff,
one of us. That was

01:11:40.448 --> 01:11:44.208
a beautiful, beautiful post. Did you
in fact get in trouble with the boss?

01:11:44.308 --> 01:11:47.408
- No. No. My boss was Allen.

01:11:47.428 --> 01:11:51.308
And Allen was very understanding
and he... they kind of knew

01:11:51.348 --> 01:11:52.878
what they were getting into-

01:11:52.928 --> 01:11:56.808
when they hired me. And that
post actually embarrasses me

01:11:56.868 --> 01:12:01.468
when I hear it now.
There's so much ego in it-

01:12:01.478 --> 01:12:08.648
... and I think that's...
it's got that 20 year old-

01:12:08.688 --> 01:12:11.418
... you know, "I don't
know what I don't know."

01:12:11.428 --> 01:12:15.068
- "I know exactly how to fix this
video game and all video games and-"

01:12:15.088 --> 01:12:18.368
But there's brilliance behind that.
There's a passion behind that.

01:12:18.388 --> 01:12:22.358
Like, we're... when you're a gamer
and you really put in the hours

01:12:22.408 --> 01:12:25.508
in a game like EverQuest, you
understand what makes for a compelling

01:12:25.548 --> 01:12:29.508
experience. You don't, at that time,
understand how much hard work is required

01:12:29.548 --> 01:12:33.468
to create that experience and
how much uncertainty there is,

01:12:33.488 --> 01:12:36.718
how difficult it is, how many
trade-offs there are. How your

01:12:37.048 --> 01:12:40.928
designs, when they actually are brought to
the world and are experienced by thousands of

01:12:40.968 --> 01:12:44.728
people, millions of people,
they are different from

01:12:44.788 --> 01:12:48.708
the division you had for it. So all
those elements you don't know, but you

01:12:48.748 --> 01:12:51.448
have to have that ego in
the beginning, right?

01:12:51.468 --> 01:12:55.448
Do you even have the guts to try? Do you
have the guts to put in all that work? So

01:12:55.488 --> 01:12:59.078
what were the... what was it
like? What were the vibes of

01:12:59.648 --> 01:13:03.428
early Blizzard like? They've...
at this point, Warcraft

01:13:03.568 --> 01:13:07.108
I and II, Warcraft III is in production.

01:13:07.228 --> 01:13:11.068
StarCraft. These are legendary
games. I don't... I spent probably

01:13:11.128 --> 01:13:14.968
over 1,000 hours in
these games combined. I

01:13:14.988 --> 01:13:18.918
played Warcraft I, II, III.
I played StarCraft I and II.

01:13:18.928 --> 01:13:22.388
I played WoW, of course.
Diablo I, II, III,

01:13:22.458 --> 01:13:27.300
IV. Play Diablo II with "Stay a while
and listen," with Deckard Cain.

01:13:27.640 --> 01:13:29.400
- Stay a while and listen.

01:13:29.680 --> 01:13:33.540
- I mean, some of these characters, some of
these experiences just, they'll stay with me

01:13:33.580 --> 01:13:37.460
forever. Anyway, so big thank you to those

01:13:37.500 --> 01:13:41.450
early Blizzard folks.
What was it like? What

01:13:41.460 --> 01:13:45.320
was the team like? What were the developers
like? What were the vibes like in those

01:13:45.400 --> 01:13:45.960
early days?

01:13:46.480 --> 01:13:53.800
- It was the dream. When I showed up at
Blizzard on my first day, the office

01:13:53.920 --> 01:13:57.880
was on the University of
California Irvine campus

01:13:57.920 --> 01:14:01.869
at the time. They have this research
and development park where,

01:14:01.920 --> 01:14:05.260
if you're like a tech company,
you can get office space there,

01:14:06.120 --> 01:14:09.600
and Blizzard took up...
When I joined, it was

01:14:09.640 --> 01:14:13.480
three-fourths of the building was Blizzard,
and there were... There was like a

01:14:13.500 --> 01:14:17.400
building right next to it that had
like Cisco and, you know, it was like

01:14:17.480 --> 01:14:22.620
all kind of techy places. And it was
so funny because you drive up and like

01:14:23.620 --> 01:14:27.200
everything was very serious and
corporate, and then outside of the

01:14:27.280 --> 01:14:30.760
Blizzard offices, everybody
is wearing black T-shirts and

01:14:30.900 --> 01:14:34.700
shorts and throwing frisbees
and playing Hacky Sack

01:14:34.760 --> 01:14:37.910
and on scooters and skateboards,
and you're like, "Okay, that's

01:14:37.940 --> 01:14:41.780
where, that's where Blizzard
is." So it was that

01:14:41.820 --> 01:14:45.550
environment. I remember walking in
the door and thinking like, "It

01:14:45.760 --> 01:14:48.420
feels like I'm walking into a dorm room-"

01:14:48.430 --> 01:14:51.980
"... 'cause it was just posters
on the wall." And there were

01:14:52.080 --> 01:14:56.020
actually, like people would have
futons because they'd be sleeping

01:14:56.040 --> 01:15:03.420
because we would work so much back then.
But the vibe was... It was very small. Like

01:15:03.460 --> 01:15:07.420
Blizzard, the day I joined in May of 2002,

01:15:07.460 --> 01:15:11.320
was fewer than 200 people, and
that included... There was a

01:15:11.380 --> 01:15:14.980
whole group up in San Mateo
called Blizzard North.

01:15:15.620 --> 01:15:19.380
So Blizzard South, the Irvine
group, was responsible

01:15:19.480 --> 01:15:23.380
for StarCraft and Warcraft, and there

01:15:23.400 --> 01:15:27.310
were two development teams at
Blizzard. It was called Team

01:15:27.420 --> 01:15:31.489
One and Team Two at Blizzard South. Um,

01:15:32.700 --> 01:15:36.600
Team One was revered.
These are the RTS guys.

01:15:36.620 --> 01:15:40.460
They made, you know,
StarCraft, Warcraft II, and

01:15:40.520 --> 01:15:45.600
they were, at that time, they're
working on Warcraft III.

01:15:45.680 --> 01:15:49.660
Team Two was kind of the
red-headed stepchild.

01:15:49.680 --> 01:15:53.640
Like apparently, before I joined,
they had tried to spin off

01:15:53.680 --> 01:15:57.600
a second team multiple times
and failed, and then they

01:15:57.680 --> 01:16:01.620
finally decided they were
gonna make World of Warcraft.

01:16:01.700 --> 01:16:05.580
There was a game called Nomad. I don't

01:16:05.620 --> 01:16:09.380
know what that game was
exactly, but that was what Team

01:16:09.460 --> 01:16:13.350
Two was working on at
first. That got scrapped,

01:16:13.400 --> 01:16:21.049
and Allen stor- steered the team towards
World of Warcraft. And there's amazing

01:16:21.080 --> 01:16:27.940
designer named Eric Dodds. He'd go on later
in his career to be the game director of

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:31.860
Hearthstone. Him and Ben,
Ben Brode basically were the

01:16:31.920 --> 01:16:36.780
core designers behind that.
But Eric and Kevin Jordan

01:16:37.580 --> 01:16:42.260
were these two key designers
working on World of Warcraft

01:16:43.060 --> 01:16:49.660
for Team Two, and then you had this tech
group that was headed up by John Cash.

01:16:49.740 --> 01:16:53.860
And John Cash, the first
day that I showed up

01:16:54.680 --> 01:16:58.060
to work on Team Two, they said,
"You have to go get your login

01:16:58.760 --> 01:17:03.740
from John Cash." I'm like,
"John... The John Cash from id?"

01:17:03.800 --> 01:17:07.460
And, you, you know, John Cash
has a skin. You could be

01:17:07.520 --> 01:17:15.060
John Cash in Quake III. So, and then he
saw me, and he, he was a huge EverQuest

01:17:15.120 --> 01:17:18.760
player, and you're like... He was
like, "You're the guy who runs

01:17:18.820 --> 01:17:22.400
Legacy of Steel." I'm like, "You're
John Cash." We had, we had that

01:17:22.540 --> 01:17:25.600
moment where we kind of
fanboyed out on each other.

01:17:26.620 --> 01:17:30.560
And it was just... The
vibe was so cool there.

01:17:30.580 --> 01:17:36.200
Like, there were very few producers.
So a game team, there are

01:17:37.120 --> 01:17:41.859
five core disciplines that
make a video game. You've got

01:17:43.080 --> 01:17:46.780
engineers or programmers who
are writing the code. You've

01:17:46.840 --> 01:17:50.720
got the art team that's making
all the visuals for the

01:17:50.760 --> 01:17:54.420
game, and that spans everything
from like 3D modeling, characters,

01:17:54.460 --> 01:17:58.420
environments, to also
animation, tech art, you

01:17:58.480 --> 01:18:02.120
know, making it all work. You've got game

01:18:02.220 --> 01:18:05.760
design, which some companies
don't have design. The

01:18:05.840 --> 01:18:09.740
artists and the engineers
do it. Valve famously has

01:18:09.780 --> 01:18:12.300
very few designers because
everybody there is a

01:18:12.380 --> 01:18:16.300
designer. But in companies where design is

01:18:16.360 --> 01:18:20.300
a discipline, which it very
much is so at Blizzard, game

01:18:20.360 --> 01:18:24.300
designers are sort of the
creating the game experience

01:18:24.460 --> 01:18:28.260
people, you know, setting up all
the systems and content in a

01:18:28.320 --> 01:18:32.500
way that gets the player to
navigate through the game.

01:18:33.020 --> 01:18:36.820
- So that's part of a story, part of this quest
design, part of it is like how you move

01:18:36.900 --> 01:18:38.600
through the game world.

01:18:38.720 --> 01:18:41.980
- Yes. So game designers, there's a

01:18:42.040 --> 01:18:45.870
spectrum, like same with
art, same with engineering,

01:18:45.940 --> 01:18:49.710
of roles within game design. Some are

01:18:49.740 --> 01:18:53.480
more heavy on the systems side. So like
any game that you've played where loot

01:18:53.680 --> 01:18:58.220
drops- Diablo IV, World
of Warcraft, you know,

01:18:58.380 --> 01:19:02.220
Escape from Tarkov,
whatever. If there's loot

01:19:02.420 --> 01:19:08.880
dropping, a designer has planned out very
carefully what drops where and at what

01:19:08.980 --> 01:19:12.920
percentages. That would be
like a systems designer.

01:19:12.960 --> 01:19:15.760
A content designer is
somebody who's gonna make

01:19:16.420 --> 01:19:20.340
quests or write storylines,
or there might even

01:19:20.380 --> 01:19:27.762
be a narrative designer, which is even more
focused on a story. But designers, you

01:19:27.812 --> 01:19:31.672
know, run the gamut, and then you've
got these jack-of-all-trade designers

01:19:31.712 --> 01:19:33.092
that can do it all.

01:19:33.192 --> 01:19:40.692
Um, so that's the design group. There's
production, which is project management, and

01:19:40.812 --> 01:19:44.792
production is different at every game
company you go to. So if you talk to someone

01:19:44.872 --> 01:19:48.752
from EA or Blizzard, production might be

01:19:48.852 --> 01:19:52.192
very different. They might be the
boss. They might actually be a

01:19:52.212 --> 01:19:59.592
designer or they might be more of a project
manager. And then one of my favorite

01:19:59.632 --> 01:20:03.892
disciplines on a game team that's
often overlooked is sound and-

01:20:03.902 --> 01:20:10.672
... you know, audio, which is comprised
of the sound designers and composers.

01:20:10.712 --> 01:20:14.692
And there are two things, I think there
are two things that no one realizes

01:20:14.732 --> 01:20:20.692
how much they bring to a game until
they're missing, and that's audio and

01:20:20.792 --> 01:20:24.322
lighting. Because most of the time, we're

01:20:24.352 --> 01:20:28.232
playing without these things,
and it just feels a little

01:20:28.412 --> 01:20:32.322
off and wrong. And when
you have a great lighting

01:20:32.412 --> 01:20:36.292
artist or you have a
great composer or sound

01:20:36.312 --> 01:20:40.212
designer, like, it... the experience.
You're just tapping into these

01:20:40.292 --> 01:20:46.662
senses that you wouldn't otherwise. But
that's who comprises the game team.

01:20:46.772 --> 01:20:50.912
- Is the lighting, you
know, all the different

01:20:52.012 --> 01:20:55.312
kinds of graphics, would
that be under the art team?

01:20:56.132 --> 01:21:00.012
- Yeah. Lighting, you're gonna have
lighting under the art team, but

01:21:00.032 --> 01:21:03.172
they're gonna be best friends
with the graphics programmer.

01:21:03.212 --> 01:21:06.772
And, you know, like I mentioned
with design, there's this wide

01:21:06.892 --> 01:21:10.792
spectrum on the engineering team,
you have some guys who are like,

01:21:10.872 --> 01:21:14.732
Architectural geniuses who are coming up

01:21:14.772 --> 01:21:18.252
with, you know, the server client
model or the networking or

01:21:18.312 --> 01:21:21.972
whatever. Others are more,
like, gameplay focus. On

01:21:22.032 --> 01:21:25.432
Overwatch, we had an audio
programmer just doing nothing but

01:21:25.492 --> 01:21:32.452
audio hooks for the audio team. And
on every game team, you're gonna

01:21:32.492 --> 01:21:34.672
have graphics programmers who

01:21:35.931 --> 01:21:39.872
will work with people like the
lighting artists or the environmental

01:21:39.992 --> 01:21:43.781
artists, character artists on shaders, and

01:21:44.592 --> 01:21:48.552
basically any way to make the game.
They'll always ask, "What's your vision?

01:21:48.592 --> 01:21:52.441
What are you trying to get it to look like?"
They'll want an illustration of what should the

01:21:52.512 --> 01:21:56.152
world look like, and they'll be the
ones who say, "I know how to write

01:21:56.212 --> 01:21:59.872
code to- that will let
you do that." So you

01:21:59.932 --> 01:22:03.842
partner a great graphics programmer
with a great lighting artist, and

01:22:03.892 --> 01:22:07.672
that's... That's actually
the creative tension behind

01:22:07.712 --> 01:22:11.672
games and what makes game
teams so unique, is if we were

01:22:11.712 --> 01:22:18.912
to line them up on some crazy spectrum,
on one end, you're gonna have the artists

01:22:20.312 --> 01:22:24.812
who... They're creative,
dare I say emotional-

01:22:24.912 --> 01:22:28.882
... you know, they are
artistes on that end. And on

01:22:28.912 --> 01:22:31.892
the other end, you have the
most logical, brilliant

01:22:31.952 --> 01:22:38.712
programmers whose minds just work very
differently from the most creative art-

01:22:38.721 --> 01:22:42.712
Like artists could be sitting, you have a meeting
with them and they'll just sit illustrating.

01:22:42.752 --> 01:22:46.452
If there's any piece of paper,
they're drawing on it. Um,

01:22:48.032 --> 01:22:51.392
and programmers, you know, they're just so

01:22:51.832 --> 01:22:54.812
brilliant and organized in their
thinking and everything is so

01:22:55.132 --> 01:22:58.612
logical. And then in the middle
are people like the sound

01:22:58.672 --> 01:23:02.652
designers, the- the game designers,
and the producers. They're kind

01:23:02.692 --> 01:23:06.632
of a little bit in- in
all those fields, but

01:23:06.672 --> 01:23:10.292
it's the brilliance of
taking people who are so

01:23:10.332 --> 01:23:14.122
vastly different in their
interests and talents, but

01:23:14.212 --> 01:23:18.072
aiming them at that shared
goal or that shared vision of

01:23:18.112 --> 01:23:21.092
the game that, like, really
makes something special.

01:23:21.792 --> 01:23:25.262
- And there, I mean, you showed me the size of
the team for World of Warcraft, but you've

01:23:25.372 --> 01:23:29.332
also are well known for working on
quite small teams to create these

01:23:29.372 --> 01:23:33.952
incredibly huge games. What is
the- the power of a small team

01:23:35.172 --> 01:23:38.252
in this kind of context where
a lot... there's that creative

01:23:38.372 --> 01:23:44.772
tension? Is it- is it because
a small team avoids maybe the

01:23:44.892 --> 01:23:48.572
compartmentalization, like
the modular where the

01:23:48.612 --> 01:23:52.392
artists now have their own
wing building where they never

01:23:52.432 --> 01:23:54.652
talk to the engineers, that kind of thing?

01:23:54.972 --> 01:23:58.812
- Absolutely. I mean, you hit the nail
on the head. The bigger the team, the

01:23:58.872 --> 01:24:01.952
more you become a cog in the machine.

01:24:02.032 --> 01:24:07.552
And on a small team, the way I like to
describe it is you get to have a loud voice.

01:24:07.632 --> 01:24:10.602
If we're a small team, let's
say we're gonna make a game

01:24:11.512 --> 01:24:15.312
and it's at sort of the
incubation period of a game

01:24:15.792 --> 01:24:19.362
and there's only 10 of us, all
10 of us are in the room for

01:24:19.612 --> 01:24:23.472
every decision. You know, I'm
not a server networking guy, but

01:24:23.532 --> 01:24:27.272
I'm in the room for that
discussion. I'm not an illustrator,

01:24:27.312 --> 01:24:31.032
but I'm gonna sit in the room when
we decide what the art style looks

01:24:31.072 --> 01:24:36.572
like. As soon as the team starts to
grow, we become compartmentalized.

01:24:36.612 --> 01:24:38.572
It's exactly like you said. And

01:24:39.992 --> 01:24:43.872
there's a weird thing that happens
that's just kind of a human nature

01:24:43.982 --> 01:24:48.472
thing. The less you interact
with somebody, the more you

01:24:49.352 --> 01:24:54.092
sort of become alienated from them
and vilify their point of view.

01:24:54.162 --> 01:24:58.482
You tend to look at what they
do and say with skepticism

01:24:58.552 --> 01:25:02.412
rather than trust and belief in them. And

01:25:02.612 --> 01:25:06.572
I find on smaller teams where
we all know each other's names,

01:25:06.652 --> 01:25:10.202
I know what everybody's working on
every day, they know what I'm working

01:25:10.272 --> 01:25:17.922
on, everybody can talk to each
other, there's none of that

01:25:18.492 --> 01:25:22.512
stereotyping of a discipline.

01:25:22.532 --> 01:25:26.492
On big unhealthy teams, you start to
say things like, "Well, the artists

01:25:26.572 --> 01:25:27.992
just don't get it."

01:25:28.002 --> 01:25:31.982
"They don't understand what we're trying to
make." And when you back up and you think about

01:25:32.012 --> 01:25:35.768
the statement that you just said,
it's like... Such an asshole

01:25:35.848 --> 01:25:39.188
statement. Like, really, all
the artists don't get it? Like,

01:25:39.248 --> 01:25:42.788
that's... A, that's not
true. B, that's sort of

01:25:42.828 --> 01:25:48.488
demeaning to them. Like, they signed up
for the... This is their life's work, too.

01:25:48.508 --> 01:25:51.128
This game is gonna be
as much theirs as it is

01:25:51.488 --> 01:25:55.948
mine. So who am I to say
a statement like that?

01:25:55.988 --> 01:25:59.448
- Yeah. It's harmful to a
discipline to think that you

01:25:59.808 --> 01:26:02.027
understand the world.
Most silly other folks

01:26:02.848 --> 01:26:06.828
don't, and you have nothing to
learn from them, really, and,

01:26:06.948 --> 01:26:12.508
They're deluded in some in some
kind of way. That's so powerful.

01:26:12.628 --> 01:26:19.148
- Fast-forwarding a little bit, when we
formed Team Four and... Which went on to

01:26:20.448 --> 01:26:24.428
make Titan and ultimately fail,
and then that got rebooted

01:26:24.438 --> 01:26:31.168
as the Overwatch team, the idea
that I tried to get through to the

01:26:31.248 --> 01:26:39.048
team was to make an assumption. And really,
like, Blizzard is one of the top game

01:26:39.128 --> 01:26:43.108
developers in the world, and
we were very fortunate when

01:26:43.248 --> 01:26:47.208
I was there, and I imagine
it's this way today, that we

01:26:47.248 --> 01:26:51.158
could recruit whatever talent
we wanted. It... The best of

01:26:51.188 --> 01:26:53.768
the best wanted to come work at Blizzard.

01:26:55.148 --> 01:26:58.978
And if you sort of go through
the paces of that and

01:26:59.008 --> 01:27:02.568
say, "Okay, when we recruit
somebody..." Let's say

01:27:02.688 --> 01:27:10.448
we're recruiting an artist to make
props. Boxes, chairs, whatever. That is

01:27:10.748 --> 01:27:14.728
the best prop artist in the industry.
That's who's gonna show up on our

01:27:14.768 --> 01:27:21.688
doorstep, so when they show up here, we
should treat them like the best prop

01:27:21.788 --> 01:27:25.368
artist in the industry
instead of starting from a

01:27:25.428 --> 01:27:33.018
place of doubt and cynicism. So, when that
person speaks up and says, "I think..."

01:27:33.088 --> 01:27:37.048
Like, with Overwatch, for example, "I think
we should do this." You know, "We should

01:27:37.088 --> 01:27:40.728
do X instead of Y." Instead of saying,

01:27:41.588 --> 01:27:44.968
"Well, I'm a believer in
Y, why are you against my

01:27:45.048 --> 01:27:48.797
idea X?" You should take a
moment, have a deep breath, and

01:27:48.948 --> 01:27:52.268
say, "Man, the best prop
artist in the industry

01:27:52.368 --> 01:27:57.388
is suggesting something.
Why don't I listen to it?"

01:27:57.468 --> 01:27:59.788
- I actually do it for
myself, like this kinda

01:28:01.508 --> 01:28:05.348
thought framework or thought
experiment. Whenever I'm

01:28:05.388 --> 01:28:09.168
talking to a new person, especially if
I feel, myself, a little bit tinge of

01:28:10.028 --> 01:28:13.588
that feeling. Usually, it happens with,
like, a really young person, like an

01:28:13.648 --> 01:28:17.348
undergraduate student or someone like
this. I pretend that they are the smartest

01:28:17.408 --> 01:28:22.548
person in the world in my head, and then
not... Like, it puts me in the mode of,

01:28:22.588 --> 01:28:25.098
like, assuming I have

01:28:25.988 --> 01:28:29.868
a lot to learn from them, and it
helps. You actually, like, really

01:28:29.908 --> 01:28:36.708
listen. I literally think they're the
smartest, wisest human on Earth. It helps me.

01:28:36.808 --> 01:28:40.628
- I had that, like, I think...
You know, I'm no expert.

01:28:40.708 --> 01:28:44.548
I'm a game designer, so, like, as
much psychology as I know is how to

01:28:44.628 --> 01:28:48.168
manipulate people into
having fun, hopefully.

01:28:48.208 --> 01:28:54.228
Like, I don't know, I don't have an
important job. But psychologically speaking-

01:28:54.308 --> 01:28:55.028
- That's fun.

01:28:55.488 --> 01:29:02.648
- ... I... One thing I think a lot about is
ego, and I think about insecurity. And

01:29:03.008 --> 01:29:06.868
insecurity, we all have. Like,
all of us as human beings

01:29:06.948 --> 01:29:11.018
have insecurity. It just manifests
itself in different ways.

01:29:11.068 --> 01:29:14.808
And as we kind of go through our
life journey, the insecurity also

01:29:15.128 --> 01:29:18.968
changes. So, like, some people, for
example, use their insecurity to

01:29:19.108 --> 01:29:23.028
rip other people apart. Some people
destroy themselves through their

01:29:23.208 --> 01:29:26.468
own insecurity. Some people
destroy everybody with their

01:29:26.508 --> 01:29:34.908
insecurity. But I had that moment as a young
lead, when I first was made a lead on,

01:29:34.928 --> 01:29:39.388
like, World of Warcraft, where I felt
it was very important to be right

01:29:40.468 --> 01:29:46.848
and to, you know, be shepherding the
correct idea. And I actually got pulled

01:29:46.888 --> 01:29:53.288
aside. Like, Pardo and I had a meeting
with a couple people who weren't game

01:29:53.308 --> 01:29:55.068
designers, and

01:29:56.208 --> 01:29:59.668
it's always tricky as a game designer
because constantly everybody is throwing

01:29:59.748 --> 01:30:03.408
ideas out in- on a game team.
Like, there's no shortage of ideas

01:30:03.488 --> 01:30:07.208
ever. And we were in some
meeting about something,

01:30:07.268 --> 01:30:10.998
and these people kind of
threw out these ideas. And I

01:30:11.048 --> 01:30:17.928
wasn't mean to them, but I very kind of
systematically, like an insecure, you know,

01:30:18.068 --> 01:30:21.588
ego-driven new lead would do, I kind

01:30:21.628 --> 01:30:25.528
of, "Let me tell you why that's
wrong, and let me tell you what we're

01:30:25.548 --> 01:30:29.057
gonna do instead." And after the

01:30:29.128 --> 01:30:32.808
meeting, you know, Pardo pulled me
aside, and he said, "You're a very smart

01:30:32.848 --> 01:30:39.488
designer, but you shouldn't do what you
just did to those people. You should always

01:30:39.548 --> 01:30:47.378
listen to what people have to say and try
to make their ideas work." And I just...

01:30:47.488 --> 01:30:51.348
Over and over, I was like, "Okay,
anytime an idea comes my way, let's try

01:30:51.408 --> 01:30:58.148
to make it work." And it went from this
kind of thing that I didn't believe into

01:30:59.128 --> 01:31:02.468
to actually, like, a core part of who I am

01:31:02.728 --> 01:31:10.088
today as a leader, as a game designer,
as a game director. And some of the best

01:31:10.768 --> 01:31:16.118
ideas have come from developing
other peoples' ideas-

01:31:16.788 --> 01:31:20.748
... where your first reaction is like,
"No, that's wrong," and then just kind of

01:31:20.888 --> 01:31:26.818
sticking with it and going, "But how could
we make it work?" And the most gratifying

01:31:26.988 --> 01:31:31.408
part when it succeeds is
they get all the credit,

01:31:33.268 --> 01:31:37.254
and you've sort of
elevated this person who

01:31:37.364 --> 01:31:41.224
Whose idea wouldn't have
been championed, whose idea

01:31:41.424 --> 01:31:48.934
by the insecure, egotistical lead of, you
know, early 2000s would have just said

01:31:49.124 --> 01:31:53.024
no. Now their idea is the
thing everybody in World

01:31:53.044 --> 01:31:59.104
of Warcraft or Overwatch is just
loving, and they get all the credit.

01:31:59.184 --> 01:32:03.664
- I should give context to the listener who
doesn't know about the great Jeffrey Kaplan,

01:32:04.624 --> 01:32:08.144
That you're one of the most humble

01:32:08.624 --> 01:32:12.584
and always give credit to the team
for everything and anything. And so

01:32:12.644 --> 01:32:16.104
everything we talk about
today, I know you're probably

01:32:16.144 --> 01:32:19.864
resisting constantly giving
credit to the team on everything.

01:32:19.964 --> 01:32:27.884
So you're the famous, "Hi, I'm Jeff from
the Overwatch team," right? So just as

01:32:27.924 --> 01:32:31.724
a small aside, thank you
for your humility through

01:32:32.264 --> 01:32:35.824
through your career, and thank you
for always celebrating the team. But

01:32:37.144 --> 01:32:40.554
let's talk about WoW.
Let's talk about World of

01:32:40.604 --> 01:32:44.024
Warcraft. Tell me what the early
days of developing WoW was

01:32:44.064 --> 01:32:47.804
like. Maybe we should
talk about what World of

01:32:47.864 --> 01:32:51.064
Warcraft, WoW is, going
to Perplexity here.

01:32:52.264 --> 01:32:56.184
World of Warcraft is a massively
multiplayer online RPG where you create a

01:32:56.204 --> 01:32:59.974
character, level it up doing quests
and dungeons, and progress your

01:33:00.084 --> 01:33:03.244
gear and power in an open
fantasy world called

01:33:03.364 --> 01:33:07.334
Azeroth. At a basic level, you
move, use abilities from your

01:33:07.424 --> 01:33:11.024
action bar, follow quests,
and gradually learn a combat

01:33:11.104 --> 01:33:14.924
rotation that fits your class.
And there's all kinds of

01:33:14.964 --> 01:33:18.864
characters and roles and classes. You
pick a race, appearance, starting zone,

01:33:18.924 --> 01:33:22.884
small racial bonuses. In a class,
how you fight, what your role is in

01:33:22.904 --> 01:33:29.084
groups. Can you continue, fill in some
of the gaps, what is World of Warcraft?

01:33:29.144 --> 01:33:32.804
- World of Warcraft, first of
all, more than anything,

01:33:32.924 --> 01:33:36.904
is a world. Like, it's a
world that you can live in

01:33:36.944 --> 01:33:39.794
with real other people, and
everybody's kinda living out their

01:33:39.824 --> 01:33:45.074
fantasy. Chris Metzen, who was the creative
director on World of Warcraft, and

01:33:46.004 --> 01:33:49.984
really, like, Allen Adham, who's one
of the founders of Blizzard, calls

01:33:50.044 --> 01:33:53.024
Chris "the heart and soul of Blizzard."

01:33:53.084 --> 01:33:58.694
And it's almost like when you're
making a Blizzard game, you're making

01:33:58.724 --> 01:34:02.424
Chris' imagination at some point.

01:34:02.504 --> 01:34:06.464
And Chris famously said,
"The lead character of World

01:34:06.504 --> 01:34:09.364
of Warcraft is the world."
And I always believed

01:34:09.444 --> 01:34:13.324
that. So you're trying to create
this place that's exciting and

01:34:13.384 --> 01:34:21.224
dangerous, but comfortable, but uncomfortable
and gorgeous, and, you know, it

01:34:21.284 --> 01:34:23.794
should feel massive, and it really is.

01:34:23.804 --> 01:34:29.184
It, it's, you know, can take a half an hour
to get from one end of the world to the

01:34:29.264 --> 01:34:36.384
other. But it's this world you're living
in. The world is divided into two warring

01:34:36.544 --> 01:34:40.524
factions. There's the Horde
and the Alliance, and that

01:34:40.584 --> 01:34:47.444
was a very important, very controversial
decision that was made by Allen

01:34:47.544 --> 01:34:51.064
Adham, was the champion of
the Horde and Alliance.

01:34:51.104 --> 01:34:54.424
- And that in the early days, there
was a really strong division.

01:34:54.584 --> 01:34:55.664
- Strong division.

01:34:55.684 --> 01:35:02.724
- Like... You pick a side and then you hang
around with only people of your kind.

01:35:02.804 --> 01:35:06.524
- Yeah, and you get it tattooed in real life
on you. Like, the amount of people who

01:35:06.584 --> 01:35:09.624
walk up to me and show
me their Horde tattoo.

01:35:10.244 --> 01:35:11.144
- That's awesome.

01:35:11.154 --> 01:35:14.584
- Like, it's epic. It's like
it's become who they are.

01:35:14.604 --> 01:35:17.994
Like, if you were to say, like,
"Hey, Lex, come play World of

01:35:18.064 --> 01:35:21.424
Warcraft with me. We're Alliance
on Tichondrius," you'd be like-

01:35:21.444 --> 01:35:21.593
- Right

01:35:21.944 --> 01:35:22.414
- ... "Dude-"

01:35:22.444 --> 01:35:23.074
- Lose my number.

01:35:23.074 --> 01:35:23.554
- "... Alliance?"

01:35:23.554 --> 01:35:23.564
- Yeah.

01:35:23.584 --> 01:35:27.294
- Like, "Okay, I don't think
we can be friends anymore."

01:35:27.324 --> 01:35:31.274
But the Horde-Alliance decision
was really controversial because

01:35:31.364 --> 01:35:33.373
in EverQuest, it was mixed race.

01:35:34.304 --> 01:35:38.144
They had all the races kind of
like WoW did, but they could

01:35:38.204 --> 01:35:44.024
all group with each other. And Pardo
and I came from EverQuest, where we

01:35:44.064 --> 01:35:47.864
felt like this was a horrible
decision Allen was making.

01:35:48.664 --> 01:35:52.604
And we argued, Allen, Rob, Bob,

01:35:52.624 --> 01:35:56.584
Fitch, and I would have lunch every
single day, and we would just talk about

01:35:56.663 --> 01:36:00.484
WoW and the core design of WoW. Rob
wasn't even on WoW at that time.

01:36:00.494 --> 01:36:04.384
He was finishing Warcraft III. And we

01:36:04.404 --> 01:36:08.104
would fight over the Horde-Alliance
split, if it was a good idea or not. And

01:36:08.204 --> 01:36:11.624
Allen had... He came from
more of the Dark Age of

01:36:11.684 --> 01:36:15.304
Camelot community, which
was another massive

01:36:15.664 --> 01:36:19.844
multiplayer online game
that was more PvP based.

01:36:19.884 --> 01:36:23.764
And he said the magic of that game
was they had three factions, and

01:36:24.304 --> 01:36:27.864
he liked the fact that you were
instantly on a team. You weren't a

01:36:27.944 --> 01:36:31.664
loner in the world. And whether
you liked it or not, you

01:36:31.724 --> 01:36:35.304
had people on your side.
And Rob and I just

01:36:35.384 --> 01:36:42.344
argued and argued against it, and then
sometime before beta, Allen retired.

01:36:42.384 --> 01:36:45.414
He went on to run a hedge
fund, of all things.

01:36:45.414 --> 01:36:51.424
Like, got super into poker, got super
into finance, left, and retires,

01:36:51.444 --> 01:36:58.504
like, I think it was nine months to a
year before WoW shipped, which is kinda

01:36:58.604 --> 01:37:06.424
nuts. And Rob takes over as lead designer
in Allen's stead, and to Rob's credit,

01:37:06.444 --> 01:37:10.144
the first thing he did was
go... Speaking to what we were

01:37:10.244 --> 01:37:12.764
speaking about earlier,
he said, "Allen's a smart

01:37:12.884 --> 01:37:16.894
guy. The fact that he was
fighting so hard for-"

01:37:16.894 --> 01:37:20.464
"... Horde Alliance, we gotta do it." And,

01:37:20.584 --> 01:37:24.044
uh, Rob and I sort of
changed our point of view

01:37:24.104 --> 01:37:29.233
and got on board with Horde
Alliance and went all in. And

01:37:30.344 --> 01:37:36.944
so, you know, the early days of WoW was...
It was a great team. It was a mix of

01:37:37.004 --> 01:37:40.974
these veterans that we all looked up to.

01:37:41.044 --> 01:37:45.014
You know, we had Mark Kern running
the team. Shane Dabiri was, you

01:37:45.064 --> 01:37:48.894
know, legendary Blizzard developer.

01:37:48.914 --> 01:37:52.434
Bill Petris was the art director,
and then we had Metzen, who was

01:37:53.094 --> 01:37:59.664
sort of like... Metzen was the cool big
brother we all, you know, aspired to be.

01:37:59.664 --> 01:38:05.254
Uh, I'm older than Metzen, but I looked
up to him like a big brother. And

01:38:06.154 --> 01:38:09.784
then there were a lot of us
who had never done it before,

01:38:09.874 --> 01:38:13.204
or they had also pulled a
lot of people from other

01:38:13.254 --> 01:38:16.894
teams and other game types. Like, for

01:38:16.914 --> 01:38:21.834
example, the guys building the dungeons,
they hired out of the Quake community.

01:38:21.844 --> 01:38:25.554
And because they didn't have
any hardcore MMO designer

01:38:26.254 --> 01:38:29.594
on the staff at that time,
it was, you know, Kevin

01:38:30.094 --> 01:38:33.604
and Eric and Alan were sort of the only

01:38:33.674 --> 01:38:37.703
designers, they started
building Quake dungeons-

01:38:37.703 --> 01:38:41.654
... as, like, Quake levels as
the dungeons. At one point, WoW

01:38:41.694 --> 01:38:45.744
was even made in QERadiant,
which was the Quake engine.

01:38:45.754 --> 01:38:49.654
And then they later, you know,
retooled to where they were using

01:38:49.694 --> 01:38:56.144
a proprietary engine. So we were like
this hodgepodge, like the Bad News Bears-

01:38:56.154 --> 01:38:59.934
... is how I would describe
the WoW team, of this mix of

01:39:00.714 --> 01:39:04.534
veterans and then people
like me. Like, I'm

01:39:04.614 --> 01:39:09.374
just some fucking idiot, you know-
... who played a lot of EverQuest.

01:39:09.414 --> 01:39:10.544
And I end up at Blizzard.

01:39:10.554 --> 01:39:11.794
- Designing quests.

01:39:11.854 --> 01:39:18.034
- Yeah. Like, okay, we're gonna
design World of Warcraft now. And

01:39:19.954 --> 01:39:23.534
I've said this later with
hindsight, I think a

01:39:23.634 --> 01:39:30.834
huge part of WoW's success with, especially
with the early WoW team, Team Two in its

01:39:30.914 --> 01:39:34.824
earliest formation, was that we didn't

01:39:34.874 --> 01:39:38.384
know what we were doing.
You kind of... Like, it's

01:39:38.494 --> 01:39:42.414
that... Titan was the
example for me. Titan was

01:39:42.454 --> 01:39:46.734
the attempt at making an MMO after
World of Warcraft at Blizzard.

01:39:46.774 --> 01:39:49.954
And we failed horribly, and we
had the best of the best on that

01:39:50.014 --> 01:39:53.794
team. And it's because
everybody was too much of an

01:39:53.873 --> 01:39:59.114
expert on how to make a
groundbreaking phenomenon MMO.

01:40:01.354 --> 01:40:04.834
World of Warcraft was a
bunch of people, like a very

01:40:04.974 --> 01:40:11.784
successful, sure of itself company
who had made StarCraft, Diablo

01:40:11.814 --> 01:40:18.834
Warcraft, with a bunch of yayhoos basically-
... who was like, "Yeah, we can compete

01:40:18.914 --> 01:40:25.854
with Sony Online." At the time, they
were making EverQuest II. Like, if we go

01:40:25.874 --> 01:40:28.934
back in the time machine,
EverQuest II had been

01:40:28.974 --> 01:40:32.874
announced. And EverQuest
fans, we were just

01:40:33.014 --> 01:40:36.694
drooling for EverQuest II. It
wasn't, "Oh, cool, World of

01:40:36.734 --> 01:40:43.474
Warcraft." It was EQ2 was gonna take, you
know, the chalice and run with it. And

01:40:43.534 --> 01:40:46.654
then, of all things, they
announced Star Wars Galaxies,

01:40:47.634 --> 01:40:51.554
and they had a brilliant designer on that,
a guy named Raph Koster, who had come

01:40:51.594 --> 01:40:54.994
from that Ultima Online,
and he's just a really

01:40:55.074 --> 01:40:59.034
smart game designer. If you ever watch
one of his lectures, like, he lectured a

01:40:59.074 --> 01:41:06.254
lot at GDC, and, you know, we're like,
"Oh my God, they're making EverQuest

01:41:06.954 --> 01:41:14.074
II and Star Wars Galaxies, and they have
the Star Wars intellectual property."

01:41:14.214 --> 01:41:15.334
"We're fucked."

01:41:15.354 --> 01:41:21.314
Like, "How are we gonna compete?" And
everybody had seen the success of EQ,

01:41:21.494 --> 01:41:25.394
EverQuest, and everybody
was gonna make an MMO,

01:41:25.454 --> 01:41:28.394
and it was just a question
of who was gonna win.

01:41:28.434 --> 01:41:31.834
- So you're feeling this immense
pressure. You have this small team

01:41:33.134 --> 01:41:40.554
of just this hodgepodge of this unlikely
team that kind of looks fast forwarding

01:41:40.594 --> 01:41:44.114
to Overwatch, the heroes in Overwatch, but

01:41:44.834 --> 01:41:52.384
working extremely hard. Now, you told me
about crazy, crazy work hours, and not

01:41:52.414 --> 01:41:56.084
because you were forced to,
but because you wanted to,

01:41:56.094 --> 01:41:59.154
because your heart was in it,
because you're like, "This is

01:41:59.214 --> 01:42:01.454
everything." Like, you loved it.

01:42:01.594 --> 01:42:08.434
- Yeah. The- the games industry has a
terrible reputation for insane amounts of

01:42:08.534 --> 01:42:12.414
overtime. It's just called
crunch. Like do you crunch

01:42:12.474 --> 01:42:19.294
or not? These days, crunch is not
allowed, not permitted, heavily frowned

01:42:19.334 --> 01:42:26.174
upon. If we were to work overtime,
somebody'd write an article about

01:42:26.214 --> 01:42:34.524
it next week and say how horrible we are
for working overtime. Um, back then,

01:42:35.794 --> 01:42:39.614
we worked insane, and I
mean insane hours. The

01:42:39.694 --> 01:42:42.794
longest shift I ever
worked straight was 30

01:42:42.894 --> 01:42:48.954
hours. That's when we were gold mastering
Warcraft III. This was in my... I think,

01:42:48.994 --> 01:42:56.784
um, War III shipped on July 3rd,
2002 so this would have been,

01:42:56.814 --> 01:43:00.634
like, late June, early July. Probably late

01:43:00.794 --> 01:43:04.583
June. And I had nothing
to do with War III.

01:43:04.614 --> 01:43:08.054
I should just say that. Like,
in the credits, I'm additional-

01:43:08.094 --> 01:43:12.384
additional help or additional
testing or something like that. Um,

01:43:13.254 --> 01:43:19.154
when I showed up in May of 2002, it was all
hands on deck World of Warcraft for E3.

01:43:19.174 --> 01:43:22.994
We got through E3, and then
all hands on deck, the

01:43:23.034 --> 01:43:26.114
whole company, get War III out the door.

01:43:26.174 --> 01:43:27.334
- For shipping Warcraft III.

01:43:27.374 --> 01:43:30.974
- For shipping Warcraft III,
and because I had not been

01:43:31.014 --> 01:43:34.504
involved with the game at
all, and I was a brand new

01:43:34.534 --> 01:43:38.314
wet-behind-the-ears game designer,
they're like, "You're just gonna help

01:43:38.334 --> 01:43:44.454
test whatever we tell you to test."
So we're trying to gold master,

01:43:45.394 --> 01:43:51.622
and there's a crash that happens rarely.
If you run one of the cinematics, like you

01:43:51.662 --> 01:43:54.521
have to be watching the
cinematic after one of the

01:43:54.562 --> 01:43:58.382
levels, and then there was
a crash that happened. And

01:43:58.462 --> 01:44:02.242
so a programmer put in
some logging to catch

01:44:02.322 --> 01:44:06.102
it, and then they needed
somebody to just over and

01:44:06.182 --> 01:44:09.702
over again, "I need the crash
to happen so I can fix the

01:44:09.722 --> 01:44:15.732
bug." And I sat there for 30 hours and
just watched the cinematic for 30 hours-

01:44:15.732 --> 01:44:19.562
... straight. And it was the funniest
thing, like it was almost surreal

01:44:20.642 --> 01:44:24.582
watching everybody leave at
the... which was a trickle

01:44:24.662 --> 01:44:26.752
out. Like, everybody kind
of trickles out, like, at-

01:44:26.752 --> 01:44:30.582
... different hours, you know? The
family guys go much earlier than the

01:44:30.642 --> 01:44:34.402
single guys. And then watching everybody

01:44:34.522 --> 01:44:38.242
show up again in... the next morning,
and they're all, like, dressed

01:44:38.282 --> 01:44:42.302
different, and they look all refreshed.
And I'm just like in the same position.

01:44:42.382 --> 01:44:45.112
You know, like eyes are beet red.

01:44:45.142 --> 01:44:47.772
- To the soundtrack of
the cinematic and yeah.

01:44:47.772 --> 01:44:53.582
- Yeah. But we crunched World of Warcraft,
we crunched... The date slipped, so

01:44:53.642 --> 01:44:56.602
you do this thing. I remember
Mark Kern standing the team up

01:44:57.742 --> 01:45:01.702
and saying, "We're gonna
crunch early so we don't

01:45:01.722 --> 01:45:04.762
have to crunch later in the project."

01:45:04.822 --> 01:45:08.702
And I really believe he wasn't
manipulating us. Like, I

01:45:08.962 --> 01:45:13.822
really genuinely believe
that he believed in that.

01:45:13.842 --> 01:45:17.062
But with games anything
can happen, and they're

01:45:17.122 --> 01:45:20.342
just... We slip uncontrollably all the

01:45:20.402 --> 01:45:27.242
time. And we slipped, and it sort of
created just this death march endless death

01:45:27.322 --> 01:45:31.102
march that... Like to this

01:45:31.122 --> 01:45:35.002
day, members of the WoW team will
remember, like, Newport Rib.

01:45:35.062 --> 01:45:38.942
If I say that, they'll have,
like, twitches because, like,

01:45:39.002 --> 01:45:43.502
they would cater the dinner. They'd bring
it in at, like, 6:00 or 7:00 at night.

01:45:43.542 --> 01:45:47.421
And they'd... Everybody
was eating Newport Rib

01:45:47.482 --> 01:45:51.442
or Panda Express. It was like
the worst diet ever. I actually

01:45:51.462 --> 01:45:56.742
like Newport Rib, no shade- ... on them.
But you can only eat so much of it.

01:45:56.762 --> 01:46:01.532
And the carpets are stained and, like,
dudes are falling asleep on the couches.

01:46:01.582 --> 01:46:05.562
And it was an unhealthy
work environment. It

01:46:05.602 --> 01:46:10.862
gets pinned on... 'Cause at a lot
of places it is executive driven.

01:46:10.872 --> 01:46:14.672
And it is mandated from the
top, but the hours that I

01:46:14.722 --> 01:46:19.642
worked, I never blamed on anyone
but myself. I just wanted to.

01:46:19.662 --> 01:46:23.422
I remember, you know,
coming in on Memorial

01:46:23.542 --> 01:46:26.622
Day, like, with sand from the beach on my

01:46:26.702 --> 01:46:30.422
feet because I really wanted to
get some work done that day, and

01:46:30.562 --> 01:46:34.442
working through Christmas, and
those were things I wanted to

01:46:34.502 --> 01:46:38.762
do. I never felt like somebody, you
know, held my feet to the coals.

01:46:38.802 --> 01:46:42.622
- Yeah, it's such a complicated thing because
yeah, okay, you could say that's unhealthy,

01:46:43.382 --> 01:46:47.262
but I know a large number of
people, especially in their 20s,

01:46:48.442 --> 01:46:53.402
but actually throughout their career, that
have been at companies that do crunch

01:46:54.782 --> 01:46:58.612
for a thing they believe in, for a thing they
love, and it's some of the most fulfilling

01:46:58.722 --> 01:47:01.622
years of their life, months and
years of their life. And they

01:47:01.822 --> 01:47:05.732
also it's not just fulfilling, they

01:47:05.842 --> 01:47:09.722
grow from it, they learn
from it, and it... You know,

01:47:09.902 --> 01:47:13.622
and when they... Especially when
they talk back about it, about that

01:47:13.682 --> 01:47:17.612
time, they can see how incredible
it was. Of course, when

01:47:17.622 --> 01:47:21.582
you're going through it, sometimes
it's extremely difficult, you

01:47:21.622 --> 01:47:25.502
don't know. And then the crunch, like you
mentioned, it's supposed to be a month

01:47:25.542 --> 01:47:29.342
or two, and then it turns out to be
a half a year, and then maybe it

01:47:29.351 --> 01:47:32.802
turns out to be something like a Titan
type game where you never actually ship

01:47:32.842 --> 01:47:36.692
it, and it's heartbreaking and the pain,
it's all... But then you look back

01:47:36.862 --> 01:47:39.422
and you realize how
incredible that journey was.

01:47:39.522 --> 01:47:45.322
- I think, like, my reflections on it
many years later, and having gone

01:47:45.382 --> 01:47:52.392
through, like, pretty crazy levels
of crunch to more controlled, I

01:47:52.462 --> 01:47:56.322
think where crunch is
problematic and people are

01:47:56.362 --> 01:48:02.502
good to be vocal about being opposed
to it, is when it's forced and

01:48:02.582 --> 01:48:06.222
unnecessary. There's a
lot of like, "Hey, if

01:48:06.342 --> 01:48:10.041
anybody on the team stays, we all stay"-

01:48:10.112 --> 01:48:10.432
- Yeah.

01:48:10.432 --> 01:48:16.982
- ... kind of, which I think is not necessary.
I don't think executives who take

01:48:17.102 --> 01:48:22.151
off and work 40-hour weeks should
be telling anybody to stay late.

01:48:22.182 --> 01:48:29.142
I think that's wrong and immoral. But
to me as an individual, as long as I'm

01:48:29.222 --> 01:48:35.122
not telling other people to do
it, my life's work is my passion

01:48:36.382 --> 01:48:39.682
and I want to do it as
much as possible. I find

01:48:39.702 --> 01:48:43.342
myself, I don't think I've
ever worked less than 10

01:48:43.402 --> 01:48:49.242
hours in a day. Like that... 10 hours
is like a normal-ish day to me.

01:48:49.322 --> 01:48:49.892
- Yeah. Yeah.

01:48:49.962 --> 01:48:57.642
- And I enjoy lots of weekends working
because I enjoy it. It brings

01:48:57.682 --> 01:49:01.482
me pleasure and fulfillment.
And all of that

01:49:01.562 --> 01:49:05.422
said, from a place of caution,
especially in this era

01:49:05.502 --> 01:49:07.342
when people are very touchy about it.

01:49:08.182 --> 01:49:12.062
I don't try to impose that on anybody
else. I don't want anybody to

01:49:12.122 --> 01:49:16.082
feel like they're obligated
to, but please understand

01:49:16.142 --> 01:49:19.652
it's what makes me who
I am, that work ethic.

01:49:19.652 --> 01:49:25.422
I enjoy it. I actually... Some of my fondest
memories are from those WoW crunches.

01:49:25.442 --> 01:49:29.242
- And then looking back and reading some of these
stories, it's pretty cool because me, as a

01:49:29.322 --> 01:49:32.962
fan, on the receiving end of
some of those video games, you

01:49:33.302 --> 01:49:36.782
bring joy to millions of
people. It's awesome.

01:49:36.922 --> 01:49:43.222
Let me ask you about quests, but first,
quick bathroom break if it's okay.

01:49:43.342 --> 01:49:46.522
Quick 30-second thank you to our
sponsors. Check them out in the

01:49:46.542 --> 01:49:50.442
description. It really is the best
way to support this podcast. Go to

01:49:50.482 --> 01:49:58.210
lexfridman.com/sponsors. We got Fin for
customer service AI agents, Blitzy for

01:49:58.370 --> 01:50:02.110
code generation in large code
bases, BetterHelp for mental

01:50:02.170 --> 01:50:08.970
health, Shopify for selling stuff online,
CodeRabbit for AI-powered code review, and

01:50:09.070 --> 01:50:12.090
Perplexity for curiosity-driven knowledge

01:50:12.230 --> 01:50:16.110
exploration. Choose wisely,
my friends. And now,

01:50:16.170 --> 01:50:19.310
back to my conversation with Jeff Kaplan.

01:50:19.870 --> 01:50:23.790
Okay, we're back. So I think
it's fair to say that before

01:50:23.850 --> 01:50:27.190
WoW, MMO leveling, like
in EverQuest, consisted

01:50:27.250 --> 01:50:31.230
of, maybe that's simplifying it a bit, but
standing in one spot and killing monsters

01:50:31.270 --> 01:50:38.630
for hours. You helped develop with
WoW, I would say a revolutionary

01:50:38.810 --> 01:50:42.439
idea of quest-driven
leveling, where there's a

01:50:43.070 --> 01:50:47.010
story-driven, quest-driven
guide through the world, and

01:50:47.210 --> 01:50:51.130
it so happens that as part of doing that,
you're also leveling the character.

01:50:52.010 --> 01:50:55.960
So the leveling is both
fun and is the engine that

01:50:55.970 --> 01:50:59.830
drives the story that then
also immerses you into the

01:50:59.870 --> 01:51:03.290
world and pulls you in more
and more and more and more. So

01:51:03.810 --> 01:51:10.850
take me through this process of developing
that idea of quest-driven design.

01:51:10.970 --> 01:51:14.890
- Sure. Yeah, there were actually a lot of
people involved in it, and they all kind of

01:51:14.930 --> 01:51:21.710
contributed in their own unique ways.
Allen Adham was the lead designer on

01:51:21.790 --> 01:51:25.380
WoW. When we first sort of
decided we were gonna have a

01:51:25.450 --> 01:51:31.600
quest-based game, we used to joke that,
like, EverQuest barely had any quests in it.

01:51:31.630 --> 01:51:35.570
It did have quests, they just...
They weren't really in front

01:51:35.630 --> 01:51:38.970
of the player in an obvious way. You
kind of had to seek them out on a

01:51:39.010 --> 01:51:44.890
website. And Allen knew that he
wanted quests to be a big part of,

01:51:45.730 --> 01:51:51.790
of World of Warcraft. And so he
hired me. That was my entry level

01:51:51.890 --> 01:51:55.850
position at Blizzard. And
on the same day, he hired

01:51:55.910 --> 01:51:59.810
a guy named Pat Nagle, which
was hilarious to me, because

01:51:59.870 --> 01:52:03.709
Pat was the... He had this funny title

01:52:03.719 --> 01:52:07.510
of HR and Facilities at
Blizzard, because it was such a

01:52:07.590 --> 01:52:11.499
small company. So, like, if
you sent an application in,

01:52:11.550 --> 01:52:15.170
Pat would deal with the
application, or if the toilet

01:52:15.270 --> 01:52:18.650
overflowed, Pat would
have to deal with it. And

01:52:19.490 --> 01:52:23.410
so the whole time I was applying at Blizzard, I
was going through Pat, and then on my first day,

01:52:23.430 --> 01:52:27.120
they put Pat and I in an office
together, and he's like,

01:52:27.120 --> 01:52:30.659
"Yeah, they hired me also
as the quest designer." And

01:52:31.310 --> 01:52:34.990
so Pat... And he was the most
wonderful guy. We had so much

01:52:35.090 --> 01:52:38.370
fun. So Pat and I kind
of designed the quest

01:52:38.510 --> 01:52:42.330
system. It was Allen's
idea to have it in the

01:52:42.370 --> 01:52:46.330
first place. And then there was that
great designer I mentioned, Eric

01:52:46.450 --> 01:52:53.850
Dodds, who helped a lot with the
interface of it all. And the idea was at

01:52:53.910 --> 01:52:57.590
first, we actually on a
whiteboard in Allen's

01:52:57.730 --> 01:53:01.530
office, we estimated how many
quests we thought EverQuest

01:53:01.690 --> 01:53:05.610
had to date. And EverQuest had
had, you know, I think four

01:53:05.770 --> 01:53:09.730
or three expansions at that point in time,

01:53:09.770 --> 01:53:13.190
and we're like, "Wow, we have to make
all of these quests like EverQuest

01:53:13.230 --> 01:53:19.930
has." It's gonna be a lot of quests,
and it's kind of up to me and Pat to do

01:53:19.990 --> 01:53:26.830
it all. And we believed all we had to
do was match that EverQuest number. And

01:53:27.750 --> 01:53:31.390
Pat and I started working on, like, the
design of the system and how it would

01:53:31.450 --> 01:53:35.430
interact, and Eric Dodds was really
involved in how the interface... You know,

01:53:35.470 --> 01:53:38.310
like how you were going to interact
with the NPCs and all of that.

01:53:39.310 --> 01:53:43.290
And we split up the world into like two

01:53:43.390 --> 01:53:46.960
zones. He was gonna take
Elwynn Forest, which was the

01:53:47.090 --> 01:53:50.910
starting area for the humans, and I
was gonna take Westfall, which was

01:53:51.310 --> 01:53:58.710
the sophomore zone after Elwynn for the
humans. Pat and I would meet with Chris

01:53:58.810 --> 01:54:02.510
Metzen, and those were the funnest
meetings ever because Chris just

01:54:03.870 --> 01:54:07.650
has stories in his head and
visions. Chris is, like,

01:54:07.730 --> 01:54:11.699
artist, storyteller, world
builder extraordinaire, and

01:54:11.749 --> 01:54:15.090
he sort of described what
he wanted going on in those

01:54:15.150 --> 01:54:18.310
zones. You know, you want
the gameplay to follow the

01:54:18.370 --> 01:54:25.360
flow of what was going on with the stories
of those areas. So we finished Elwynn and

01:54:25.450 --> 01:54:32.000
Westfall, and we did, like,
a team play test. And our

01:54:32.010 --> 01:54:35.630
assumption was because the way EverQuest

01:54:35.750 --> 01:54:39.850
worked, players just wanted to level
up. It was a level based game.

01:54:39.870 --> 01:54:43.790
You go out. You kill a creature.
You get experience points.

01:54:43.830 --> 01:54:47.750
You level up a little bit. And so
the way people played EverQuest is

01:54:47.770 --> 01:54:51.370
they'd find these areas where
there were lots of creatures,

01:54:51.710 --> 01:54:54.710
and you'd usually find the best experience

01:54:55.390 --> 01:54:58.130
efficiency cycle you could
find, so, like, fast

01:54:58.230 --> 01:55:04.860
respawn kind of easy things to kill, and
that's how you would progress through

01:55:04.910 --> 01:55:08.840
EverQuest. And I remember
Alan kind of telling

01:55:08.890 --> 01:55:12.650
us, like, "Hey, the
quests... When Pat and Jeff

01:55:12.690 --> 01:55:15.970
write quests, they'll aim
us to where the creatures

01:55:16.070 --> 01:55:19.730
are." You'll do a quest, and
then you'll spend a few hours

01:55:19.810 --> 01:55:24.950
killing creatures in that area afterwards,
and that's how he imagined it would work.

01:55:25.870 --> 01:55:29.850
So we kind of set up the world that
way. You know, Pat probably did

01:55:30.430 --> 01:55:34.270
a dozen, maybe 20 quests
in Elwynn. I'd do a dozen,

01:55:34.430 --> 01:55:37.310
20 quests in Westfall, and
we'd do this team play

01:55:37.410 --> 01:55:41.280
test. And we had a bunch of
people on the team who never

01:55:41.330 --> 01:55:45.120
played MMOs, like guys with
shooter background, you know,

01:55:45.210 --> 01:55:49.170
StarCraft fans, et cetera.
And they'd play World of

01:55:49.270 --> 01:55:53.230
Warcraft. I think we played for, like,
an hour or two, and we only did Elwynn

01:55:53.290 --> 01:55:57.260
Forest. And the overwhelming
feedback from our team...

01:55:57.270 --> 01:56:00.160
And these are people who really
didn't play EverQuest, they're

01:56:00.230 --> 01:56:06.182
like, "My God, Pat, that was horrible.
I ran out of quests, like, right

01:56:06.242 --> 01:56:13.082
away." And we're like, "Wait a second.
You expect to just have quests just keep

01:56:13.142 --> 01:56:16.852
going?" And they're like,
"Yeah, we expect to have

01:56:16.922 --> 01:56:20.822
quests just keep going the
whole way. And we kinda had

01:56:20.862 --> 01:56:24.622
an oh shit moment right after that
Elwynn Forest play test, where we

01:56:24.662 --> 01:56:29.962
realized, like, we had vastly underestimated
the number of quests we were gonna

01:56:30.062 --> 01:56:34.502
need. And we changed, we
developed this philosophy

01:56:35.422 --> 01:56:39.022
that's kind of a shared philosophy
across Blizzard games in

01:56:39.082 --> 01:56:43.022
general at this point. And I've heard it
outside of Blizzard, other people in the

01:56:43.102 --> 01:56:49.922
industry, which is you design along
the path of least resistance.

01:56:50.102 --> 01:56:52.882
So basically what that means, like, in

01:56:52.962 --> 01:56:56.862
EverQuest, the path of least
resistance if you wanted your

01:56:56.922 --> 01:57:00.732
character to hit max level is to
find the easiest creatures and

01:57:00.802 --> 01:57:04.762
kill them over and over again
in place, which to some

01:57:04.802 --> 01:57:08.612
people think is very boring. To me, I would
do that for eight hours 'cause I think that's

01:57:08.642 --> 01:57:12.342
fun. But we decided in World of

01:57:12.442 --> 01:57:15.822
Warcraft, we said, why don't
we make the path of least

01:57:15.922 --> 01:57:19.742
resistance, so in this
case, the way to get the

01:57:19.762 --> 01:57:23.542
best experience the fastest not to be

01:57:23.602 --> 01:57:27.262
killing creatures in one
place, but will overload the

01:57:27.322 --> 01:57:30.802
experience into the quests themselves,
and then that will move you through the

01:57:30.842 --> 01:57:34.502
world, which will get you to
see everything. It will enable

01:57:34.602 --> 01:57:38.572
us to tell these awesome
storylines. It sort of did a

01:57:38.662 --> 01:57:42.272
lot for the game, and I think
it was like a fundamental

01:57:42.482 --> 01:57:45.632
change in the genre. Like,
if you look at the things

01:57:45.722 --> 01:57:48.922
that... EverQuest was
very popular and very

01:57:48.962 --> 01:57:52.562
successful, and it was hitting
like hundreds of thousands of

01:57:52.602 --> 01:57:56.572
players. And WoW blew the
doors open and was tens of

01:57:56.602 --> 01:58:00.042
millions of players. And
I think the fundamental

01:58:00.102 --> 01:58:05.362
difference there was that WoW allowed
you to play as a single player.

01:58:06.942 --> 01:58:11.622
And what makes an MMO, massively
multiplayer online game,

01:58:13.182 --> 01:58:16.742
massive is having the other people there.

01:58:16.762 --> 01:58:20.722
And they're so important or else
the world feels kind of wrong and

01:58:20.862 --> 01:58:24.522
dead. But the concept that
we have to force you to

01:58:24.582 --> 01:58:27.962
interact with them to do anything is very

01:58:28.062 --> 01:58:31.842
off-putting to a lot of people.
And the fact that people could

01:58:31.922 --> 01:58:38.892
come into WoW and just kind of the
game design, the game design way of

01:58:39.062 --> 01:58:46.122
describing it is directed gameplay.
And some games have extremely tight

01:58:46.302 --> 01:58:49.842
directed gameplay. Like,
for example, if you were to

01:58:49.882 --> 01:58:53.762
play a single player game
like Last of Us, you

01:58:53.802 --> 01:58:57.792
know, you'll have those moments where they'll
be like, you'll come up to a log and then

01:58:57.802 --> 01:59:01.272
press Triangle to duck or else,
or whatever the duck button is—

01:59:01.322 --> 01:59:05.142
... left stick to duck to go under.
And that's like the ultimate

01:59:05.262 --> 01:59:08.962
in directed gameplay. Like, they're
telling you exactly what to

01:59:09.002 --> 01:59:12.842
do. On the other end of the spectrum
is a game like Minecraft, like

01:59:12.982 --> 01:59:16.662
vanilla Minecraft, where
you'll find it's very

01:59:16.702 --> 01:59:20.342
divisive amongst gamers
who love Minecraft or hate

01:59:20.402 --> 01:59:24.122
it. The ones who hate it are like,
"I don't know what I'm supposed to

01:59:24.182 --> 01:59:27.982
do." Like, "You drop me in this
world. I'm supposed to dig or

01:59:28.062 --> 01:59:31.922
something." And that's the type of player

01:59:31.942 --> 01:59:35.222
that needs directed gameplay
or they're gonna cycle

01:59:35.362 --> 01:59:39.072
out. Not all players need it. And what

01:59:39.182 --> 01:59:43.782
WoW did, that it doesn't seem like
an innovation, it doesn't seem

01:59:44.602 --> 01:59:52.142
like revolutionary, but it sort of
created this directed gameplay that felt

01:59:52.402 --> 01:59:54.782
optional, but really wasn't.

01:59:54.842 --> 01:59:58.362
- I mean, I think it's
absolutely revolutionary. It

01:59:58.402 --> 02:00:01.922
basically changed gaming.
It changed the way we

02:00:02.242 --> 02:00:05.602
see games. And it was
so successful in part

02:00:07.122 --> 02:00:11.082
because it became a mechanism by which you
could spend hundreds of hours, thousands

02:00:11.102 --> 02:00:14.662
of hours in the game. I
mean, it's kind of a, like,

02:00:14.782 --> 02:00:18.622
obviously... It's one of those... All
these great ideas are always like this,

02:00:18.682 --> 02:00:22.592
right? In retrospect, you're like,
"Well, obviously if you make the path of

02:00:22.622 --> 02:00:26.222
least resistance quest-driven
gameplay, then it's

02:00:26.702 --> 02:00:30.622
gonna be the reason that most people
play." But it is true that... I'm with

02:00:30.702 --> 02:00:39.002
you on... I both like the
quests and cow level.

02:00:39.022 --> 02:00:42.622
I guess you have to design for everybody.
That's the tricky thing. Like, how do you

02:00:43.542 --> 02:00:47.482
fine-tune this? If you think
of it as a loop of like accept

02:00:47.582 --> 02:00:51.462
quest, kill 10 rats, turn in quest, ding,

02:00:51.482 --> 02:00:56.822
level up, that loop. Like, how do you
fine-tune that so it's maximum fun

02:00:58.142 --> 02:01:03.562
or fun for the maximum number of people?
Is it... How- how difficult is that?

02:01:03.982 --> 02:01:07.842
- It's extremely difficult.
And not everybody's good

02:01:07.882 --> 02:01:12.882
at doing that. We all, to some
degree, lack the self-awareness

02:01:13.722 --> 02:01:17.322
of how we tick. So we're
all different types of

02:01:17.362 --> 02:01:21.022
gamers, but if you ask me to
describe the type of gamer I

02:01:21.142 --> 02:01:24.802
am, I might actually be giving
more of a picture of the type of

02:01:24.842 --> 02:01:28.682
gamer I wish I was or the
type of gamer I want you

02:01:28.722 --> 02:01:34.082
to think I am versus the
type of gamer I actually am.

02:01:34.122 --> 02:01:40.942
By playing lots of games, you cannot
be an exceptional game designer

02:01:41.762 --> 02:01:45.662
without playing the shit
out of as much as you

02:01:45.742 --> 02:01:51.332
can and understanding on a deep level.
And the weirdest part about it is

02:01:52.182 --> 02:01:56.082
you're not just looking for the
greatest hits. You learn just as

02:01:56.162 --> 02:02:03.382
much from a shitty game that you do
from an amazing game. And also—like, a

02:02:03.462 --> 02:02:10.692
lousy game can have a great system that
was tuned wrong, or lacked the correct

02:02:10.902 --> 02:02:14.422
interface, or they didn't put
the right visceral polish on

02:02:14.482 --> 02:02:18.382
it. There's an executional aspect to

02:02:18.482 --> 02:02:22.132
all of it. When I'm playing,
I'm not only, like, thinking

02:02:22.222 --> 02:02:26.022
about what makes this fun, I'm
thinking about what makes this

02:02:26.102 --> 02:02:34.002
not fun. But I'm also watching everyone
around me. My wife plays games, my kids

02:02:34.082 --> 02:02:37.882
play games. And understanding,
like, well, what do

02:02:37.922 --> 02:02:41.902
they do and how are they different to
me? Why are they finding enjoyment in

02:02:41.962 --> 02:02:46.282
this? Why are they not? What's
frustrating? What did they miss?

02:02:46.382 --> 02:02:50.242
- And being raw honest with exactly
what you're saying. I mean,

02:02:50.302 --> 02:02:54.202
I, if I were to analyze the
kind of gamer I am, why do I

02:02:54.222 --> 02:03:01.442
enjoy cow level? And why, above that,
why do I enjoy loot? Why- why is

02:03:01.502 --> 02:03:05.362
loot so fun? Like, what-
what does- what is it about

02:03:05.522 --> 02:03:09.382
opening a chest and getting a
bunch of stuff? I mean, I, that

02:03:09.442 --> 02:03:13.202
might be like at the core of what
I enjoy about gaming. That, and

02:03:13.242 --> 02:03:16.482
walking around a beautiful
world with nice music.

02:03:16.542 --> 02:03:22.122
- As a game designer, I am, at best,
a quack psychologist. You know?

02:03:22.132 --> 02:03:26.122
We can motivate you to
do some weird things.

02:03:26.182 --> 02:03:29.602
The two driving motivators
are extrinsic and

02:03:29.722 --> 02:03:33.622
intrinsic. And all of us,
at different times in

02:03:33.662 --> 02:03:37.312
our lives, in our gaming
careers, whatever, we can

02:03:37.402 --> 02:03:41.262
shift from being intrinsically
motivated to being

02:03:41.322 --> 02:03:45.122
extrinsically motivated.
Obviously, loot is a

02:03:45.162 --> 02:03:48.942
big extrinsic motivation,
but even saying that is

02:03:48.982 --> 02:03:56.802
too simplistic. Like, for example, on
the loot boxes of Overwatch, there's

02:03:56.882 --> 02:04:03.402
a masterfully designed system that was
designed by a game designer, not by a

02:04:03.442 --> 02:04:10.982
businessperson or whatever. Like, not
a commercial person. But beyond that,

02:04:11.042 --> 02:04:14.922
we also had a really
good team who said the

02:04:14.982 --> 02:04:18.511
visceral opening of the
box, the sound it makes-

02:04:19.182 --> 02:04:26.242
... the graphics, like the way things
spill out and animate, all of that is as

02:04:26.302 --> 02:04:30.262
satisfying as well. And you're trying
to... Like, there's the lizard

02:04:30.282 --> 02:04:33.882
brain part of it. Of like,
how does it... Like, I see

02:04:33.942 --> 02:04:37.882
chest. I know I'm gonna... It's gonna
feel good. It's gonna feel good.

02:04:37.902 --> 02:04:41.712
And then there's the spreadsheety
part of it. Of, what does it

02:04:41.712 --> 02:04:45.282
have? Is it an upgrade? And I think

02:04:45.342 --> 02:04:49.942
great game designers know how to
tap into both of those things.

02:04:49.982 --> 02:04:52.832
You know, tap into the intrinsic and

02:04:52.922 --> 02:04:56.702
extrinsic. There's...
Like, when I was studying

02:04:56.782 --> 02:05:00.642
writing, you would study
the elements of fiction.

02:05:00.702 --> 02:05:04.442
And, you know, these are just
like basic things like plot and

02:05:04.482 --> 02:05:07.222
character development and
setting and theme and

02:05:07.262 --> 02:05:10.962
whatever. And there's
no, like, textbook that

02:05:11.042 --> 02:05:14.422
exists for game design, at least
none that has been introduced to me

02:05:14.502 --> 02:05:19.442
yet. But I think about,
like, elements of fun.

02:05:19.482 --> 02:05:22.802
What are the things that create fun
for players? And they're not the

02:05:22.882 --> 02:05:30.602
same. Like, it really... Every human being
is different. Like, progression is fun.

02:05:30.622 --> 02:05:34.262
Sense of progression that I'm
investing. I'm putting an

02:05:34.302 --> 02:05:37.562
investment into this game,
and then the game is

02:05:37.722 --> 02:05:41.482
recognizing my investment. That
things like leveling, things like the

02:05:41.502 --> 02:05:44.482
amount of gold you have,
those are all investment

02:05:44.582 --> 02:05:52.042
based. There's mastery. There's
just pure raw skill. Creativity is

02:05:52.142 --> 02:05:55.652
one. And hand-in-hand with creativity is

02:05:55.682 --> 02:05:59.152
customization. And some of
those can be aesthetic.

02:05:59.222 --> 02:06:03.202
Like, look at my customized
character, and I have the black

02:06:03.282 --> 02:06:06.962
curly hair, and I put an earring in my

02:06:07.022 --> 02:06:10.842
character and I'm customizing
in that way. The other is

02:06:10.862 --> 02:06:14.322
customizing my build.
I'm gonna come up with a

02:06:14.382 --> 02:06:22.082
whirlwind barbarian and I'm the first
to do it. These are all elements of fun

02:06:22.702 --> 02:06:26.322
that designers can tap into,
and in fact are frequently

02:06:26.402 --> 02:06:29.542
tapping into. But they're never defined

02:06:29.602 --> 02:06:33.582
anywhere, and I find that
players drift. Like, I'm the

02:06:33.622 --> 02:06:37.382
type of player who's not really
loot motivated. I'm more

02:06:37.442 --> 02:06:45.082
motivated by seeing the content the world
has to offer. And often that takes me on a

02:06:45.142 --> 02:06:48.862
detour of being loot
motivated, because there

02:06:48.922 --> 02:06:56.702
might be a dragon or a demon somewhere that
I can't beat without this level of armor

02:06:56.742 --> 02:07:00.582
and sword. So now I'm loot
motivated for some period

02:07:00.622 --> 02:07:07.122
of time, to get back to being content
motivated. Or if I'm having trouble

02:07:07.222 --> 02:07:10.842
defeating a boss, I might
have to go back and look

02:07:10.922 --> 02:07:14.822
at the skills and abilities that
my character's using, and I have

02:07:14.842 --> 02:07:18.632
to go into creativity mode.
"Oh, he has that one AE where

02:07:18.742 --> 02:07:22.152
he..." Area of effect. "...where
he puts a curse on me."

02:07:22.202 --> 02:07:26.022
And, you know, "If I had this
counterability to the curse, I

02:07:26.042 --> 02:07:33.372
could beat the boss to get the loot, to get
to the next boss." These are all cycles

02:07:33.402 --> 02:07:36.942
that are tapping into all those
different elements of fun.

02:07:36.962 --> 02:07:42.582
- And ultimately enjoying and
discovering what the world gives you.

02:07:42.592 --> 02:07:46.472
Has to offer to you. And
you're... You have a lot of hats

02:07:46.602 --> 02:07:53.142
as a gamer, so you love the RPG, MMORPG
world, but you're also a big shooter guy.

02:07:53.782 --> 02:07:57.772
Can you explain to me what fun
in a shooter context is? And

02:07:57.802 --> 02:08:01.672
we'll talk about Overwatch as a
specific kind of fun. Maybe...

02:08:01.922 --> 02:08:05.582
But you're also a huge fan of the
ultra-realistic shooters. Call of

02:08:05.662 --> 02:08:08.942
Duty. What is the definition of fun there?

02:08:09.626 --> 02:08:13.246
- There's a lot of skill
and mastery. Off the

02:08:13.326 --> 02:08:17.086
cuff, flippant comment would
be clicking heads, you

02:08:17.166 --> 02:08:18.886
know? I'm just trying to click heads.

02:08:18.946 --> 02:08:19.746
- Okay.

02:08:19.816 --> 02:08:23.606
- There's an intimacy also to the first

02:08:23.786 --> 02:08:27.686
person camera. And now,
not all shooters are first

02:08:27.786 --> 02:08:35.406
person. There is a large trend these days
to third person. I really think PUBG and

02:08:35.506 --> 02:08:39.186
Fortnite sort of opened
that third person shooter

02:08:39.286 --> 02:08:44.246
door. And you're seeing games like ARC
Raiders are third person. But to me,

02:08:45.566 --> 02:08:48.836
nothing is as pure as
first person. Like you're

02:08:48.886 --> 02:08:52.815
... literally living in the world
as that being. You can look

02:08:52.866 --> 02:09:00.386
at your hands, and it's that pure
visceral test of skill of, "Can you click

02:09:00.446 --> 02:09:05.606
on the thing fast enough?" And when it's
PvP-based, you know that's coming at you.

02:09:05.666 --> 02:09:09.216
- Could you lay out for people who
don't necessarily know what PvP and

02:09:09.246 --> 02:09:11.546
PvE is? And single player

02:09:11.566 --> 02:09:11.635
- Absolutely

02:09:11.666 --> 02:09:13.706
- ... multiplayer, massively
online multiplayer?

02:09:14.486 --> 02:09:18.186
- So PvP is player versus
player, so that means a

02:09:18.226 --> 02:09:21.786
combative, you know... If Lex
and I are up against each

02:09:21.866 --> 02:09:25.836
other, we're attacking each other. We
call that PvP. You can get killed by

02:09:25.866 --> 02:09:31.466
another player. Uh, player versus
environment is anytime you're shooting

02:09:31.926 --> 02:09:35.666
computer controlled
opponents. So if it's a game

02:09:35.746 --> 02:09:41.106
about dragons, the dragon is
the E, the environment in PvE.

02:09:41.586 --> 02:09:45.166
- And we should say that PvP and
PvE, the P might be multiple

02:09:45.266 --> 02:09:48.766
players. It could be five
versus five, six versus

02:09:48.866 --> 02:09:56.656
six for PvP. And for PvE, it could be,
like, raids where it's multiple people,

02:09:56.706 --> 02:09:59.366
large groups of people
going against the AI.

02:09:59.426 --> 02:10:03.206
- Yep. So single player,
that's a game that you

02:10:03.246 --> 02:10:07.186
play totally by yourself. Like, you
don't play with anybody else. You

02:10:07.266 --> 02:10:11.246
can't play with anybody
else. It's not networked to

02:10:11.286 --> 02:10:15.146
play with other people. For example,
I'm playing a game called Story of

02:10:15.246 --> 02:10:19.085
Seasons right now on the
Switch, which I just

02:10:19.146 --> 02:10:23.086
play by myself. I have my farm.
You know, there's a town. I'm

02:10:23.366 --> 02:10:27.246
meeting people in the town, and
no one can come and join me and

02:10:27.306 --> 02:10:30.565
interact with that. So
it's a very controlled

02:10:30.686 --> 02:10:32.726
experience. Single player games are very

02:10:33.586 --> 02:10:37.186
difficult, or they can be
very difficult and expensive

02:10:37.746 --> 02:10:41.446
in terms of production to
create. Like, if you think of a

02:10:41.546 --> 02:10:44.826
game, like Uncharted or Last of Us

02:10:45.446 --> 02:10:49.006
that's made by Naughty Dog,
like, those are kind of the

02:10:49.066 --> 02:10:52.946
preeminent best single
player games you could talk

02:10:53.026 --> 02:10:59.486
about. They're very handcrafted.
Every experience is made just for

02:10:59.566 --> 02:11:07.086
you. One up from that is what
I call co-op. And these terms

02:11:07.306 --> 02:11:11.086
become interchangeable, so I'm
using some semantics here.

02:11:11.106 --> 02:11:15.026
But co-op is any cooperative
experience that we

02:11:15.066 --> 02:11:18.866
can play together, but
we're sharing an exact

02:11:18.926 --> 02:11:22.756
same experience very
intentionally. And it's

02:11:22.866 --> 02:11:26.086
me sharing that experience
only with other people that I

02:11:26.166 --> 02:11:29.556
know. So a great example of a cooperative

02:11:29.666 --> 02:11:32.556
game, maybe one of the best
of all times, was Left 4

02:11:32.646 --> 02:11:36.336
Dead, which is a game
where you and three other

02:11:36.366 --> 02:11:40.296
people go in and you fight,
like, hordes of zombies,

02:11:40.306 --> 02:11:44.236
and you try to progress
through to the end safe room.

02:11:44.236 --> 02:11:47.886
it's a very cooperative
experience. A game like

02:11:47.926 --> 02:11:54.646
Diablo IV, you can play cooperatively
with other people. Now, one up from that

02:11:54.766 --> 02:11:58.136
is multiplayer, and that's
when you're engaging with

02:11:58.586 --> 02:12:02.486
strangers who are in the same
world that you might not have the

02:12:02.546 --> 02:12:09.206
same cooperative goals as. You might have
very opposed goals to them. You might PvP

02:12:09.266 --> 02:12:12.866
them, or they might just be
random strangers that you

02:12:13.006 --> 02:12:19.586
pass in a town or city and never see again.
And then massively multiplayer, which

02:12:19.646 --> 02:12:23.506
is what the MMO online sort of stands

02:12:23.566 --> 02:12:27.166
for, massively multiplayer
online game, that's when you're

02:12:27.186 --> 02:12:30.906
breaking into thousands
of players. And the

02:12:30.926 --> 02:12:34.666
worlds become really,
really big at that point.

02:12:34.766 --> 02:12:38.366
- By the way, we should say
that the co-op could be

02:12:38.766 --> 02:12:42.526
remote connection, but
there's also what would you

02:12:42.626 --> 02:12:46.536
call it, couch co-op where you
have two people. Some games are

02:12:46.536 --> 02:12:50.406
really designed well for the experience of two
humans sitting together and playing the game

02:12:50.466 --> 02:12:51.716
together.

02:12:51.726 --> 02:12:55.306
Which is a really tricky thing to design
for, but if it's done well, it's a,

02:12:55.366 --> 02:12:58.766
It's a really fulfilling
experience. Like, with a

02:12:58.826 --> 02:13:02.426
friend, with a loved one, you can,
like, play a game together. And Diablo

02:13:02.506 --> 02:13:06.396
IV, I should say, is an example of a
game that does that really well. They do

02:13:06.906 --> 02:13:10.316
couch co-op. Like, two people
can play Diablo sitting together

02:13:10.946 --> 02:13:13.316
and there's a real intimate
experience in that.

02:13:13.316 --> 02:13:17.086
- Yeah, couch co- it's funny, 'cause it
actually, like, predates the couch even.

02:13:17.126 --> 02:13:19.786
Some of those old arcade games-

02:13:20.686 --> 02:13:23.836
... like, would have two joysticks
on them and then you could play-

02:13:23.836 --> 02:13:27.826
... with somebody else. Or there's
you know, famous game Gauntlet-

02:13:27.866 --> 02:13:31.746
... had four joysticks and four
people playing together. And

02:13:31.786 --> 02:13:35.426
then anybody who grew up
in that early console era,

02:13:35.486 --> 02:13:42.706
like, you know, NES, Sega Genesis was a
legendary one. We would sit and we'd play

02:13:42.866 --> 02:13:50.606
NHL 93- ... on the couch. And anybody
who lost, you'd lose the controller.

02:13:50.686 --> 02:13:54.446
And you could play that with up to
four people playing, or we... I

02:13:54.486 --> 02:13:57.826
remember one of the big games
that came out was Mortal

02:13:57.946 --> 02:14:01.426
Kombat. And we would play
Mortal Kombat on the Sega

02:14:01.506 --> 02:14:05.066
Genesis, and it was the house
rules were, you know, whoever

02:14:05.146 --> 02:14:09.046
lost, so whether you were in your
college dorm or just some buddy's

02:14:09.106 --> 02:14:12.526
apartment and there's five
people there, you're constantly

02:14:12.566 --> 02:14:16.406
cycling everybody in and
out. But there's just a

02:14:16.666 --> 02:14:21.826
magic to multiplayer, of engaging
and sharing in the experience-

02:14:21.836 --> 02:14:25.427
... with other people. Um, that's why I've

02:14:25.498 --> 02:14:29.488
always... I've never made a single
player game. Uh, I have great admiration

02:14:29.518 --> 02:14:33.408
for them. I don't know if I
could do it. The challenge...

02:14:33.438 --> 02:14:36.798
The reason I love multiplayer
so much, the way I

02:14:36.858 --> 02:14:40.668
describe being a game
director or game designer on

02:14:40.858 --> 02:14:44.818
a multiplayer game, it's like
imagine if you were gonna

02:14:44.858 --> 02:14:51.528
be a movie director, and you were gonna
have all these actors and set designers and

02:14:51.578 --> 02:14:55.428
props and, you know, writers
and scripts and all of

02:14:55.478 --> 02:14:58.698
this stuff, and your goal
was to get a certain movie

02:14:58.738 --> 02:15:05.698
made. But we're gonna ask you, the director,
to just... You're gonna leave the room.

02:15:07.078 --> 02:15:10.718
You can set it all up ahead of time, and

02:15:10.758 --> 02:15:16.058
then you're not allowed to be there
or talk to anybody involved in it.

02:15:16.098 --> 02:15:19.868
And now you need the actors to
have an experience, and it's

02:15:19.938 --> 02:15:24.078
just kind of the wildest,
funnest experiment. Like-

02:15:24.138 --> 02:15:28.118
- From a designer/creator perspective, 'cause
you don't know what the players will

02:15:28.178 --> 02:15:33.478
create, so that's fun to see. You
lay out the chessboard, you lay

02:15:33.538 --> 02:15:38.138
out the world, and then you get to watch
what they create together. That's true.

02:15:38.278 --> 02:15:44.098
- I struggle because sometimes people
call me the anti-story guy in

02:15:44.138 --> 02:15:51.138
games, and that really hurts me
because, like, I actually love story in

02:15:51.258 --> 02:15:55.138
games, and I counter that
I'm the anti-shitty story

02:15:55.638 --> 02:15:59.628
guy. And what I mean by
that is like, A, the most

02:15:59.678 --> 02:16:05.658
magical stories that I've ever heard come
out of video games are player stories

02:16:06.198 --> 02:16:10.158
about, you know, the time
I gave Barfa a potion

02:16:10.238 --> 02:16:17.538
and then I met him in real life. Like,
that's better than any video game writing

02:16:17.738 --> 02:16:24.998
that I've heard in a long while. The
player story is so much more interesting.

02:16:25.078 --> 02:16:28.218
You know? "Lex, why do you
like the cow level so much?"

02:16:28.228 --> 02:16:30.378
"Tell me about some goofy time-"

02:16:30.388 --> 02:16:33.308
"... like a loot goblin drew
you into the most danger."

02:16:33.318 --> 02:16:36.498
"And... But there was another player
there, and then..." You know, like,

02:16:37.078 --> 02:16:39.898
those are the stories that I
think are more interesting from

02:16:39.998 --> 02:16:47.258
games. There are some exceptional writers
in video games and some exceptional games

02:16:47.798 --> 02:16:51.678
at story. You know, I've
mentioned Naughty Dog,

02:16:51.718 --> 02:16:55.498
like they're kind of on
another level. But Valve has

02:16:55.507 --> 02:17:02.558
amazing writing. The writing behind Half-Life
2, Marc Laidlaw, the writing behind

02:17:02.618 --> 02:17:03.768
Portal-

02:17:03.838 --> 02:17:10.758
... and Portal 2. I think it was Erik
Wolpaw, who is hilarious, just amazing,

02:17:11.558 --> 02:17:18.098
and Rockstar. Red Dead Redemption
2 is one of my favorite

02:17:18.198 --> 02:17:25.018
games of all time, and that's a game where
you can see the expertise and mastery

02:17:26.398 --> 02:17:29.998
of the game design and the
narrative design, and the fact

02:17:30.058 --> 02:17:33.828
that you can have those player stories of

02:17:33.918 --> 02:17:37.558
just the goofy shit. Like,
I remember... 'Cause the

02:17:37.598 --> 02:17:40.977
controls are a little
awkward in Red Dead for a PC

02:17:41.058 --> 02:17:44.838
player who's playing on console.
Like, I always get confused

02:17:44.878 --> 02:17:48.598
about, like, taking out my
gun and putting it away, and

02:17:48.778 --> 02:17:52.518
what's, you know, the
L1 and L2. Like, as a

02:17:52.558 --> 02:17:55.458
PC gamer, I'm just like, "Let me
bind this stuff to where I want

02:17:55.518 --> 02:17:59.438
it." And so like you know,
a guy in town rides by and

02:17:59.447 --> 02:18:02.958
he's like, "Howdy, partner." And I
go to, like, give him the Arthur

02:18:03.038 --> 02:18:06.978
Morgan, you know, "Hey, what's
up?" back, and I just whip out my

02:18:07.058 --> 02:18:10.958
sawed-off shotgun and, like, blow his
fucking head off. And then the whole

02:18:11.118 --> 02:18:14.818
town is like... Suddenly
I'm, like, under... I'm

02:18:14.858 --> 02:18:18.468
wanted and I'm being chased,
and then there's a train that,

02:18:18.498 --> 02:18:21.438
like, takes out the posse, and-

02:18:21.518 --> 02:18:21.528
- Yes.

02:18:21.538 --> 02:18:25.288
- It's like those stories, and the fact
that Red Dead can have, you know, this,

02:18:25.318 --> 02:18:28.658
like, touching, heartbreaking
story of Arthur Morgan and his

02:18:28.718 --> 02:18:32.638
journey, but you can also have, you
know, the player story of blowing

02:18:32.698 --> 02:18:34.208
off the poor guy that's just trying to-

02:18:34.208 --> 02:18:35.608
- And that's the combination.

02:18:35.638 --> 02:18:39.568
And then Rockstar does a really good job
with you know, even in Grand Theft Auto with

02:18:39.578 --> 02:18:46.678
the radio, it can be kind of a side aspect
to the game, that great writing there can

02:18:46.758 --> 02:18:49.358
create- help create the world-

02:18:49.418 --> 02:18:52.838
... with, with humor, with color, with
depth, with heartbreak, all that kind of

02:18:52.878 --> 02:18:53.938
stuff.

02:18:53.978 --> 02:19:01.118
- There was a moment in Red Dead where
it... There's the Daniel Lanois song-

02:19:01.298 --> 02:19:04.978
..."That's the Way It Is".
I just... I love Daniel

02:19:05.018 --> 02:19:12.518
Lanois, so the fact that somehow Rockstar
landed him and like, was able to

02:19:12.578 --> 02:19:16.488
get that song out of him. And

02:19:16.498 --> 02:19:20.568
there's this moment where you're, like,
riding back and they start that song, and-

02:19:20.598 --> 02:19:20.838
- Yeah.

02:19:20.898 --> 02:19:24.798
- Everything up to then had been
gorgeous, like, more of a

02:19:24.958 --> 02:19:28.938
score. There's Woody Jackson,
who's, like, a really amazing game

02:19:29.398 --> 02:19:33.338
composer. He had done the
score for that, and so

02:19:33.378 --> 02:19:37.298
nothing had been, like, lyrical
with words. And then they play

02:19:37.308 --> 02:19:41.528
the Daniel Lanois song, and there's,
like, the quotes are coming back-

02:19:41.698 --> 02:19:43.798
... from, like, Dutch
and Arthur Morgan, and

02:19:45.278 --> 02:19:48.858
I'm just like, "Goddam,
this is, like... This is

02:19:48.998 --> 02:19:52.978
art." You know, this is like I know it's
supposed to be entertainment, I know it's a

02:19:53.058 --> 02:19:58.778
business, but the top of the pyramid is
art, and- ... it just hit me emotionally.

02:19:58.818 --> 02:20:02.738
- Yeah, there's certain games where, you
know... I mean, that moment, you just

02:20:02.758 --> 02:20:06.578
imagine the number of people who shed
a tear during that moment, and that's

02:20:06.618 --> 02:20:10.428
just a reflection of how much you're
invested into this world, into

02:20:10.428 --> 02:20:14.198
these characters, and it's
a beautiful thing. Uh,

02:20:14.458 --> 02:20:17.978
I have to ask you about this image
that you sent me. It's super cool, so

02:20:18.638 --> 02:20:22.558
I'd love it if we could nerd out about
it a little bit, the zone flow for

02:20:22.598 --> 02:20:26.568
the original World of Warcraft.
There's a bunch of zones. It'd

02:20:26.598 --> 02:20:29.838
be awesome if you kinda talk
through how, like, this world is

02:20:29.878 --> 02:20:33.590
built. Take me to that time when you
were designing this, before anyone

02:20:33.710 --> 02:20:35.360
else got a chance to play it.

02:20:35.470 --> 02:20:42.230
- All WoW stuff. It would start from that
inspiration of Chris and the world.

02:20:42.290 --> 02:20:45.870
And, you know, it was so
fun hanging out with Chris

02:20:45.890 --> 02:20:49.410
because we had whiteboards
all over the place, and, you

02:20:49.470 --> 02:20:53.430
know, "Hey, Chris, we should
make Eastern Kingdoms.

02:20:53.470 --> 02:20:57.030
What do you think it should be?"
And he would just tell you the

02:20:57.150 --> 02:21:01.050
story of each of these as he's
just drawing. And Chris is

02:21:01.170 --> 02:21:05.090
a really talented artist, so
the map would be gorgeous. I

02:21:05.130 --> 02:21:08.810
have lots of, like,
photographs of Chris maps,

02:21:08.910 --> 02:21:12.510
That he would just kind of
whiteboard up. He's like, you know,

02:21:12.520 --> 02:21:16.469
"Here's the Dwarven Lands,
there's Wetlands with Khaz Modan

02:21:16.530 --> 02:21:20.450
up there, and that's where this,
you know, tribe of dwarves

02:21:20.510 --> 02:21:24.350
were from. And then they, you
know, humans are going to be down,

02:21:24.410 --> 02:21:28.370
With Elwynn Forest. And then
Westfall, there's, you know,

02:21:28.450 --> 02:21:32.170
this group called the Defias Brotherhood
and they have a place called

02:21:32.230 --> 02:21:35.390
Deadmines." So I would talk to Chris

02:21:35.430 --> 02:21:38.650
because you want to capture
the spirit, like, as a game

02:21:38.690 --> 02:21:42.490
designer, you want to capture
the experience that's in

02:21:42.530 --> 02:21:47.660
people's heads. So, like, take
Burning Steppes, for example.

02:21:47.690 --> 02:21:51.180
Supposed to be one of the
scariest places with lava and

02:21:51.290 --> 02:21:55.150
dragons and, you know, all
this kind of stuff. That

02:21:55.190 --> 02:21:58.620
doesn't feel like where you want to
start. It feels like where you want to

02:21:58.850 --> 02:22:05.810
end, so you kind of work the world
flow in a way that puts that at the

02:22:05.910 --> 02:22:09.730
end. But there was also
kind of some magic to the

02:22:09.890 --> 02:22:17.210
original starting areas, where we gave the
dwarves and the humans a free flight path

02:22:17.230 --> 02:22:20.950
between... The dwarf hometown
was called Ironforge, the

02:22:21.010 --> 02:22:23.350
human hometown was called Stormwind.

02:22:23.360 --> 02:22:26.950
And we allowed you to fly for
free. So, like, these little

02:22:27.010 --> 02:22:30.670
newbies who were, you know, level five or

02:22:30.730 --> 02:22:34.650
something, if you played a dwarf
and I played a human, I'm like,

02:22:34.660 --> 02:22:38.430
"Oh, Lex, don't worry, I'll come. You
know, I'll come to Ironforge and we'll

02:22:38.490 --> 02:22:42.150
hook up and I'll just fly out to
you," which is the magic of World of

02:22:42.230 --> 02:22:46.020
Warcraft. You have to fly
over Burning Steppes and

02:22:46.070 --> 02:22:49.870
Searing Gorge, and you look
down and you're like, "Holy

02:22:50.010 --> 02:22:56.610
shit, that looks scary and dangerous." And
it plants that seed of things to come.

02:22:56.710 --> 02:23:00.410
- Uh, so you've designed some
incredible quests. Is there any that

02:23:00.470 --> 02:23:04.110
stand out that you're proud of
ashamed of? I mean, you are

02:23:04.170 --> 02:23:09.259
famously have designed the Green
Hills of Stranglethorn quest.

02:23:09.290 --> 02:23:13.170
One of the most infamous
quests in the history of WoW,

02:23:13.230 --> 02:23:16.460
of gaming, where you had to
collect a bunch of pages, or...

02:23:17.010 --> 02:23:20.770
Green Hills of Stranglethorn,
maybe, can you,

02:23:21.210 --> 02:23:26.050
comment on that one or any quest
that just springs to mind?

02:23:26.110 --> 02:23:29.800
- Green Hills of Stranglethorn
holds a lot of emotional

02:23:29.890 --> 02:23:33.870
value for me because
amongst WoW players back in

02:23:33.910 --> 02:23:41.740
the day, it was unanimously hated as one of
the shittiest, most annoying quests. Um,

02:23:41.770 --> 02:23:45.060
but it holds a really special
place in my heart. First of

02:23:45.130 --> 02:23:48.910
all, it's one of the few times
that I just, like, wrote a

02:23:48.930 --> 02:23:55.290
short story that's actually in the
game. Um, it's me paying homage to

02:23:55.450 --> 02:23:59.230
Hemingway, and the guy who gives
you the quest, his name is

02:23:59.310 --> 02:24:06.690
Hemet Nesingwary, which is just me
rearranging the letters of Hemingway.

02:24:06.770 --> 02:24:10.530
There's another quest giver
there that's Kerouac's

02:24:10.610 --> 02:24:18.650
name also mixed up. Um, and then
it was the typical hubris of

02:24:18.690 --> 02:24:25.819
a junior game designer who thinks he's
clever but is actually a dipshit. That's-

02:24:25.850 --> 02:24:29.410
That's the Green Hills of
Stranglethorn, like, summed up.

02:24:29.420 --> 02:24:33.190
So, like, I wrote the story
over, like, it was, I think,

02:24:33.770 --> 02:24:37.670
winter break, like, everybody
was gone and I just was so

02:24:37.790 --> 02:24:41.550
happy to be in the office, you
know, I'm at Blizzard by myself

02:24:42.150 --> 02:24:46.070
writing late at night. And
the whole idea, and this

02:24:46.130 --> 02:24:49.289
is, this is very much what I call ant farm

02:24:49.490 --> 02:24:53.239
designer, which is bad. Which
is, you know, you're the

02:24:53.350 --> 02:24:57.230
game designer who's playing
God, and players are the ants

02:24:57.270 --> 02:25:01.210
in your ant farm, and you want to
see what they're gonna do, which is

02:25:01.230 --> 02:25:07.190
not the correct way to be a good multiplayer
designer. But I hadn't learned that

02:25:07.270 --> 02:25:13.730
yet, and there's a, there's a
really great famous Sid Meier quote

02:25:14.870 --> 02:25:18.650
where he says there's three
types of fun. Fun for the

02:25:18.710 --> 02:25:21.670
player, fun for the
designer, and fun for the

02:25:21.730 --> 02:25:25.630
computer. And we catch
ourselves, we're like, you know,

02:25:25.670 --> 02:25:28.750
we gotta be really care... It has to
be fun for the player, not fun for

02:25:28.850 --> 02:25:32.770
us. So this Green Hills of
Stranglethorn quest was like

02:25:32.810 --> 02:25:36.790
an ant farm design of,
I'm gonna write this,

02:25:36.810 --> 02:25:40.210
honestly, probably pretty shitty
story, I haven't read it since

02:25:40.330 --> 02:25:44.230
2003 so God only knows
if it's any good. But I

02:25:44.250 --> 02:25:48.070
wrote the story and then I divided
it up into all of these different

02:25:48.130 --> 02:25:51.880
pages. And the quest
giver, Hemet Nesingwary,

02:25:52.310 --> 02:25:56.290
wants you to put together, like, the
story's like, he wrote this book,

02:25:56.330 --> 02:26:00.230
but then the pages got scattered
across Stranglethorn Vale.

02:26:00.350 --> 02:26:04.210
And some... When you're doing quest
design, you're really thinking

02:26:04.250 --> 02:26:09.870
about the player flow and you're
directing them from quest giver hubs

02:26:10.710 --> 02:26:14.630
out until these destinations, and you
want them to do all the destinations.

02:26:14.670 --> 02:26:18.310
But sometimes we would
do these bridging quests

02:26:18.490 --> 02:26:21.530
where you could do anything in
the zone and it sort of had this

02:26:21.630 --> 02:26:29.150
overlap. And so the pages of Green Hills of
Stranglethorn could be looted off of any

02:26:29.290 --> 02:26:33.030
creature anywhere in Stranglethorn
Vale, and it was kind of

02:26:33.070 --> 02:26:35.830
like that McDonald's Monopoly game

02:26:36.590 --> 02:26:39.910
where you have to have all the
pieces or else you're not gonna

02:26:39.950 --> 02:26:43.850
win. But where I really went
south, I don't think the

02:26:43.930 --> 02:26:52.050
idea in a vacuum is horrible, but where
this really fell apart was the interface

02:26:52.230 --> 02:26:56.130
of World of Warcraft wasn't
set up. Like the pages

02:26:56.190 --> 02:27:00.070
didn't stack, there wasn't
a dedicated container to

02:27:00.130 --> 02:27:04.050
put all the pages in, so
players had very limited bag

02:27:04.110 --> 02:27:10.790
space. And as they're fighting in
Stranglethorn Vale, I'm just shitting up their

02:27:10.890 --> 02:27:14.470
inventory with all of these
pag- And they only needed so

02:27:14.550 --> 02:27:18.130
many. Like you might get
unlucky and you have like three

02:27:18.290 --> 02:27:24.430
page fives that are just junk in your
inventory, and I might have like eight page

02:27:24.630 --> 02:27:28.590
sixes. And then everybody...
And this was the goal, like

02:27:28.830 --> 02:27:32.710
the designer trying to
puppeteer everybody. Everybody

02:27:32.770 --> 02:27:36.310
in Stranglethorn chat is like,
"Hey, I'm looking for a page

02:27:36.390 --> 02:27:40.210
six. Anyone got a page three?"
And that was like my fantasy as a

02:27:40.270 --> 02:27:43.730
designer of like, and then
they're gonna be social and

02:27:44.230 --> 02:27:47.990
meet each other, and players are
gonna be appreciative for each

02:27:48.090 --> 02:27:51.770
other, but really all everybody did was
just no... Eventually, no one did the

02:27:51.830 --> 02:27:55.590
quest. They just were super annoyed,
or they went to the Auction House.

02:27:55.650 --> 02:28:02.280
auction house. So the quest is famous
in that it was so aggravating and

02:28:02.330 --> 02:28:05.990
annoying and it just became a

02:28:06.030 --> 02:28:09.350
way... It not only became a
way for me to learn from my

02:28:09.390 --> 02:28:13.370
mistakes, but because I was
very open with the fact

02:28:13.390 --> 02:28:17.210
that I didn't think it was good
and that the quest had failed, it

02:28:17.310 --> 02:28:21.270
opened the door for us at
Blizzard to be critical of

02:28:21.310 --> 02:28:25.290
our own work. Like it's always easier
if you're the first one to go out

02:28:25.330 --> 02:28:28.930
and say, "Hey, guys, I think I made
one of the shittiest quests in the

02:28:29.050 --> 02:28:32.990
game and here's why." Um, and then
it sort of challenged people to make

02:28:33.410 --> 02:28:34.770
better versions of it.

02:28:35.870 --> 02:28:39.750
- I mean, again, you continue to speak
with so much humility. But WoW

02:28:39.850 --> 02:28:43.630
turned out to be one of the
biggest games of all time

02:28:43.710 --> 02:28:47.150
both in terms of popularity,
how many players play it,

02:28:48.010 --> 02:28:55.779
revenue, and critical acclaim. And then
you rose to become a game director of WoW

02:28:55.870 --> 02:28:59.550
helping release Wrath of the
Lich King, which by many is

02:28:59.590 --> 02:29:03.570
considered to be the greatest expansion.
I mean, there's a million questions I can

02:29:03.650 --> 02:29:07.530
ask here, but maybe this is
also a good place to ask about

02:29:07.590 --> 02:29:12.380
the famous Blizzard polish.
So Blizzard as a company

02:29:13.310 --> 02:29:17.300
has historically, and you
were certainly a big part of

02:29:17.370 --> 02:29:23.190
that, delivered these games. They were
just, uh, got so many pieces right and

02:29:23.750 --> 02:29:27.710
well-functioning and
well-coordinated, and just feel

02:29:28.190 --> 02:29:32.150
finished in a way that a lot of
other games don't get right. So what

02:29:32.170 --> 02:29:35.990
does it take to take this
gigantic game, this game

02:29:36.070 --> 02:29:39.770
played by millions of people,
loved by millions of people,

02:29:39.890 --> 02:29:44.470
And deliver it in a way where
it's like it all just works?

02:29:44.530 --> 02:29:52.179
- To have a level of polish is like a studio
wide culture that has to be instilled in

02:29:52.250 --> 02:29:59.490
everybody, like no one can be satisfied
with a bug. Every game is gonna have bugs,

02:29:59.570 --> 02:30:03.150
and Blizzard games have
bugs. It's a question

02:30:03.210 --> 02:30:07.290
of, how quickly do you fix
them and with what urgency?

02:30:08.170 --> 02:30:11.130
And as players ourselves, if we're

02:30:11.250 --> 02:30:15.110
playing as much as anybody
else, we're gonna be motivated

02:30:15.830 --> 02:30:22.830
to fix the bugs. There are some really
tactical aspects to it, too. The quality

02:30:22.890 --> 02:30:26.610
assurance department at Blizzard is the

02:30:26.710 --> 02:30:30.570
best in the industry.
Like the people who come

02:30:31.110 --> 02:30:34.750
and do QA at Blizzard, they are passionate

02:30:34.790 --> 02:30:38.530
gamers. Many of them want to be
developers themselves, and they're

02:30:38.540 --> 02:30:45.870
not just doing it for a job. They do it
because they fucking love the game. And the

02:30:46.330 --> 02:30:50.179
relationship we tried to
develop between us on the

02:30:50.230 --> 02:30:53.290
development teams and QA was extremely

02:30:53.350 --> 02:30:57.190
tight. And whenever possible,
we also tried to sit

02:30:57.270 --> 02:31:01.180
as many QA members up with
the development team as

02:31:01.190 --> 02:31:04.500
as possible, depending on the logistics

02:31:04.590 --> 02:31:07.890
of... You know, in the early days,
we didn't always have the space

02:31:08.650 --> 02:31:12.330
for all of QA to sit with us. We
were very fortunate on the Overwatch

02:31:12.370 --> 02:31:16.060
team to have a large
amount of QA sitting with

02:31:16.150 --> 02:31:20.050
us, and then developing that
relationship. You know, in

02:31:20.090 --> 02:31:23.930
the early days there, there were
these fears of like, "Well, QA can't

02:31:24.030 --> 02:31:26.990
talk to the developers,"
and trying to shatter that-

02:31:27.370 --> 02:31:30.010
... of, because some of our QA members

02:31:30.890 --> 02:31:34.630
knew the game so inside out, you
would just say to them like, "Hey,

02:31:34.690 --> 02:31:38.670
dude. Just message me.
Here's my home number. Like,

02:31:38.710 --> 02:31:44.190
call me if there's a bug. If you think we're
gonna get raked over the coals on this,

02:31:45.070 --> 02:31:48.910
you gotta speak up. I don't care what
the chain of command is. Like, we gotta

02:31:48.990 --> 02:31:52.370
fix this thing." So QA was amazing.

02:31:52.410 --> 02:31:56.400
- I mean, so can you speak to
QA, quality assurance? At

02:31:56.430 --> 02:31:59.990
the peak of the craft, what does
it entail? Like you're basically

02:32:00.830 --> 02:32:04.810
experiencing the game and
trying to figure out,

02:32:04.870 --> 02:32:09.210
particular slices of that
experience that could be improved?

02:32:09.290 --> 02:32:13.190
- Yeah. People simplify
the role by just, "Oh,

02:32:13.230 --> 02:32:16.730
these guys just get to play games all day
and then, like, let us know if there's a

02:32:16.810 --> 02:32:20.450
bug." They are so
systematic in the way they

02:32:20.530 --> 02:32:24.450
test stuff. They come up
with these plans that are

02:32:24.570 --> 02:32:28.530
actually amazing of, like,
who's gonna test what.

02:32:28.630 --> 02:32:32.570
There's a lot of regression
testing that goes on.

02:32:32.730 --> 02:32:36.650
within QA there will also be
compatibility testing. The

02:32:36.690 --> 02:32:40.590
Blizzard compatibility
department was amazing.

02:32:40.630 --> 02:32:44.410
Like, they had every card,
every machine, every

02:32:44.490 --> 02:32:48.482
configuration, and they would roll through

02:32:48.492 --> 02:32:52.362
to make sure there wasn't some quirk that
was gonna come up on some video card

02:32:52.402 --> 02:32:56.252
or some motherboard that
you weren't expecting. But

02:32:56.322 --> 02:33:00.032
it was all very systematic.
It wasn't just Wild

02:33:00.142 --> 02:33:03.682
West, let's play the game.
And then as a developer

02:33:03.722 --> 02:33:07.352
interacting with QA, you would
find that there were certain

02:33:07.442 --> 02:33:13.842
specialists whether like, for example, on

02:33:13.942 --> 02:33:17.772
Overwatch, there were a
couple of players that...

02:33:17.782 --> 02:33:21.542
Like, we all were shooter players when
we were making Overwatch, but I'm

02:33:21.582 --> 02:33:28.682
not like esports level shooter player.
I'm like, you know, Gen Xer, "Remember

02:33:28.962 --> 02:33:30.602
Doom, how good I was"-

02:33:30.611 --> 02:33:30.652
- Yeah, right. Yeah, yeah.

02:33:30.652 --> 02:33:38.602
- ... type of shooter player. But we
had, you know, a couple of these QA

02:33:38.862 --> 02:33:40.942
specialists who, like,

02:33:41.842 --> 02:33:45.242
they could just snipe from 100
meters out and hit the shot every

02:33:45.302 --> 02:33:48.242
time and tell us if there
was a frame of input

02:33:48.642 --> 02:33:52.142
delay, you know? And then
you sit that person with an

02:33:52.202 --> 02:33:58.072
engineer and say, "Hey, I think
there's some input lag here."

02:33:58.082 --> 02:33:59.122
- That's amazing.

02:33:59.162 --> 02:34:02.582
- And sure enough, they'd be right. But
you have to have that relationship

02:34:02.682 --> 02:34:10.562
where the devs trust QA. Or just even
on, like World of Warcraft, they had a

02:34:10.642 --> 02:34:14.222
great relationship with QA in
that they built out a full raid

02:34:14.302 --> 02:34:18.242
team to do the raids. And then you're

02:34:18.282 --> 02:34:22.222
not only, like, looking for bugs, like, "Hey,
the dragon was supposed to fly and instead

02:34:22.262 --> 02:34:25.562
it just, like, sunk through the world
and the game crashed," which would

02:34:25.622 --> 02:34:28.822
happen. But, like, if you really value

02:34:29.282 --> 02:34:32.882
QA, you're asking them, "What
do you... Dude, what do you

02:34:33.002 --> 02:34:36.662
think? You're..." You know? Like,
"10 million people are gonna see

02:34:36.682 --> 02:34:40.472
this. Your opinion, multiply it, you

02:34:40.522 --> 02:34:44.062
know? It matters. What do you think? You know?
Are you having fun? Oh, yeah, this is cool.

02:34:44.102 --> 02:34:48.082
This isn't cool." Um, so QA was important.

02:34:48.102 --> 02:34:52.002
The other thing that was important
is the Blizzard engineering,

02:34:52.082 --> 02:34:57.992
which you have to architect
your game to be hotfixable.

02:34:58.002 --> 02:35:04.342
And what a hotfix is, games, there's a
couple ways to fix 'em. The way most

02:35:04.422 --> 02:35:08.142
of us know, 'cause all the software we
have gets a patch, you know? You have to

02:35:08.282 --> 02:35:12.262
update it. You have to download a new
version of it. Windows, you know,

02:35:12.322 --> 02:35:15.842
you get that annoying message, like,
"There's a new version of Windows." And it

02:35:15.882 --> 02:35:19.822
takes, you know, a few minutes and you
update it. You know, obviously, we

02:35:19.942 --> 02:35:23.722
patch our games and that's where
we fix a lot of bugs, but if you

02:35:23.842 --> 02:35:27.642
really wanna run a game like
Overwatch or World of Warcraft

02:35:27.682 --> 02:35:31.082
successfully, you need master level

02:35:31.162 --> 02:35:35.142
engineers who have architected
the client and server

02:35:35.182 --> 02:35:39.062
in such a way that you can hotfix
the game on a dime. And what a

02:35:39.102 --> 02:35:44.662
hotfix is, is a server patch that
no one's client has to go down for.

02:35:44.702 --> 02:35:48.302
- Mm-hmm. That's 'cause you're dealing with a
huge number of players and you discover an

02:35:48.362 --> 02:35:51.802
issue and you want to respond
to that issue really quickly.

02:35:51.882 --> 02:35:55.122
- Yeah. There's emergency
issues like something's

02:35:55.162 --> 02:35:59.062
crashing. Like, the worst
case scenario is anytime the

02:35:59.102 --> 02:36:02.671
server's crashing. Or in
Overwatch, like, a really

02:36:02.722 --> 02:36:05.562
catastrophic bug would be something
where you have to disable a

02:36:05.622 --> 02:36:09.342
hero. Like, someone found an
exploit and you have to disable a

02:36:09.402 --> 02:36:14.022
hero from the lineup. You want
to turn around that hotfix

02:36:15.702 --> 02:36:19.642
if you can in a half an hour,
get that hero back live. You

02:36:19.702 --> 02:36:23.592
might have somebody who only
plays that hero, and the only

02:36:23.662 --> 02:36:27.622
reason they're gonna play Overwatch
is because that hero's active. You

02:36:27.662 --> 02:36:32.222
don't want to wait for patches and you
want to hotfix- ... as fast as you can.

02:36:32.282 --> 02:36:36.962
- And then also to improve the game quickly
to just even settle stuff to do that.

02:36:36.972 --> 02:36:40.352
- Yeah. Players feel it.
Like, they... That's where

02:36:41.522 --> 02:36:45.462
there's this idea of, like, the love and

02:36:45.522 --> 02:36:52.632
the craftsmanship of the developer that
you can feel. Like, any, any product, you

02:36:52.702 --> 02:37:00.022
know your iPhone or Android or, like, any
computer or consumer product, you can feel

02:37:00.522 --> 02:37:04.361
when there are people who
loved it behind it and

02:37:04.442 --> 02:37:08.361
aren't just putting it out on a
shelf. And games have that as

02:37:08.421 --> 02:37:11.802
well, where you can feel the,
like, heart and soul of the the

02:37:11.882 --> 02:37:15.832
developer in, in the
thing. And some of that's,

02:37:15.842 --> 02:37:19.582
like, the joy and delight of, like,
that there's a cow level, right? That

02:37:20.022 --> 02:37:25.392
that's... You know, you can feel the
humanity of the development team-

02:37:25.392 --> 02:37:28.442
... through that. But
another part of that is,

02:37:28.482 --> 02:37:32.382
like, do they clean up their
fucking yard, you know? Does this

02:37:32.482 --> 02:37:35.952
game work? Is it... And it's
not just the bugs and the

02:37:36.062 --> 02:37:39.362
crashes. It's, like, when
balance gets wacky and

02:37:39.582 --> 02:37:43.432
stupid and, you know, suddenly
everybody's a barbarian and

02:37:43.462 --> 02:37:47.442
whirlwinding and no one else will
play anything else. You're like, "We

02:37:47.502 --> 02:37:49.282
should probably fix that," you know?

02:37:50.022 --> 02:37:54.722
- Oh, those were the days. I sadly
was the barbarian whirlwind guy.

02:37:54.782 --> 02:37:56.122
- One-handed.

02:37:56.142 --> 02:38:00.082
- It was... Yeah, it
brought so much joy. So a

02:38:00.122 --> 02:38:05.702
lot of people modern day think of
you as Jeff from the Overwatch team.

02:38:05.762 --> 02:38:09.662
- My name is Jeff from the Overwatch
team. I'm Jeff from the Overwatch

02:38:09.722 --> 02:38:12.022
team. I'm Jeff from the Overwatch team.

02:38:12.062 --> 02:38:15.982
- But y'all must have forgot, you
were the game director of WoW

02:38:16.222 --> 02:38:20.142
in an era when WoW was
one of the biggest games

02:38:20.202 --> 02:38:24.082
in the world. Just, you
know, looking back,

02:38:24.122 --> 02:38:27.802
what wisdom can you draw
from that time when

02:38:28.402 --> 02:38:32.242
you got to experience
this era of gaming that

02:38:32.282 --> 02:38:37.602
changed gaming forever, where it's millions
of people playing this video game?

02:38:37.682 --> 02:38:44.142
- It was my first game I worked on, and
I joined it as this entry level dude.

02:38:44.702 --> 02:38:50.292
I still have my offer letter from
Blizzard, which was for 35K a year.

02:38:50.302 --> 02:38:57.742
You know, that's what I was making.
And, um... Very shortly after

02:38:57.842 --> 02:39:01.522
WoW shipped, you know, Allen left his

02:39:01.662 --> 02:39:05.182
lead before the beta, or
like right around the

02:39:05.222 --> 02:39:13.332
beta, and then Rob took over as the lead
designer, and then he left the team very

02:39:13.342 --> 02:39:16.622
shortly after WoW shipped
to go start StarCraft

02:39:16.782 --> 02:39:24.642
II. And he put myself and Tom Chilton
in charge. Uh, Tom is a designer

02:39:24.702 --> 02:39:32.022
who... He was a great partner of mine and
a great leader and he, he actually came

02:39:32.062 --> 02:39:35.462
from Ultima Online. And so
I always looked up to Tom

02:39:36.282 --> 02:39:42.522
because he had a lot more experience
than I did. And this is like early 2005,

02:39:44.202 --> 02:39:48.032
the world was on fire, the
servers were barely running-

02:39:48.202 --> 02:39:54.322
... WoW was just, had taken off like
gangbusters, and they basically put me

02:39:54.402 --> 02:39:58.102
and Tom in charge of WoW. And at the

02:39:58.162 --> 02:40:02.042
time they promoted me, my title...
I didn't even have a lead title,

02:40:02.102 --> 02:40:05.942
my title was Senior Game Designer. And

02:40:06.382 --> 02:40:11.122
Tom and I were running the
design of WoW at that time. So

02:40:12.942 --> 02:40:16.812
I thought it was totally normal, and I

02:40:16.822 --> 02:40:20.802
thought what we were
experiencing with WoW was just

02:40:20.882 --> 02:40:24.742
normal for making a video game
because it was the first video game

02:40:24.922 --> 02:40:32.032
that I had worked on. Mm-hmm. Um, I
thought it was the funnest joyride

02:40:33.682 --> 02:40:37.502
because we were working on WoW,
we were still working insane

02:40:37.622 --> 02:40:41.482
hours- and then I'd get home,

02:40:42.402 --> 02:40:47.022
eat dinner, and then me and my
wife would log in and play WoW,

02:40:48.082 --> 02:40:51.122
you know, for four hours, and then I'd

02:40:51.842 --> 02:40:55.582
go in the next day and I'd work...
And it was just this... My

02:40:55.662 --> 02:40:59.262
whole life was World of Warcraft. And I

02:40:59.422 --> 02:41:03.342
loved it. Like I loved everything
from, you know, the creative

02:41:03.442 --> 02:41:07.272
meetings with Chris Metzen and
just what an inspiration and

02:41:07.322 --> 02:41:12.422
muse he was, down to the
simplest, dumbest design

02:41:14.162 --> 02:41:17.962
stuff that like we as game
designers, like, you wanna

02:41:18.022 --> 02:41:24.682
talk about why a button is in the lower-left
versus lower-right and what does that

02:41:24.782 --> 02:41:31.022
mean? That's like two hours
of discussion. And is there a

02:41:31.042 --> 02:41:37.692
better way? Like the 10,000
minutiae problems- were

02:41:37.702 --> 02:41:41.542
thrilling to me. And then
also the big disasters.

02:41:41.602 --> 02:41:45.532
Like the big... I had in the early days

02:41:45.562 --> 02:41:49.242
of WoW, we didn't really have all the
processes in place for, like, how to

02:41:49.282 --> 02:41:53.082
deal with being a successful
online game, and I literally

02:41:53.122 --> 02:41:56.612
had GMs, like game masters,
these are customer support

02:41:56.742 --> 02:42:01.782
guys, calling my home phone
at 3:00 in the morning.

02:42:02.602 --> 02:42:05.042
Like, I remember this
one time there was some

02:42:05.982 --> 02:42:09.882
faction token in Stranglethorn Vale and

02:42:09.902 --> 02:42:13.682
they figured out a way to
exploit it, and this GM

02:42:13.762 --> 02:42:17.682
calls me panicked, it's 3:00
in the morning. He's like,

02:42:17.692 --> 02:42:21.662
"I'm just spawning..." Uh,
what, what did we call 'em? Uh,

02:42:21.702 --> 02:42:25.442
Guardians of Blizzard. They were these
giant infernals that we just made that

02:42:25.522 --> 02:42:29.502
instantly death touched anything.
We used to have them when we

02:42:29.522 --> 02:42:33.502
were in the beta, like often the distance
of places players weren't supposed to

02:42:33.542 --> 02:42:37.382
get in case they cheated their
way there. And this GM is just

02:42:37.462 --> 02:42:41.182
spawning them all over
Stranglethorn Vale because

02:42:41.222 --> 02:42:45.172
he's worried because the players
are exploiting. It's like 3:00

02:42:45.182 --> 02:42:49.082
in the morning and I'm talking in hushed
tones because my wife is sleeping right

02:42:49.242 --> 02:42:53.122
next to the bed. I'm doing this 'cause
it was actually like before the cell

02:42:53.182 --> 02:42:56.602
phone days when I actually had
a landline. But that's just

02:42:56.662 --> 02:43:00.582
how... And I loved it.
I loved the thrill of

02:43:00.642 --> 02:43:04.472
those big moments, the
minutiae. And I felt

02:43:04.502 --> 02:43:08.462
like through the running
WoW Live, which was

02:43:08.482 --> 02:43:12.322
me and Tom together with an
amazing team, we kind of learned

02:43:12.382 --> 02:43:19.662
how to be the WoW team. And putting
WoW in a box and shipping it was like

02:43:19.982 --> 02:43:26.962
only chapter one in a 12-chapter book
essentially. And that first how to run the

02:43:27.062 --> 02:43:30.852
game, how to patch it, what type
of content, how to deal with

02:43:30.902 --> 02:43:34.242
emergencies, what should
our customer support be

02:43:34.302 --> 02:43:37.882
like. I mean, we would debate
should we have a launcher or

02:43:37.942 --> 02:43:41.582
not. You know, in the early days, the
only reason the launcher existed in

02:43:41.622 --> 02:43:48.242
WoW was to run anti-cheat on your machine.
And we had a moment where we figured

02:43:48.282 --> 02:43:49.122
out how to put that

02:43:50.222 --> 02:43:53.982
into the game and out of the launcher.
And it was the first time I ever

02:43:54.062 --> 02:43:57.852
really had an in-depth conversation with Mike
Morhaime. He's like, "You gotta bring the

02:43:57.922 --> 02:44:01.842
launcher back, guys." We're like, "Why?"
He's like, "There's no better way

02:44:01.962 --> 02:44:07.202
for us to talk to our players." And I
remember trying to hide the launcher.

02:44:08.002 --> 02:44:11.942
And to this day, Mike was right.
Like, that launcher turned out to be

02:44:11.982 --> 02:44:15.822
the best thing we ever had.
That's essentially what

02:44:15.982 --> 02:44:19.822
Battle.net has morphed into
these days. But all those

02:44:19.862 --> 02:44:23.402
decisions and when it
came time to make Burning

02:44:23.462 --> 02:44:27.242
Crusade, you know, at that
point, Tom and I were leads. We

02:44:27.262 --> 02:44:31.202
were full, they had actually promoted
us. There was, there were two

02:44:31.222 --> 02:44:37.852
big exoduses of groups that quit
Blizzard, they were disenfranchised

02:44:38.802 --> 02:44:42.112
if you can believe it. Like
we just shipped World of

02:44:42.202 --> 02:44:46.062
Warcraft and this whole group just
walked out the door. I was actually

02:44:46.122 --> 02:44:49.642
sitting, my, my desk faced Morhaime's

02:44:49.722 --> 02:44:53.662
office, and I watched them all go in
and quit, and they were the group

02:44:53.762 --> 02:44:57.538
that formed Carbine....
which made the game

02:44:57.638 --> 02:45:00.918
WildStar. Ended up taking them 10 years to

02:45:00.978 --> 02:45:04.028
make, and they were just
really unhappy with World of

02:45:04.118 --> 02:45:07.818
Warcraft, and they were unhappy with,

02:45:07.918 --> 02:45:11.808
um... I don't know what they were
unhappy with. They were unhappy

02:45:11.858 --> 02:45:16.858
enough to walk out the door
right after we had shipped WoW.

02:45:16.978 --> 02:45:20.868
- That's incredible. Like, what is it? Just because
they put their heart and soul into the game and

02:45:20.898 --> 02:45:23.398
they maybe get exhausted
in a certain kind of way?

02:45:23.438 --> 02:45:27.868
- Yeah, and I don't want to... It's not fair
of me to speak on their behalf. I think

02:45:29.218 --> 02:45:32.908
they were promised some compensation
that they didn't immediately

02:45:32.998 --> 02:45:37.738
see. I don't know if the game... Like,
here's the weird part when you make a game.

02:45:38.938 --> 02:45:42.518
When you come up with
the idea and you start

02:45:42.578 --> 02:45:46.558
pitching it to people, that's the
best the game is ever gonna be,

02:45:47.418 --> 02:45:51.138
and then you work on it. Like,
you know, games I worked on

02:45:51.198 --> 02:45:59.218
take five years, you know? Overwatch was
two and a half, three years. Every day you

02:45:59.278 --> 02:46:04.798
get close to ship, the
imagination of the ideal game

02:46:05.738 --> 02:46:09.298
gets farther and farther from
the reality, and you're always

02:46:10.138 --> 02:46:13.818
shipping this, like,
greatly sacrificed thing

02:46:13.898 --> 02:46:18.148
that nowhere near matches the imagination-

02:46:18.418 --> 02:46:24.118
... of the inception of the idea, so you
become disenfranchised with the concept.

02:46:24.198 --> 02:46:28.158
- So in some sense, you're shipping...
You're constantly in a state

02:46:28.178 --> 02:46:32.078
of disappointment. You're
basically shipping

02:46:32.158 --> 02:46:37.248
a lesser thing than you've
been dreaming about.

02:46:37.278 --> 02:46:37.348
- Yes.

02:46:37.348 --> 02:46:41.218
- You're doing less and less and less, saying
no and no, and cutting, and all that kind of

02:46:41.258 --> 02:46:45.058
stuff. Yeah, it's difficult, psychologically
difficult, but nevertheless, the result when you

02:46:45.178 --> 02:46:49.038
zoom out, it's one of the greatest games
of all time that millions of people

02:46:49.078 --> 02:46:54.328
played for thousands of hours.
It's just... What... Did

02:46:54.378 --> 02:46:58.188
it... Did you ever have an
experience, a realization how

02:46:58.358 --> 02:47:01.978
huge WoW was in terms of not, like,

02:47:02.058 --> 02:47:05.918
statistics on the server and so on,
but the cultural impact it had?

02:47:05.938 --> 02:47:11.958
- The first time was the first
BlizzCon, which was in

02:47:12.118 --> 02:47:18.738
2005. So when WoW shipped and this
is so weird to tell people, but

02:47:18.838 --> 02:47:26.338
on the team not everyone, but a lot
of us were very demoralized after

02:47:26.458 --> 02:47:32.958
WoW shipped. There were, there were
all sorts of issues with the servers

02:47:34.078 --> 02:47:37.808
because the game did way more successful

02:47:38.298 --> 02:47:42.158
than we expected it to
do and the server load

02:47:42.198 --> 02:47:45.878
was just nuts. Like, we were
just... We were doing our best to

02:47:45.938 --> 02:47:49.918
hire database programmers, you
know, 'cause we just didn't

02:47:49.998 --> 02:47:57.568
know how to deal with the sheer scope of
the game. But when you're an individual

02:47:57.678 --> 02:48:01.598
like... And at that time, like I
mentioned, there were multiple exoduses of

02:48:01.658 --> 02:48:05.438
people who quit Blizzard.
They went and formed a

02:48:05.498 --> 02:48:13.208
couple notable studios. One was Carbine
the other was Red 5. And we lost, like,

02:48:13.258 --> 02:48:17.158
kind of our core people.
Like, when Red 5 started,

02:48:17.198 --> 02:48:21.098
that was our team leader, that was
Mark Kern and our art director,

02:48:21.138 --> 02:48:24.978
Bill Petras, they quit. When Carbine

02:48:25.018 --> 02:48:28.827
started, it was, I think all of
our animators and some of our

02:48:28.898 --> 02:48:32.878
best programmers and... Like,
it's really demoralizing when you

02:48:32.958 --> 02:48:36.288
lose team members like
that, but then we were also

02:48:36.318 --> 02:48:40.238
underwater. Like, the
servers aren't running,

02:48:40.338 --> 02:48:43.038
We're not able to keep up with demand,

02:48:44.538 --> 02:48:48.278
and we had to start putting patches
out, and now we're making patches

02:48:48.358 --> 02:48:52.218
like... For a while we
had one animator who

02:48:52.338 --> 02:48:55.958
stuck around, and then eventually
he left also, but you're doing

02:48:56.018 --> 02:49:03.518
like, okay, we gotta now do a patch without
an animator. A lot of our art team was

02:49:03.558 --> 02:49:07.298
gone at that point, and you're
trying to keep the ship afloat

02:49:07.498 --> 02:49:11.338
and the morale was just in
the shitter. Like, everybody

02:49:11.458 --> 02:49:15.238
felt very down on Team Two, the

02:49:15.298 --> 02:49:22.118
WoW team was called Team Two, and that we
had somehow failed. And during that time,

02:49:23.058 --> 02:49:30.378
there was this idea to do BlizzCon,
and the way that started was

02:49:30.438 --> 02:49:34.418
EverQuest had done these, like, meetups
because they knew it was, like, a big

02:49:34.478 --> 02:49:38.338
guild social game, and people would
get together at like some hotel

02:49:38.498 --> 02:49:44.448
ballroom and you'd sit with your
guild at like a banquet room table.

02:49:44.518 --> 02:49:48.018
And to give credit where credit's due,
I remember sitting in the meeting

02:49:48.158 --> 02:49:51.518
for what was to become
BlizzCon, it was Pardo who

02:49:51.598 --> 02:49:55.467
said, "Blizzard's bigger
than that. We're not just

02:49:55.538 --> 02:49:59.478
one game, and I know everybody's
focused on World of Warcraft

02:49:59.498 --> 02:50:01.467
right now, we should do BlizzCon."

02:50:02.418 --> 02:50:06.198
And at the time, we had a game
called StarCraft Ghost was in

02:50:06.258 --> 02:50:10.218
development, and that was getting
ready to show, and there was

02:50:10.358 --> 02:50:14.098
Frozen Throne, which was the
expansion to Warcraft III, but,

02:50:14.118 --> 02:50:17.858
like, we knew we were gonna make
StarCraft II. And then there was

02:50:18.098 --> 02:50:21.798
a lot of motion happening with
Blizzard North, which is a whole

02:50:21.918 --> 02:50:27.158
separate story, but there was like,
hey, we could really do a cool show-

02:50:27.168 --> 02:50:30.078
... that's this BlizzCon
thing. And at first,

02:50:31.038 --> 02:50:34.478
we kind of announced it and it just was
crickets. You know when you're, like,

02:50:34.538 --> 02:50:38.338
excited about something, you're like,
"Man, everybody's gonna love. Like, we're

02:50:38.348 --> 02:50:41.918
doing BlizzCon," and everybody's
kinda like, "Crickets. What's

02:50:41.958 --> 02:50:45.528
BlizzCon? Who cares?" And we're

02:50:45.678 --> 02:50:49.158
idiots, we're reading the forums, and
the forums are just flaming us all the

02:50:49.198 --> 02:50:52.958
time, like, "There's lag
on this server and can't

02:50:53.018 --> 02:50:56.318
log into that server." And that's,
that was our perspective of what was

02:50:56.418 --> 02:51:00.282
happening. And then,
like I said, give Mike

02:51:00.322 --> 02:51:06.612
Morhaime credit where credit's
due. He kept us committed to that

02:51:06.662 --> 02:51:10.602
launcher, and they put the BlizzCon
tickets on the launcher, which

02:51:10.612 --> 02:51:14.522
they hadn't done before. It was on the
website. And so everybody who logged

02:51:14.602 --> 02:51:18.142
into World of Warcraft suddenly
got this like, "Hey, we're

02:51:18.562 --> 02:51:25.082
doing BlizzCon in Anaheim, do you
wanna come?" Sold out instant. Like,

02:51:25.682 --> 02:51:33.402
instantly sold out. And when I showed
up at that show, it... One of the

02:51:33.442 --> 02:51:38.532
most emotional things in my life. It
was nothing but an outpouring of love.

02:51:39.702 --> 02:51:43.362
And up until that point, your
perception was, because you're

02:51:43.502 --> 02:51:50.862
just reading online and it was... The
perception is such hatred, because

02:51:50.902 --> 02:51:54.682
people who are passionate
online, they express

02:51:54.722 --> 02:51:58.662
themselves in the harshest ways
'cause it gets attention. You know,

02:51:58.682 --> 02:52:02.602
that's the lesson I should've
learned from my early days.

02:52:02.702 --> 02:52:07.402
And it's such an unfortunate thing, because
then you met these people in person

02:52:08.402 --> 02:52:12.262
and they loved World of Warcraft.

02:52:12.282 --> 02:52:16.142
And all they wanted to do was talk
about World of Warcraft and hear about

02:52:16.202 --> 02:52:22.402
what was coming next and be around other
people who loved World of Warcraft, and-

02:52:22.442 --> 02:52:25.922
- It's incredible. It's a fascinating theme,
to me, about human nature, and it's

02:52:26.022 --> 02:52:29.882
absolutely true, and I wish there was a
thing that could be solved. But then again,

02:52:29.942 --> 02:52:32.402
maybe not. Maybe that's
just the way it is. But in

02:52:32.442 --> 02:52:36.182
person, all of the people that are

02:52:36.322 --> 02:52:39.502
passionate about a particular topic,
and whatever that topic is, it could be

02:52:39.562 --> 02:52:46.082
games it could be at conferences, technical
conferences, they're all mostly full of

02:52:46.142 --> 02:52:50.082
love. And just the way they talk
about stuff, they nerd out.

02:52:50.122 --> 02:52:52.822
Even the disagreements
are drenched in this,

02:52:54.422 --> 02:52:58.312
Respect and appreciation and
love for the game, for the

02:52:58.382 --> 02:53:02.282
game, for the topic. And online,
you're right, I don't know if

02:53:02.322 --> 02:53:06.262
it's because of popularity
or clicks or so on, but

02:53:06.322 --> 02:53:12.562
it's just the way of speaking on
the internet is more mockery and-

02:53:12.622 --> 02:53:13.662
- Cynical.

02:53:13.722 --> 02:53:20.682
- If you say, "I love this thing. Here's
an apple. I love apples," or, "I love

02:53:21.162 --> 02:53:27.502
bananas. I love fr..." Like, "I love
X," whatever. You just get made fun of.

02:53:27.522 --> 02:53:31.162
You get... And so the lesson
you learn from that is,

02:53:31.822 --> 02:53:35.062
"Well, I'm just not going
to speak up when I love

02:53:35.202 --> 02:53:38.402
something. I'm going to
instead speak up when

02:53:38.502 --> 02:53:41.932
I, maybe how much I hate another
thing that's similar to it."

02:53:41.982 --> 02:53:45.502
Or maybe join in when we're
making fun of a particular quirky

02:53:45.622 --> 02:53:48.842
thing, about, "Don't you hate
it when bananas are too ripe or

02:53:48.882 --> 02:53:52.772
too..." Versus like not
saying the, calling out the

02:53:52.862 --> 02:53:58.822
elephant in the room is, "We're all gathered
here today 'cause we love the thing."

02:53:58.882 --> 02:54:02.342
It's interesting. It's that aspect of the
internet that I think is jarring to a lot of

02:54:02.382 --> 02:54:06.842
people depending on the game, but if
you go to Discord or Reddit or so on,

02:54:07.722 --> 02:54:11.662
in the communities that love a
particular video game, there's a... If

02:54:11.702 --> 02:54:12.722
you're not used to it,

02:54:13.562 --> 02:54:17.382
and I don't often go, so when I
go it's like, "Wow, there's a lot

02:54:17.442 --> 02:54:21.122
of, like, pretty intense kinda
mockery and derision and so

02:54:21.222 --> 02:54:24.702
on." But you get used to it pretty quick and you
understand it. I just, I wish there was more

02:54:24.782 --> 02:54:25.282
love.

02:54:25.302 --> 02:54:32.232
- I feel bad because I played a role in
the earliest development of some of

02:54:32.282 --> 02:54:40.022
that online culture. It really was social
media before it was called social media.

02:54:40.122 --> 02:54:43.582
You know, I ran a... Uh,
I actually, I had this

02:54:43.622 --> 02:54:47.282
reputation for being
edgier than I really was.

02:54:47.382 --> 02:54:51.162
Um, there were a couple
notable posts that survived

02:54:51.342 --> 02:54:57.912
30 years that people like to look back
on but they don't look back on the ones

02:54:58.042 --> 02:55:01.762
where I'm just being chill. And that's

02:55:01.822 --> 02:55:05.782
unfortunate. I think a lot
as a game designer about the

02:55:05.902 --> 02:55:09.682
design of social media. And unfortunately,

02:55:10.102 --> 02:55:14.182
social media in general is
designed in such a way where

02:55:15.622 --> 02:55:19.322
the maximum hyperbole works,

02:55:20.202 --> 02:55:27.622
and that's how you get the most
points is by being max hyperbolic.

02:55:27.642 --> 02:55:31.542
And usually, unfortunately,
it's more in the

02:55:31.582 --> 02:55:35.492
negative direction than the
positive direction. You know, if

02:55:35.702 --> 02:55:43.162
I say, "That's a pretty
nice mug. I've seen nicer,

02:55:43.202 --> 02:55:47.122
but I like this one,"
no one's interested in

02:55:47.182 --> 02:55:50.022
that. I have to either love this thing, or

02:55:50.202 --> 02:55:53.282
better, this thing's a
crime against humanity-

02:55:53.362 --> 02:55:58.732
... in some way. And it's
very self- reinforcing

02:55:59.682 --> 02:56:03.272
and everybody sort of feeds into it and-

02:56:03.322 --> 02:56:07.052
- Especially when you're young. I got to see
this kinda interesting thing. So I was

02:56:07.122 --> 02:56:10.882
at I, I spent, that's what we're
talking about, you're from Pasadena, so

02:56:10.942 --> 02:56:13.962
I've been spending a
lot of time in Caltech

02:56:14.142 --> 02:56:21.932
and working on robots, and we get to see
students come in from high school. Uh,

02:56:22.102 --> 02:56:25.942
undergraduates come in and,
like a tour, hang out with the

02:56:25.962 --> 02:56:29.722
robots. And middle school also.
And the interesting thing

02:56:30.002 --> 02:56:36.982
you see, the younger that they are,
the more prevalent this effect, which

02:56:37.062 --> 02:56:42.342
is all of them are kind of
afraid to show that they think a

02:56:42.422 --> 02:56:48.302
thing is awesome. They're all... You could
just feel they're checking, "Is it okay?"

02:56:48.442 --> 02:56:51.862
So they're, they're kind of
like the default mode is

02:56:51.902 --> 02:56:55.692
whatever, this, everything is
stupid, this is stupid. You

02:56:55.722 --> 02:56:59.622
know, that, 'cause that's
the safe place to be. It's

02:56:59.702 --> 02:57:03.642
a real act of vulnerability. I would say
it's an act of courage, especially for a

02:57:03.702 --> 02:57:07.632
young person, to be like, "Holy
shit, that's awesome." Like, I'm

02:57:07.662 --> 02:57:11.602
gonna, if I think this is awesome, I'm gonna
be the nerd, I'm gonna take the risk and

02:57:11.682 --> 02:57:15.482
be made fun of for saying,
"I love this," in that case,

02:57:15.562 --> 02:57:18.962
it's, "I love this robot."
So that's a actual

02:57:18.982 --> 02:57:22.082
psychological effect that also young
people are dealing with, in-person

02:57:22.182 --> 02:57:26.022
also. So I think, I just
wanna say, for young

02:57:26.042 --> 02:57:29.422
people listening to
this, be vulnerable, be

02:57:29.502 --> 02:57:33.422
courageous and say you love a thing
if you love a thing. And do more

02:57:33.462 --> 02:57:37.182
of that on the internet, I
think. Um, I think people

02:57:37.762 --> 02:57:41.562
make up the internet, people build the
internet, and young people, more than

02:57:41.622 --> 02:57:43.602
anybody else, define the
future of the internet. So

02:57:44.762 --> 02:57:48.102
put more love out there in the world.
If you love a video game, if you love

02:57:48.242 --> 02:57:50.182
Overwatch, say you love it.

02:57:50.282 --> 02:57:54.262
- I couldn't agree more. You know,
as somebody who's taken a lot of

02:57:54.322 --> 02:57:57.642
heat online, like any game
developer, you just get

02:57:58.302 --> 02:58:01.562
destroyed. Doing what you do,
you must get destroyed, you

02:58:01.642 --> 02:58:06.402
know? And it doesn't matter,
you get 100 compliments,

02:58:07.802 --> 02:58:11.202
it's the one, you know,
you're... And you're

02:58:11.602 --> 02:58:15.502
supposed to read it and supposed to be
fine with it and have it not affect you.

02:58:15.522 --> 02:58:19.362
It'll stay with you for years,
you know? I have those. And I

02:58:19.422 --> 02:58:23.382
think of it, like the cheesy, the
cheesy way I think about it is

02:58:23.422 --> 02:58:31.102
like, is there some kind of social
Darwinism going on? And my big worry is

02:58:31.162 --> 02:58:38.862
that there are creators... Like, now
being a creator of anything, writer,

02:58:38.922 --> 02:58:42.742
musician, you know, make online
videos, whatever- whatever

02:58:42.862 --> 02:58:49.882
creator means to you, make games. Now
part of the skillset is being able to

02:58:50.062 --> 02:58:56.322
weather like a fire hose of criticism
like the world has never seen. And

02:58:56.562 --> 02:59:03.442
I make up these scenarios in my
head of like, would van Gogh have

02:59:03.522 --> 02:59:08.642
existed if, you know, Reddit and

02:59:09.622 --> 02:59:13.422
all these things were out there
commenting on... Like, how many

02:59:13.562 --> 02:59:20.782
people were able to communicate with
Beethoven in his lifetime, or in a

02:59:20.822 --> 02:59:27.902
week? Like, how many influences could
comment on his music directly to him?

02:59:27.942 --> 02:59:32.582
Versus like if I want to
insult Brad Pitt right now,

02:59:33.442 --> 02:59:37.482
I can just go on 10 different
devices and do it. And it's like

02:59:38.822 --> 02:59:45.962
that level of access is very dangerous,
and I worry that there is a whole group of

02:59:46.042 --> 02:59:49.282
people who's receding
from us that will never

02:59:49.462 --> 02:59:53.202
see the brilliance, and
they're being shut out

02:59:53.262 --> 03:00:00.502
by the negativity. There's a very
real example, was Jay Wilson, who I

03:00:00.542 --> 03:00:06.862
think is one of the great design minds,
who was the game director of Diablo

03:00:06.982 --> 03:00:10.962
III. And he took so much heat,

03:00:11.062 --> 03:00:14.622
it just affected him to the
point where he essentially

03:00:14.642 --> 03:00:18.242
retired from making games.
Went and, you know, wrote

03:00:18.282 --> 03:00:22.142
novels. I was very happy for him
because, you know, I'm glad he

03:00:22.202 --> 03:00:25.862
found his place, and I think
he's getting back into

03:00:25.902 --> 03:00:29.362
making games now. But we lost, we

03:00:29.382 --> 03:00:33.231
essentially... Like, think how
many people loved Diablo III

03:00:33.562 --> 03:00:36.502
and played the shit out of Diablo III.

03:00:36.692 --> 03:00:41.302
And Jay is one of the people
you have to thank for that. And

03:00:41.362 --> 03:00:45.002
yet that community basically
removed him from making

03:00:45.102 --> 03:00:50.582
games for like 10, 15 years,
and it feels criminal to me.

03:00:50.662 --> 03:00:54.182
- Yeah, absolutely. They... So
this is a call to action,

03:00:54.282 --> 03:00:58.082
again. People out there,
support, especially young

03:00:58.122 --> 03:01:02.082
creators, support them.
They need it. Like you

03:01:02.162 --> 03:01:06.002
think negativity has no
cost, but it does. You're

03:01:06.042 --> 03:01:09.852
robbing the world of some of
the great creations. And also,

03:01:09.942 --> 03:01:16.342
allow creators to suck and to
improve. Because that's what the

03:01:16.362 --> 03:01:20.211
process of creation is
like, is to take risks. To

03:01:20.562 --> 03:01:25.522
and take risks meaning being
vulnerable, being cringe.

03:01:25.531 --> 03:01:29.382
To doing the thing that like,
the embarrassing failure

03:01:29.502 --> 03:01:33.402
where you're standing there on, you

03:01:33.442 --> 03:01:37.422
know, in a in a silly clown
outfit, on stage, dancing, and

03:01:37.462 --> 03:01:41.442
nobody, and nobody's laughing.
And it's a, it's... Comedians

03:01:41.502 --> 03:01:45.242
go through this all the time, when... They
talk about this all the time, when they bomb,

03:01:45.302 --> 03:01:49.202
right? They, the act just
doesn't work, and you have to go

03:01:49.242 --> 03:01:53.142
through that. And you have to,
you have to support the creators

03:01:53.162 --> 03:01:58.532
through that journey. In order to have
great things, we need to support those

03:01:58.622 --> 03:02:02.432
folks. So, after shipping
WoW, Wrath of the

03:02:02.482 --> 03:02:06.202
Lich King, again, many consider
it to be one of the great

03:02:06.242 --> 03:02:10.062
expansions for WoW, you stepped
down as WoW's game director and

03:02:10.162 --> 03:02:16.912
switched to developing Titan. This epic

03:02:18.202 --> 03:02:21.882
huge game that promised to be
the, sort of the MMO to end

03:02:22.082 --> 03:02:29.022
all MMOs. Um, I mean, it's kind of a
legendary vision for a game, right? It's

03:02:29.082 --> 03:02:36.222
gigantic. With a lot of, like you said,
a brilliant team, a team that's now

03:02:36.232 --> 03:02:42.962
hardened and knows how to do a great game.
But it was canceled after seven years in

03:02:43.002 --> 03:02:47.762
development. So, tell me, what was the
vision of the game and what happened?

03:02:47.862 --> 03:02:51.502
- Sure. So, as we were experiencing

03:02:51.602 --> 03:02:55.522
success with World of Warcraft,
there was this concept in

03:02:55.562 --> 03:02:58.452
the studio that WoW wasn't
gonna last forever.

03:02:58.922 --> 03:03:02.902
WoW would be maybe successful for
five years, and eventually kind of

03:03:03.102 --> 03:03:06.894
age out.And the studio would be real, in

03:03:06.934 --> 03:03:10.414
real trouble if we didn't
have another massively

03:03:10.454 --> 03:03:16.734
multiplayer online game sort of
waiting in the wings. So starting

03:03:16.814 --> 03:03:28.254
around, I wanna say 2006, maybe 2005,
um, the talk of starting a team

03:03:29.814 --> 03:03:36.094
really picked up momentum, and we
were working on Burning Crusade.

03:03:36.954 --> 03:03:40.874
Uh, Rob Pardo took the
helm to start sort of

03:03:40.934 --> 03:03:47.914
Titan development. We didn't even really
have a team then. And I remember,

03:03:47.954 --> 03:03:51.934
being like embroiled in
Burning Crusade and going to

03:03:51.974 --> 03:03:55.884
Titan meetings, and Rob pulled
a group, you know, from

03:03:55.894 --> 03:03:59.774
kind of across the company, and
we started talking about what

03:03:59.834 --> 03:04:04.914
this next MMO could be and
when it would get going. And

03:04:06.074 --> 03:04:09.854
eventually, it started
in earnest, like real

03:04:09.874 --> 03:04:13.594
development, around 2007.
The first team members

03:04:13.714 --> 03:04:17.354
joined, and it was a real
ambitious project, including like

03:04:17.414 --> 03:04:21.274
building a new engine from
scratch. I think maybe the

03:04:21.374 --> 03:04:27.774
first team member was a guy named
John LaFleur, who was just a

03:04:27.794 --> 03:04:31.454
stellar game programmer, and the engine,

03:04:31.474 --> 03:04:35.214
which ultimately failed for
Titan ended up becoming

03:04:35.874 --> 03:04:39.634
the engine for Overwatch, which
is a great success story for

03:04:39.694 --> 03:04:44.433
him. And the idea behind the
game, it was gonna take place

03:04:45.294 --> 03:04:50.254
in future Earth, and the players
played as secret agents.

03:04:51.634 --> 03:04:55.034
And by day, they all had day jobs,

03:04:55.934 --> 03:05:02.954
and by night, they went off and did cool
secret agent stuff. And the secret agent

03:05:03.074 --> 03:05:08.594
stuff was very first-person shooter,
but over-the-top abilities,

03:05:09.654 --> 03:05:13.334
Like you would see in Overwatch,
because that's where they came from.

03:05:14.774 --> 03:05:18.594
And the by day stuff, we were
gonna let you run businesses.

03:05:18.694 --> 03:05:25.394
We took a lot of influence from games
like Animal Crossing, Harvest Moon, the

03:05:25.554 --> 03:05:32.994
Sims. We had a brilliant game designer
and game director named Matt Brown, who

03:05:33.114 --> 03:05:36.274
was the creative director
on the Sims. He came

03:05:36.354 --> 03:05:42.554
over. And so we had this vision that
there was gonna be all this like daytime

03:05:43.654 --> 03:05:47.374
business house stuff. You could build a

03:05:47.394 --> 03:05:50.974
house. You could live
in a neighborhood. Um,

03:05:52.174 --> 03:05:56.054
and beyond that, there
was also a vision on the

03:05:56.194 --> 03:05:59.794
technical side, game design
and technical side, that

03:05:59.894 --> 03:06:03.774
unlike World of Warcraft,
which the modern day term for

03:06:03.834 --> 03:06:07.824
it is that it's sharded.
Mm-hmm. So meaning people

03:06:07.824 --> 03:06:10.234
play on different realms
or servers. In a WoW

03:06:10.374 --> 03:06:13.984
server, I don't, I haven't been
on that team in a very long

03:06:14.014 --> 03:06:17.634
time, but back in the day, you
might have 5,000 people on a WoW

03:06:17.714 --> 03:06:20.314
server before they'd have
to spin up another WoW

03:06:20.414 --> 03:06:24.334
server. The big idea behind Titan is that

03:06:24.854 --> 03:06:28.794
everybody would play on one
server. It was a one server,

03:06:28.854 --> 03:06:36.324
one world game, and the world was massive.
It was gonna take place in future Earth,

03:06:37.314 --> 03:06:41.134
and we were literally building like,
we had what we called Bay City,

03:06:41.174 --> 03:06:44.214
which was San Francisco. We had, you know,

03:06:44.274 --> 03:06:48.174
Hollywood, and then we had
to build all of California

03:06:48.234 --> 03:06:52.674
between that, and we also wanted
to build like Cairo and London.

03:06:53.654 --> 03:06:56.974
And there's this realization of
like, how do we connect all of

03:06:57.054 --> 03:07:04.254
these? The game had driving in it,
like full-blown, like GTA-style

03:07:04.334 --> 03:07:11.614
driving. It was such a
gargantuan, huge undertaking

03:07:11.674 --> 03:07:18.474
with a brand new engine, a
brand new team, a brand new IP,

03:07:18.534 --> 03:07:22.034
intellectual property, you
know, setting, which we

03:07:22.074 --> 03:07:25.433
really wrestled over. Like,
the amount that the IP

03:07:25.634 --> 03:07:29.554
just, you know, trying to figure
out, like, are there aliens or

03:07:29.654 --> 03:07:33.254
not aliens, you know? Like,
all that sounds kinda dumb and

03:07:33.454 --> 03:07:37.114
fun, but when you're building
a game, like you, especially

03:07:37.174 --> 03:07:40.604
world-building, you have to have
rules. That's- that's what makes

03:07:40.654 --> 03:07:44.364
world-building work, is that like,
this exists in this world, and this

03:07:44.454 --> 03:07:48.284
doesn't, and you know, why?
It's like, 'cause someone said

03:07:48.334 --> 03:07:51.704
so, and just the way it
needs to be. But that

03:07:51.734 --> 03:07:55.694
development started in 2007, kind of as

03:07:55.894 --> 03:07:59.824
ideation, brainstorming,
early work. Really got

03:07:59.874 --> 03:08:05.514
going in late 2007, and then I had
to ship Wrath of the Lich King,

03:08:06.514 --> 03:08:12.714
And it was... We had the like, we
always did like a champagne toast. Uh,

03:08:13.934 --> 03:08:17.614
I still remember it because it was
Election Day. I think it was like

03:08:17.674 --> 03:08:20.754
Election Day and my birthday,
and the day Obama got

03:08:20.814 --> 03:08:24.774
elected, and then I left
the WoW team on that

03:08:24.874 --> 03:08:28.834
day. It was like memorable
in all those ways. And then

03:08:28.914 --> 03:08:35.154
I joined the Titan team, and that game,

03:08:36.474 --> 03:08:40.264
we went on, like the fast-forward
part of that is we shut it

03:08:40.314 --> 03:08:47.994
down in 2013. That was one of the most
painful development processes that I've

03:08:48.114 --> 03:08:52.774
ever been a part of, and probably,

03:08:54.194 --> 03:09:01.894
probably deep into 2009, I knew that the
game in its current form could never

03:09:01.954 --> 03:09:09.974
ship and would never exist, and
by 2010—Like after numerous

03:09:10.034 --> 03:09:14.014
times trying to convince
the powers that be that,

03:09:14.714 --> 03:09:18.294
like this game is not gonna
happen, it's in trouble.

03:09:18.694 --> 03:09:25.534
I remember going to Mike Morhaime in
2010, and, like, you're going to the CEO

03:09:26.414 --> 03:09:30.254
of... You know, at that time,
Blizzard was big company, and I'm

03:09:30.314 --> 03:09:35.844
like, "You gotta shut us down.
We're just gonna burn money."

03:09:35.894 --> 03:09:39.883
- What was your intuition about why? So
like from my understanding, there was

03:09:39.934 --> 03:09:43.894
a few issues. So one, with such a
gigantic world, which by the way, is

03:09:43.934 --> 03:09:47.874
a beautiful dream, this kind of universe
simulator, because I love... Every game you

03:09:47.934 --> 03:09:51.774
mentioned there is great. I
empathize with the dream. I would

03:09:51.794 --> 03:09:55.624
love to play that game. But
one of the issues, as I

03:09:55.634 --> 03:09:59.374
understand, was that it was
unclear what, like, the

03:09:59.494 --> 03:10:03.514
quest flow is. Like what are
you supposed to really do

03:10:04.414 --> 03:10:08.014
in this game? What's the thing that
connects all of the pieces together?

03:10:08.134 --> 03:10:15.614
- So it was a multifaceted failure
for- for many reasons. Ultimately,

03:10:16.254 --> 03:10:20.134
the failure of Titan lies with leadership,

03:10:20.214 --> 03:10:24.054
team leadership, myself
included. Like, there's just

03:10:24.114 --> 03:10:27.974
no getting around that. And then on top

03:10:28.034 --> 03:10:31.574
of that, like, a lot of games you
can point to as being like an

03:10:31.654 --> 03:10:35.544
engineering failure, like the, you
know, the servers didn't work-

03:10:35.674 --> 03:10:39.654
... or like an art failure, like no one
responded to the look of the game, or a design

03:10:39.754 --> 03:10:46.434
failure, like the... it's just not fun
or it's tuned poorly. We failed on art,

03:10:46.454 --> 03:10:50.354
engineering, and design,
and I'm cautious about

03:10:50.414 --> 03:10:54.394
calling out art because some
of the best art ever made at

03:10:54.534 --> 03:11:00.234
Blizzard was made for Titan. My criticism
isn't of the art that was created. My

03:11:00.274 --> 03:11:03.794
criticism is that we never
had any art cohesion,

03:11:04.674 --> 03:11:08.214
so the art looked like it could've
come from 10 different games.

03:11:08.234 --> 03:11:18.294
- Mm-hmm. And we should say it cost $83
million across those years. So a large team

03:11:19.094 --> 03:11:24.234
doing a lot of stuff, but not converging
towards a game that could actually ship.

03:11:24.314 --> 03:11:28.214
- Correct. As, like, a game
designer, I use semantics a

03:11:28.254 --> 03:11:31.844
lot and I like to define my semantics
so people know where I'm coming

03:11:31.874 --> 03:11:39.634
from. Talking about ideas versus
vision for a second, ideas

03:11:39.674 --> 03:11:47.374
are easy. Ideas, you know, I can have 10
in 10 seconds. You know, let's make a 2D

03:11:47.394 --> 03:11:54.914
platformer about a mouse, you know,
whatever. Like, you can... A secret agent

03:11:54.994 --> 03:11:58.854
by day is, you know, doing all
this cool shooting stuff, by night

03:11:58.894 --> 03:12:02.494
is running a flower shop.
You know, ideas are

03:12:02.534 --> 03:12:06.483
just infinite. At least on
creative teams, you know, you

03:12:06.483 --> 03:12:14.064
have no shortage of ideas. What I call
vision is the ability to not only

03:12:14.154 --> 03:12:22.134
take a great idea, but shepherd it into
existence, and you're doing that through

03:12:22.234 --> 03:12:25.674
inspiration first and foremost.
If you need a team to make

03:12:25.754 --> 03:12:29.434
it, you need a team to
believe in the vision of the

03:12:29.514 --> 03:12:34.494
idea. And then there also has
to be a technological plan

03:12:35.574 --> 03:12:39.444
for the idea. There has to be a design
plan. There has to be an art style for the

03:12:39.514 --> 03:12:47.354
plan. There has to be a pragmatic
production reality to the plan. And Titan

03:12:47.714 --> 03:12:57.724
kind of was like that was the hubris of
Blizzard in that era at its height of,

03:12:58.834 --> 03:13:02.734
you know, we were over being
hurt about, you know, World of

03:13:02.814 --> 03:13:06.694
Warcraft. I don't know if people are
gonna like it. And we were now in the

03:13:06.774 --> 03:13:10.334
era of, like, we made World
of Warcraft. We can do no

03:13:10.354 --> 03:13:16.974
wrong. This next thing is gonna be the
best ever. And there was also a lot

03:13:17.014 --> 03:13:21.174
of what I call anticipatory hiring-

03:13:21.474 --> 03:13:25.064
... or, like, there's opportunity
hiring and then there's also

03:13:25.134 --> 03:13:28.953
anticipatory hiring. I
have the exact opposite

03:13:29.054 --> 03:13:32.714
hiring philosophy. I won't hire anybody on

03:13:32.814 --> 03:13:36.054
any team until, like, we're
feeling like we gotta work

03:13:36.154 --> 03:13:39.834
overtime or, like, we might not
ship if we don't get, you know,

03:13:39.954 --> 03:13:46.214
somebody else in here. And Titan kinda
had that hubris of like, well, we're

03:13:46.254 --> 03:13:50.124
gonna build a really big world.
We don't know the story of the

03:13:50.194 --> 03:13:53.474
world yet. We don't really have
it mapped out what it should be

03:13:53.534 --> 03:13:57.314
like. We don't have the art
style really defined. We don't

03:13:57.374 --> 03:14:00.994
know technically how we're gonna make
the art or what the constraints of it

03:14:01.094 --> 03:14:04.864
are, but we know we're gonna build
a really big world, so let's

03:14:04.954 --> 03:14:08.884
just start hiring
environmental artists. And,

03:14:08.894 --> 03:14:12.254
like, in one year, we would hire, like, 70

03:14:12.314 --> 03:14:16.194
environmental artists from all over
the world. You know, we're getting

03:14:16.234 --> 03:14:19.654
visas and, like, the top tier talent

03:14:19.714 --> 03:14:23.644
'cause at the height of World of
Warcraft and nobody knew the team that

03:14:23.674 --> 03:14:27.194
they were coming on.
It was Blizzard's next

03:14:27.314 --> 03:14:30.934
MMO top secret and they, you know,
their first day at work, like

03:14:30.974 --> 03:14:34.634
some, you know, poor guy
from Belgium just shows

03:14:34.874 --> 03:14:38.534
up and he's at his first day at
work and he's like, "Oh, are we

03:14:38.574 --> 03:14:42.554
making World of StarCraft? Is that..." And they're
like, "No, dude. Let me show you it." And he's

03:14:42.594 --> 03:14:46.094
like, "What is this game?"
You know? We were in that

03:14:46.234 --> 03:14:53.934
world, and we hired way too many people.
The right way to incubate a video game

03:14:53.994 --> 03:15:01.714
is you have the smallest group possible
and you try to get the idea across with

03:15:01.754 --> 03:15:05.284
whatever technology you can
get your hands on, using other

03:15:05.394 --> 03:15:09.194
engines, using art from
whatever. You prove out that

03:15:09.254 --> 03:15:14.394
idea, and once you know what you're
doing, then you expand the team.

03:15:16.030 --> 03:15:21.460
You know the cliche of idle hands
is the devil's work, or whatever.

03:15:21.510 --> 03:15:28.070
You have this, like, brilliant team,
huge, and we don't have a road map

03:15:28.670 --> 03:15:32.590
for what we're making or how
we're gonna make it. And

03:15:32.670 --> 03:15:36.590
now you're having to deal with all
these people. Like, they're coming into

03:15:36.650 --> 03:15:40.450
your office, you know, you're trying
to figure out what is the quest flow,

03:15:40.490 --> 03:15:44.170
what—how do I design the quest system
for Titan, how can we prototype

03:15:44.250 --> 03:15:47.950
it? And we're like, "Oh, this prop artist

03:15:48.049 --> 03:15:51.930
over here is running out of stuff
to do. What props should he make?

03:15:51.990 --> 03:15:55.450
Should he work on Chinatown or the

03:15:55.510 --> 03:15:59.290
Hollywood set?" And you're
just making up busy work.

03:15:59.810 --> 03:16:05.400
The engine didn't work. When we
would run play tests on Titan,

03:16:06.510 --> 03:16:10.330
we would have to tell the team, "Stop
checking in because it slows us

03:16:10.370 --> 03:16:15.750
down." We had this really great technical
artist, a guy named Dylan Jones,

03:16:16.650 --> 03:16:20.610
and he was on Titan with us,
and I remember in, like, the

03:16:20.730 --> 03:16:24.670
last days, we asked him,
because he was a very active

03:16:24.790 --> 03:16:32.270
user Titan editor was called Titan Edit
or TED which is, to this day, TED is the

03:16:32.370 --> 03:16:37.450
proprietary tool for Overwatch, since
Overwatch came from the Titan engine-

03:16:37.460 --> 03:16:41.370
... which was Tank. And we
said to Dylan, "I want you

03:16:41.410 --> 03:16:48.550
to log your uptime in the editor,
in TED." And in a 40-hour

03:16:48.750 --> 03:16:52.150
week, he was only able
to work for 20 hours.

03:16:53.410 --> 03:16:57.070
And you can imagine, you're building
a team of the best and the like, the

03:16:57.290 --> 03:17:03.430
best in the industry, and they can't work.
So not only are you just burning cash

03:17:03.550 --> 03:17:07.390
faster than anybody on the
planet, it's also, like,

03:17:07.450 --> 03:17:11.550
imagine having fighter pilots,
but we don't let them fly.

03:17:11.590 --> 03:17:19.210
Like, the creative frustration and the
way that that manifested itself, and

03:17:19.690 --> 03:17:24.690
how demoralized the team
got, it was a disaster.

03:17:24.710 --> 03:17:27.930
- And so many elements of
that were done completely

03:17:27.970 --> 03:17:31.930
differently for Overwatch, which turned

03:17:31.990 --> 03:17:35.470
out to be this incredibly
masterful execution on a short

03:17:35.510 --> 03:17:39.030
timescale with a small team with a clear

03:17:39.170 --> 03:17:42.590
vision. I read that sort of if
you- if you were to compare

03:17:42.650 --> 03:17:46.410
Overwatch and Titan, sort of
the defining characteristic

03:17:46.570 --> 03:17:50.410
for the Titan team, they said yes to
everything, and the Overwatch team said no to

03:17:50.450 --> 03:17:54.390
everything. Meaning focus, like deep,
deep focus on the execution of a

03:17:54.450 --> 03:17:57.890
very clear vision. And
maybe that's the process of

03:17:57.930 --> 03:18:04.910
designing games, like you said, is, you
know on a team that's full of incredible

03:18:04.950 --> 03:18:08.790
ideas because it's creative minds, it's
constantly saying no. It's a really

03:18:08.850 --> 03:18:12.190
painful process, but perhaps it is the

03:18:12.230 --> 03:18:16.030
responsibility of leadership
to just keep saying no. Which

03:18:16.130 --> 03:18:20.090
sucks. I guess it sucks to be a
leader on a team in that sense,

03:18:20.110 --> 03:18:21.290
because you're constantly saying no.

03:18:21.670 --> 03:18:25.350
- The being a creative leader, you're in two

03:18:25.430 --> 03:18:29.350
modes. You're pushing or you're
pulling, and whatever mode you're in

03:18:29.390 --> 03:18:32.050
is the exact opposite of the team.

03:18:32.090 --> 03:18:38.970
When they're not thinking outside the
box enough or, like, elevating the

03:18:39.030 --> 03:18:42.990
vision enough, that's when you're
pushing them. Like, "Come on guys," you

03:18:43.030 --> 03:18:46.950
know, "don't worry about the
schedule. We got—" you know, "capture

03:18:47.010 --> 03:18:50.940
hearts and minds, inspire
people." And when they're going a

03:18:51.030 --> 03:18:54.910
little crazy and they... Endless source of

03:18:54.970 --> 03:18:58.910
great ideas and really
fun development, that's

03:18:58.950 --> 03:19:02.920
when you gotta pull and say, "Guys,
we need to ship this. The best

03:19:02.950 --> 03:19:06.770
feature we can add for the
player is shipping." That was a

03:19:06.830 --> 03:19:09.090
common phrase that we had.

03:19:09.190 --> 03:19:12.690
- So when Titan was canceled,
I mean that must've been a

03:19:12.910 --> 03:19:16.839
gigantic heartbreak for everybody.
And there was this moment when

03:19:17.210 --> 03:19:21.050
the plan was for the Titan
team to be disbanded and moved

03:19:21.110 --> 03:19:23.740
elsewhere, but you fought for

03:19:24.690 --> 03:19:28.590
for keeping some part of the
Titan team, the core of the team

03:19:28.630 --> 03:19:32.309
together, and Mike Morhaime gave you six

03:19:32.369 --> 03:19:36.050
weeks to come up with a pitch for a
new game. And you've talked about this

03:19:36.090 --> 03:19:39.430
process, and you've mentioned that there

03:19:39.450 --> 03:19:46.660
were three possible ideas, directions
you were thinking about. A StarCraft MMO

03:19:46.710 --> 03:19:52.430
maybe an MMO in a new IP called
CrossWorlds, and then the third idea was

03:19:52.490 --> 03:19:56.850
Overwatch. Can you take me
through those six weeks?

03:19:56.910 --> 03:20:00.759
- Yeah, the six weeks, it's... It
was supposed to be the greatest

03:20:00.810 --> 03:20:04.550
time ever if you think about it. Because

03:20:05.150 --> 03:20:10.550
you're a game developer at Blizzard,
and you get to come up with a new idea.

03:20:10.630 --> 03:20:14.430
So that sounds awesome, like, to
everybody at Blizzard, to all

03:20:14.470 --> 03:20:18.350
game developers, it sounds
great. But we were probably the

03:20:18.390 --> 03:20:22.190
most demoralized we'd ever been in
our careers. At least I was, you

03:20:22.250 --> 03:20:26.050
know? I didn't know if I was gonna be fired.
I didn't know if that was the end of my

03:20:26.130 --> 03:20:33.410
career at that point. And so it was
like a really serious, kind of dire

03:20:34.370 --> 03:20:38.070
environment that this
was happening in. And

03:20:38.870 --> 03:20:45.910
we were given two criteria that we had to
hit for these pitches. The first one was

03:20:45.970 --> 03:20:52.890
that we had to ship within two years. And
that is a very ambitious timeframe for

03:20:52.970 --> 03:20:53.540
any game.

03:20:53.550 --> 03:20:54.290
- Yeah, crazy. That's crazy.

03:20:54.310 --> 03:20:57.810
- But for a Blizzard game,
it's kind of insane.

03:20:57.870 --> 03:21:05.390
And then the second... Okay, the second
is even more ambitious and crazy, was

03:21:05.730 --> 03:21:09.030
whatever we made, whatever
we pitched had to have the

03:21:09.070 --> 03:21:13.410
potential to have World
of Warcraft-like revenue.

03:21:13.570 --> 03:21:14.730
- Yeah. Right.

03:21:14.810 --> 03:21:18.220
- And to date, at that point, there
was one game that had World of

03:21:18.290 --> 03:21:20.710
Warcraft-like revenue, which
was World of Warcraft,

03:21:20.810 --> 03:21:24.706
so...Immediately, I just
threw out the revenue thing

03:21:24.806 --> 03:21:27.835
'cause it's all fucking
Monopoly money to me.

03:21:27.866 --> 03:21:31.746
Like, this game money is... It's
insane, and I just don't think

03:21:31.786 --> 03:21:39.616
about it. That's someone else's problem.
But I did want to be as realistic as

03:21:39.766 --> 03:21:43.706
I could about the schedule part
of it. So most of our team, the

03:21:43.746 --> 03:21:50.966
Titan team, was 140-some people. Most
of that team got moved to go work on

03:21:51.966 --> 03:21:55.886
Heroes of the Storm, the
D3 expansion, World of

03:21:55.966 --> 03:21:59.766
Warcraft, Hearthstone. So immediately,

03:22:00.066 --> 03:22:03.986
a large number of the team was gone. Then we
had a bunch of, like, what we called temp

03:22:04.066 --> 03:22:08.816
loans- ... people that someday were gonna
come back to us, but we loaned off for,

03:22:08.846 --> 03:22:12.806
like, six-month tour of duty.
And then there was a very small

03:22:12.946 --> 03:22:16.286
team. There was a group of
engineers that was mothballing

03:22:16.406 --> 03:22:19.906
Titan, so it exists somewhere at

03:22:19.946 --> 03:22:23.836
Blizzard at that point. And they
were also deconstructing the

03:22:23.946 --> 03:22:27.806
engine because they knew it didn't
work anymore, and to make a

03:22:27.886 --> 03:22:33.226
new game, it had to be way
reconsidered to sort of what it is

03:22:33.286 --> 03:22:38.946
today. And then there was a very small
creative group that was supposed to come up

03:22:38.986 --> 03:22:42.906
with these three pitches and
given six weeks. And we just sort

03:22:42.926 --> 03:22:46.446
of arbitrarily decided, like,
let's spend two weeks on each

03:22:46.486 --> 03:22:50.426
pitch. The ground rules that I sort of led

03:22:50.466 --> 03:22:54.396
with is you have to be all
in for the two weeks on the

03:22:54.506 --> 03:22:58.386
pitch. So if we're... You
know, pitch one was a

03:22:58.486 --> 03:23:02.366
StarCraft MMO, and we have
to live and breathe and want

03:23:02.426 --> 03:23:06.346
it more than anything. And I kind of
warned everybody. I said, "At the end of

03:23:06.386 --> 03:23:09.326
this two weeks, you're going to
think this is the only game idea,

03:23:10.126 --> 03:23:13.886
and you're not going to be invested in the next,
but we're going to throw it out as soon as we

03:23:13.946 --> 03:23:17.866
finish it and do the next
one." And the StarCraft

03:23:17.986 --> 03:23:21.746
MMO, I actually really loved
that pitch. It was called

03:23:21.826 --> 03:23:25.626
StarCraft Frontiers. And
the concept was, like,

03:23:25.746 --> 03:23:29.366
less of you're playing, like, space
marine. Like, it was less armies.

03:23:29.426 --> 03:23:34.206
StarCraft the RTS is always about the
three races and the giant armies.

03:23:34.226 --> 03:23:41.926
And kind of what made WoW wow and separate
from the Warcraft RTS series was that

03:23:42.266 --> 03:23:46.206
instead of being, like, a footman in the
army in World of Warcraft, you were like a

03:23:46.306 --> 03:23:49.856
lone adventurer, you know,
make your mark on the

03:23:49.946 --> 03:23:56.286
world. So we had this idea, it was this
old Chris Metzen drawing of a space

03:23:56.366 --> 03:24:00.186
prospector. And I love that
idea that, like, somewhere

03:24:00.266 --> 03:24:03.426
out in, like, where all the
giant StarCraft battles were

03:24:03.466 --> 03:24:07.246
happening, you know, thousands
of Zerg and Protoss and

03:24:07.286 --> 03:24:14.386
Terran, there's, like, this, like, lone
prospector on some planet, like, going

03:24:14.396 --> 03:24:17.176
through, like, a mysterious dungeon-

03:24:17.206 --> 03:24:21.106
... you know, looking for minerals but
finding monsters. Like, it was that

03:24:21.146 --> 03:24:22.526
kind of spirit of-

03:24:22.586 --> 03:24:23.106
- That's awesome

03:24:23.186 --> 03:24:24.586
- ... more on the ground level.

03:24:24.886 --> 03:24:28.336
- I didn't even think about that because my
intuition with a StarCraft MMO would be the

03:24:28.446 --> 03:24:32.046
soldier as part of the army, right? The
prospector. That's such a beautiful

03:24:32.086 --> 03:24:32.886
vision. Yeah.

03:24:32.956 --> 03:24:33.136
- Yeah, I—

03:24:33.136 --> 03:24:36.956
- Looking for the resources and on
the way finding the monsters.

03:24:37.546 --> 03:24:41.366
- You want to be on the ground— Like,
what's it like on the ground floor?

03:24:41.466 --> 03:24:45.326
And I don't want to be a
minion in a giant army. I want

03:24:45.346 --> 03:24:49.746
to— I want to be Indiana
Jones in space, you know?

03:24:49.826 --> 03:24:49.916
- Nice.

03:24:50.086 --> 03:24:52.556
- Um, so then there was this
Metzen picture of the

03:24:52.646 --> 03:24:59.226
prospector, and then two of the most amazing
artists, Arnold Tsang and Peter Lee.

03:24:59.306 --> 03:25:03.266
Arnold's the great character artist.
Peter Lee's the great environment

03:25:03.326 --> 03:25:07.106
artist. They did this
concept art for Frontiers

03:25:07.786 --> 03:25:11.326
that was Metzen's space
prospector. He's smoking a

03:25:11.386 --> 03:25:15.326
cigar- ... and he's got his
foot on a Hydralisk skull.

03:25:15.466 --> 03:25:15.756
- Nice.

03:25:15.756 --> 03:25:19.586
- And then there's, like, a Medivac in the
background, and they're on this, like, big

03:25:19.646 --> 03:25:22.846
alien planet. And, like, that
picture, you just wanted to

03:25:22.906 --> 03:25:29.486
like, "Here's my money. I'll pre-order
now. Like, sign me up for that game." Um,

03:25:30.746 --> 03:25:37.226
that picture ended up being McCree
from Overwatch. We redid it.

03:25:37.246 --> 03:25:37.356
- Nice.

03:25:37.406 --> 03:25:41.185
- Um, but, but yeah, that's
where McCree actually came

03:25:41.286 --> 03:25:45.246
from. So that was the StarCraft
Frontiers idea. We kind of, we went

03:25:45.306 --> 03:25:49.146
all in on the design. We had a
world design. We had class design,

03:25:49.186 --> 03:25:52.706
like how, how the classes would work what

03:25:52.826 --> 03:25:56.706
progression might look like. And you
also have to think when you're trying to

03:25:56.746 --> 03:25:59.986
design an MMO, like, what could
expansions and live content be

03:26:00.126 --> 03:26:04.066
like? And we put together
a really good pitch.

03:26:04.106 --> 03:26:07.566
We all knew there's no way
you can make this game.

03:26:07.606 --> 03:26:14.266
Like, this, even though it was more
focused than Titan, it's five years on

03:26:14.306 --> 03:26:18.066
Blizzard's best day with
nothing going wrong, in

03:26:18.146 --> 03:26:25.646
perfect scenario, five years to make that
game probably with, you know, 150 to 200

03:26:25.686 --> 03:26:30.666
people. Like, these 40 people
are not making that game in two

03:26:30.726 --> 03:26:34.686
years. So as much as I...
Like, again, that was an idea,

03:26:34.706 --> 03:26:40.726
not a vision, 'cause it lacked, it lacked
the path to reality, you know? There-

03:26:40.736 --> 03:26:44.646
- 'Cause that's a legit large-scale MMO
in a world that you haven't quite

03:26:44.686 --> 03:26:48.646
developed in the way that an MMO
needs that was really crafted

03:26:48.686 --> 03:26:52.566
for the arts or the real-time strategy
formulation of StarCraft. And it's in

03:26:52.626 --> 03:26:53.876
space. It's-

03:26:53.966 --> 03:26:57.736
It's... It would, it would take... I mean, it would
be incredible, but it would be a five-year and

03:26:57.786 --> 03:26:59.226
realistically even more.

03:26:59.266 --> 03:27:02.786
- Like, an endless thing that you'd spin
on on that team. You're making the

03:27:02.846 --> 03:27:05.556
StarCraft game. How do you
get from planet to planet?

03:27:05.566 --> 03:27:09.546
Is it a cut scene? No one's going
to want a cut scene, but we

03:27:09.566 --> 03:27:13.246
should probably make it a cut scene because
that's easy, but well, we gotta have space

03:27:13.346 --> 03:27:13.796
flight.

03:27:14.866 --> 03:27:18.446
That... You're adding, like, three years just
by saying, "We gotta have space flight."

03:27:18.646 --> 03:27:19.256
- You are. Yeah.

03:27:19.266 --> 03:27:23.046
- And then how do you make a space game
without space flight? We've all played

03:27:23.056 --> 03:27:25.786
them. We know, we know those games, so.

03:27:25.826 --> 03:27:29.626
- So are you essentially, when you're
brainstorming like that, and by the way, such an

03:27:29.646 --> 03:27:33.146
incredible thing, for two weeks, you're
just really falling in love with the game

03:27:33.226 --> 03:27:37.096
altogether and trying to figure out if
it's actually possible. So if you're

03:27:37.126 --> 03:27:41.076
developing that, are you just constantly
trying to say, like, "What is the

03:27:41.206 --> 03:27:44.566
simplest possible thing we
can do that's a complete

03:27:44.606 --> 03:27:48.466
world?" Like, are you constantly trying
to simplify or you're allowing yourself

03:27:48.506 --> 03:27:49.746
to go big?

03:27:49.846 --> 03:27:53.646
- So when you're brainstorming and
you're with the team and you're the

03:27:53.706 --> 03:28:00.276
creative leader, it's, "Guys,
what's fucking amazing?"

03:28:00.276 --> 03:28:04.146
What's big? What do players
need? There's a Blizzard

03:28:04.206 --> 03:28:06.766
design value called "What is the fantasy?"

03:28:06.786 --> 03:28:10.766
What is the fantasy? You
want to be in space.

03:28:10.866 --> 03:28:17.646
you want to be in the StarCraft universe,
and then your job as the game director,

03:28:17.686 --> 03:28:21.166
and if you have a great creative
director, art director, tech

03:28:21.226 --> 03:28:24.946
director, the director
should be scoping it back

03:28:25.246 --> 03:28:29.006
into reality. The mistake
I see on a lot of game

03:28:29.106 --> 03:28:32.766
teams is scope becomes
a production problem.

03:28:33.726 --> 03:28:37.466
You give it to the project
managers or the executives

03:28:37.666 --> 03:28:40.786
or the producers to say,
"No, there's not enough

03:28:40.846 --> 03:28:44.686
time." Or, "You guys
should hire more," 'cause-

03:28:44.726 --> 03:28:46.226
- Right.

03:28:46.286 --> 03:28:50.246
- Like, what do executives,
what do those types

03:28:50.326 --> 03:28:54.046
have at their disposal that they can
hit you with meetings in Outlook

03:28:54.566 --> 03:28:58.456
and tell you that you can hire more
people? That's not really how you get

03:28:58.546 --> 03:28:59.866
the game made.

03:28:59.906 --> 03:29:02.826
- That's why they get paid the big bucks.

03:29:02.886 --> 03:29:06.606
- The scoping, your best-case scenario is

03:29:06.686 --> 03:29:12.946
when your tech director, art director,
and game director are doing the scoping.

03:29:13.026 --> 03:29:17.006
Um, because then you know, like,
this part we gotta spend big

03:29:17.026 --> 03:29:20.946
bucks on. There's no getting
around it. This part we

03:29:21.006 --> 03:29:24.946
can cheat. If you have
a giant team and one

03:29:24.966 --> 03:29:28.706
guy's job is just to make props,
you know, crates and chairs,

03:29:29.586 --> 03:29:33.346
that guy's going to make the... You
know, that's a triple A awesome

03:29:33.426 --> 03:29:36.866
developer who's going to put his
heart and soul into it. If you let

03:29:36.906 --> 03:29:41.586
him, he'll take, you know,
six weeks to make a crate.

03:29:41.606 --> 03:29:45.106
You have to have that moment where
you're like, "I kind of need 200

03:29:45.166 --> 03:29:49.026
crates. So just spend,
like, a couple hours on

03:29:49.086 --> 03:29:52.586
that one." And that's a hard
thing to say to somebody.

03:29:52.866 --> 03:29:59.026
- You're doing this kind of
scope carving while also

03:30:00.306 --> 03:30:01.986
talking about what is the fantasy.

03:30:02.026 --> 03:30:05.986
So you're, there's a tension there that you're
constantly dancing with. So you're allowing

03:30:06.006 --> 03:30:09.996
yourself to think big, but then sculping
it down, and doing that, what, on a

03:30:10.066 --> 03:30:11.786
scale of days in this case, like?

03:30:12.186 --> 03:30:16.066
- Yeah. We had two weeks,
so, and I don't think

03:30:16.126 --> 03:30:19.906
we were... I was working on
weekends, but we weren't getting the

03:30:19.966 --> 03:30:23.826
group together. So it's, you
know, like 10 working days.

03:30:24.206 --> 03:30:27.866
- And then you, like, shut it
off and go to idea number two?

03:30:27.926 --> 03:30:34.866
- Yeah. Idea number two was Crossworlds.
That was a Metzen vision for a universe,

03:30:35.626 --> 03:30:39.506
and, like, I'm glad Metzen's back at

03:30:39.606 --> 03:30:43.486
Blizzard, and I hope they
make this game someday.

03:30:43.566 --> 03:30:49.586
The way Chris described it was there's
a planet on the edge of the universe

03:30:50.406 --> 03:30:54.366
that's like the Mos Eisley space
port with all these, you know,

03:30:54.426 --> 03:30:58.066
freakish aliens and people
from all walks of life-

03:30:58.126 --> 03:30:58.226
- Nice

03:30:58.236 --> 03:31:00.646
- ... and it's kind of seedy and criminal.

03:31:00.666 --> 03:31:04.486
And there's traders and
smugglers and diplomats

03:31:04.606 --> 03:31:08.546
and... But this one planet
is sort of the planet that

03:31:08.586 --> 03:31:12.206
they've agreed to like meet on,
and this is like the neutral

03:31:12.386 --> 03:31:16.646
place, and then the game was going
to take place on that planet, so-

03:31:16.766 --> 03:31:17.566
- This is awesome.

03:31:17.606 --> 03:31:21.426
- Yeah. So that was more of like
a world IP driven one that

03:31:21.466 --> 03:31:23.286
was really inspired by Chris.

03:31:24.106 --> 03:31:27.906
- And that allows you to play with
different characters, different... I like

03:31:27.946 --> 03:31:31.426
that, I like that idea a lot,
because it's the meeting place

03:31:32.166 --> 03:31:36.146
of different worlds, and then you
can allow your imagination to drive

03:31:36.186 --> 03:31:40.176
what the worlds from which they
came from are like. So you don't

03:31:40.226 --> 03:31:41.546
have to design those worlds.

03:31:41.586 --> 03:31:45.116
- No, you, you don't have to design
them, but then they're yours. Like,

03:31:45.166 --> 03:31:49.336
if the players really are reacting
to, like, the Green People planet-

03:31:49.606 --> 03:31:52.536
... or whatever, and someday you're like,
"Hey, what expansion should we make?"

03:31:52.536 --> 03:31:53.896
"I don't know. Green People planet."

03:31:53.896 --> 03:31:54.806
- Green People, yeah.

03:31:54.826 --> 03:31:56.246
- Like, "Let's do it."

03:31:56.326 --> 03:31:57.006
- I like it.

03:31:57.066 --> 03:32:02.686
- So it was actually that, it was CrossWorlds,
we were working on CrossWorlds,

03:32:02.746 --> 03:32:06.526
and like the StarCraft
Frontiers, you know, for

03:32:06.566 --> 03:32:10.486
for Frontiers, we were having the class
meetings, you know, how class progression work,

03:32:10.506 --> 03:32:14.406
like, the game designery stuff. And

03:32:15.406 --> 03:32:22.405
on CrossWorlds, we were having a class
meeting of, like a big decision in, like, RPG

03:32:22.606 --> 03:32:26.866
type games is always, are you doing,
like, skill based or class based?

03:32:26.886 --> 03:32:30.666
And it's usually some combination
of those, but class based, you're

03:32:30.726 --> 03:32:33.946
like choosing, "I'm going to be a
warrior, therefore I use sword and

03:32:34.046 --> 03:32:38.026
shield, and I do these
things." Where more of

03:32:38.046 --> 03:32:41.866
a skill base is everybody's
kind of an avatar, and then

03:32:41.946 --> 03:32:45.846
the skills that you pick
define, so I might take

03:32:45.886 --> 03:32:49.676
that I know how to use swords. So
you're kind of making those decisions,

03:32:49.686 --> 03:32:53.436
and with all things game design,
there's no right or wrong.

03:32:53.466 --> 03:32:57.146
It's all trade-offs. So the trade-off

03:32:58.026 --> 03:33:01.826
decision we were making is like, "Oh, I
think we want to be class based with this

03:33:01.886 --> 03:33:02.996
CrossWorlds thing,"

03:33:03.866 --> 03:33:07.626
and we were in a design meeting and
one of my favorite designers of all

03:33:07.746 --> 03:33:11.566
time is a guy named Jeff Goodman.
He was one of the original

03:33:11.666 --> 03:33:15.086
WoW encounter designer, he
designed like Onyxia and all the

03:33:15.126 --> 03:33:19.086
big raid bosses. Like, if someone
has a favorite raid boss, Jeff

03:33:19.126 --> 03:33:26.822
probably designed it. And he just kind of
off the cuff said in this meeting, "He

03:33:26.842 --> 03:33:34.022
said, "I wish instead of making, like, six
classes, I wish we could make 50 classes.

03:33:34.582 --> 03:33:42.272
And I wish instead of having, like, you
know, 100 abilities on the classes, the

03:33:42.602 --> 03:33:46.362
50 classes all just had, like,
one or two things that was really

03:33:46.402 --> 03:33:50.232
interesting about them." And
then the class meeting ended.

03:33:50.262 --> 03:33:54.082
Like, we designed our six classes
in that meeting, and then the

03:33:54.422 --> 03:34:02.082
meeting ended. And I was back at my desk,
and it just stuck with me what Jeff had

03:34:02.142 --> 03:34:05.342
said about the way he
wished he could design the

03:34:05.382 --> 03:34:13.462
classes. And then I also had... We had this
directory of all the amazing Titan art.

03:34:13.522 --> 03:34:17.322
And I started pulling up
Arnold Tsang's characters.

03:34:17.602 --> 03:34:26.242
Arnold's vision and his art is second to
none. And I started taking some of the old

03:34:26.422 --> 03:34:30.362
Titan characters that we had
designed. We had a class called the

03:34:30.422 --> 03:34:34.322
Jumper, and the Jumper could,
like, teleport forward and

03:34:34.342 --> 03:34:37.742
rewind time and come
back. And the Jumper used

03:34:37.982 --> 03:34:41.262
dual-wield pistols, which
was, at the time, designed

03:34:41.322 --> 03:34:48.002
after my dual G18s from Modern Warfare
2. It was my favorite loadout.

03:34:48.102 --> 03:34:53.782
Uh, I was just cribbing Infinity Ward.
That's where Tracer's guns came from.

03:34:53.802 --> 03:34:57.702
And we had all these, like, different guns,
like, some that bloomed and some that, you

03:34:57.742 --> 03:35:01.682
know, had this, like, really
crazy recoil, and we had other

03:35:01.742 --> 03:35:05.562
types of guns. And I took
every version of, like, the

03:35:05.602 --> 03:35:09.452
Titan Jumper, and I just
distilled it into what

03:35:09.602 --> 03:35:13.422
I thought was the best
version of the Jumper,

03:35:13.462 --> 03:35:17.302
which was, you know, the
dual-wield pistols, the blink, the

03:35:17.322 --> 03:35:21.112
recall, and time bomb. And
then I took Arnold Tsang

03:35:21.262 --> 03:35:24.892
art, and I went, you
know, to Arnold, and I'm

03:35:24.922 --> 03:35:28.682
like, "What if this wasn't,
like, a class? You know, who is

03:35:28.762 --> 03:35:32.732
this as a person, not a class?" And

03:35:32.862 --> 03:35:37.342
Arnold, "Uh, what if she's British,
and her name's Tracer?" And, like,

03:35:38.262 --> 03:35:42.222
that was the origin of Overwatch. And some

03:35:42.262 --> 03:35:46.022
of the pragmatic part
of that was I knew that

03:35:46.882 --> 03:35:50.542
Geoff Goodman was gonna be on
this team, and I knew that

03:35:50.582 --> 03:35:54.162
Arnold Tsang was gonna be on this
team. And it's a play to your

03:35:54.242 --> 03:36:01.442
strengths moment. Like, what could we make
in two years with the talent we have,

03:36:02.362 --> 03:36:07.222
and what is realistic? Like, what
could we realistically make?

03:36:07.242 --> 03:36:15.212
And so then I just sat there, and I sort
of I went through a bunch of Titan classes

03:36:16.022 --> 03:36:23.062
with a guy named The Gunjack, who was...
became Reaper. We had... Actually, the

03:36:23.102 --> 03:36:29.962
Ranger got split out and became 76,
and became Bastion of all things.

03:36:30.002 --> 03:36:33.692
- You're describing the game
of Overwatch where exactly

03:36:33.782 --> 03:36:36.022
that vision from that meeting-

03:36:36.102 --> 03:36:36.222
- Yes.

03:36:36.232 --> 03:36:40.222
- ... came to life for you. As opposed
to having a small number of classes

03:36:40.282 --> 03:36:44.242
with a large number of skills,
you have a large number

03:36:44.302 --> 03:36:50.612
of heroes with each their distinct
look, distinct set of skills.

03:36:50.662 --> 03:36:54.462
- Yeah, and persona- the personality
was a big part of it, like

03:36:54.522 --> 03:37:01.922
capturing... This isn't some generic, the
Jumper. It's this person, Lena Oxton.

03:37:01.982 --> 03:37:05.622
You know? And she has a
life, and we're gonna, you

03:37:05.662 --> 03:37:07.852
know, make you interested in her.

03:37:07.902 --> 03:37:11.802
- Yeah, there's, like, a deep backstory.
And that's also what's interesting about

03:37:11.862 --> 03:37:15.822
Overwatch, is that backstory
is not, like, revealed in,

03:37:16.242 --> 03:37:20.122
in a direct way. It's,
it sort of, like, seeps

03:37:20.222 --> 03:37:25.342
in indirectly throughout the game.
So, the backstory is implied almost.

03:37:25.362 --> 03:37:25.822
- Yeah.

03:37:26.182 --> 03:37:29.811
- And it's told not directly. So, there's a
lot of ideas like this. And so you're...

03:37:29.862 --> 03:37:32.102
This is the thing that
the team converged to.

03:37:32.162 --> 03:37:35.922
- Yeah. Well, and it was funny because,
like, we're having these Cross

03:37:36.022 --> 03:37:39.652
World. Like, people are, you know,
writing design docs and doing

03:37:39.702 --> 03:37:43.571
concept art for Cross World. And, you know,
we'd have some brainstorm meetings every

03:37:43.662 --> 03:37:48.542
day, and I put together...
It was a seven- page deck,

03:37:48.922 --> 03:37:54.682
Overwatch deck. And it was called
Monetized Shooter at the time.

03:37:54.782 --> 03:37:55.522
- Yeah.

03:37:55.582 --> 03:37:59.402
- And it just said, "Monetized
Shooter." And then the

03:37:59.542 --> 03:38:04.782
first slide was League of Legends
plus Team Fortress 2 logos.

03:38:04.882 --> 03:38:05.192
- Yeah.

03:38:05.222 --> 03:38:08.842
- And then I had, like, six
heroes, like, sloppily

03:38:08.862 --> 03:38:14.672
designed. And as everybody
was working on Cross Worlds

03:38:15.982 --> 03:38:19.582
there were two, you know, co-leaders of

03:38:20.142 --> 03:38:23.882
that team for... There was, you
know... Chris Metzen was there,

03:38:23.962 --> 03:38:30.482
and Ray Gresko. And I remember Ray coming
over. Uh, Ray is, like, a phenomenal

03:38:31.222 --> 03:38:34.782
game developer of all time. He,
like, wrote the Dark Forces

03:38:35.402 --> 03:38:42.502
engine, was the production director on
Diablo III. He and I killed Titan. And then

03:38:43.462 --> 03:38:47.232
he's at my desk looking over
my shoulder, and he's like,

03:38:47.232 --> 03:38:51.222
"Well, what are you working on? Is this the Cross
Worlds pitch?" I'm like, "No, this is, like,

03:38:51.262 --> 03:38:57.822
another idea that I'm just working on
on the side." And I show him the seven

03:38:57.982 --> 03:39:04.932
slides, and he just looks at me,
and he says, "Go show Metzen this.

03:39:04.942 --> 03:39:12.582
This is what we should make instead." And
then I went and I showed Metzen, like,

03:39:12.622 --> 03:39:16.272
"Hey, this is, hey, this
is just an idea." And then

03:39:16.302 --> 03:39:20.592
Metzen was like, "Yes." You know,
like, "This is what we should make."

03:39:20.602 --> 03:39:24.172
And I showed Arnold, and it
was Arnold's art. And then

03:39:25.102 --> 03:39:28.742
Ray tells me, he's like... 'Cause we
would- Every morning, we'd get the team

03:39:28.822 --> 03:39:32.342
together 'cause we were in this dire,
you know, dire straits, and we're

03:39:32.502 --> 03:39:36.238
midway through at that
point. And Ray and a

03:39:36.318 --> 03:39:40.158
producer named Matt Hawley said,
"Tomorrow morning at the meeting,

03:39:40.898 --> 03:39:44.478
you're gonna pitch this Monetized
Shooter idea." It was called

03:39:44.578 --> 03:39:47.938
Monetized Shooter because originally
when I pitched it, it was free to

03:39:47.978 --> 03:39:51.828
play and you had to buy the
heroes, which is fucking

03:39:51.858 --> 03:39:56.878
terrible, but at the time, I actually
thought that was a good idea.

03:39:56.938 --> 03:40:02.258
And I'm walking down the hall with
Matt Hawley to go, like, pitch this

03:40:02.438 --> 03:40:06.398
to this group, you know, out of- we're supposed
to be working on CrossWorld, and they're like,

03:40:06.408 --> 03:40:11.958
"You gotta pitch this idea to them." And
Matt Hawley stops me in the hall and says,

03:40:13.898 --> 03:40:17.598
"You, Jeff, you cannot
go into that meeting. I

03:40:17.618 --> 03:40:21.498
refuse to put up a deck in front
of the team where the first slide

03:40:21.578 --> 03:40:24.338
says, 'Monetized Shooter.'"

03:40:24.718 --> 03:40:29.358
"They'll hate that, and that's
not the spirit of who we are-"

03:40:29.368 --> 03:40:33.188
"... as, you know, creative devel-" And I'm like,
"Yeah, you're right." Like, well no one was

03:40:33.188 --> 03:40:34.708
supposed to see his deck anyway.

03:40:34.708 --> 03:40:38.538
You guys are all looking over my
shoulder. He's like, "You need to put a

03:40:38.578 --> 03:40:42.398
name on it." I'm like, "It's
Overwatch." Like, right on the

03:40:42.418 --> 03:40:46.298
spot, I said the name was Overwatch.
And where that had come from

03:40:47.198 --> 03:40:52.838
was when we were working on Titan, I was
really angry about this. We did this

03:40:52.938 --> 03:40:56.868
fake... I did not do this,
another leader on the team did

03:40:56.918 --> 03:41:00.678
this, of this fake,
like, we're gonna put up

03:41:00.718 --> 03:41:05.338
whiteboards and everyone gets to vote
for their favorite name for Titan.

03:41:07.498 --> 03:41:10.868
But the person who did it
already had a name in mind-

03:41:10.868 --> 03:41:17.358
... for the game. And just kept
pushing towards that name.

03:41:17.398 --> 03:41:21.268
And the thing that got the most
votes was Overwatch. Overwatch in

03:41:21.318 --> 03:41:23.758
Titan was, like, a police group,

03:41:23.938 --> 03:41:27.398
essentially. But somebody had
written Overwatch on that

03:41:27.538 --> 03:41:35.178
board and it got the most votes. So I
basically named the game Overwatch to,

03:41:35.198 --> 03:41:40.738
like, high five my team- ... and
kind of middle finger. Like—

03:41:40.758 --> 03:41:44.128
Don't act like it's a democracy
when it's not. You know? So...

03:41:44.128 --> 03:41:46.038
- So it's a middle finger.

03:41:46.098 --> 03:41:49.958
So Overwatch, and then the, I mean,
the rest is history. So what,

03:41:49.998 --> 03:41:53.778
what, in that slide deck, is that,
in that slide deck, were, did you

03:41:53.818 --> 03:42:00.498
already have a kind of crawl, walk, run idea
of, of the way this would be developed?

03:42:00.638 --> 03:42:04.398
- So my deck was terrible.
People actually... there's a

03:42:04.458 --> 03:42:08.418
thing called the Jeff Deck, which
is it's always gray with black

03:42:08.458 --> 03:42:12.198
writing and then the default,
like, PowerPoint blue shapes,

03:42:12.238 --> 03:42:14.978
because I just don't bother
making it look good-

03:42:15.358 --> 03:42:19.118
... Besides dragging Arnold Tsang's
art, you know, desecrating it

03:42:19.158 --> 03:42:23.008
into my deck. We put together...

03:42:23.058 --> 03:42:26.918
We had this amazing game designer
on the Overwatch team, a

03:42:26.958 --> 03:42:34.678
guy named Jeremy Craig who's now actually
game directing a game over at Bonfire.

03:42:34.758 --> 03:42:39.718
Um, Jeremy, not only was he a great
game designer, but he had the

03:42:39.758 --> 03:42:46.558
ability to sell things better than anybody
else, visually. So Jeremy took my shitty

03:42:46.698 --> 03:42:50.538
deck, and then we had lots more, like,
creative brainstorms and we thought through

03:42:50.598 --> 03:42:54.258
the game of Overwatch a lot
more, and then he made this

03:42:54.318 --> 03:42:58.078
gorgeous pitch deck that we pitched. We

03:42:58.178 --> 03:43:01.878
first had to go through the Blizzard
production and game directors

03:43:02.118 --> 03:43:06.038
for them to approve it and
give it their thumbs up,

03:43:06.658 --> 03:43:11.398
then we had to go through the Blizzard
executives, then we had to go through Activision.

03:43:11.498 --> 03:43:16.478
Um, and in that deck, because we had to

03:43:16.618 --> 03:43:20.478
speak to schedule, we had to
speak to two things that were

03:43:20.538 --> 03:43:23.998
tough to speak to. One, we
had to speak to schedule,

03:43:24.618 --> 03:43:28.398
and we came up with this concept
of crawl, walk, run. We had

03:43:28.498 --> 03:43:32.158
identified the reason Titan
failed is we just tried to

03:43:32.338 --> 03:43:36.218
run, we tried to come up with the
next World of Warcraft. But if

03:43:36.258 --> 03:43:43.718
you think about World of Warcraft, it
had Warcraft I, II, and III to build

03:43:43.778 --> 03:43:47.758
upon to even get to the point
where people gave a shit enough

03:43:47.838 --> 03:43:54.518
about that world to want to live in
the world of Warcraft. So the idea was

03:43:54.578 --> 03:43:58.318
that instead of trying to cut
right to World of Warcraft,

03:43:58.358 --> 03:44:04.998
let's try to honor Warcraft I, essentially.
So this first game is just to establish

03:44:05.758 --> 03:44:09.738
that there's a universe you
might give a shit about.

03:44:09.758 --> 03:44:13.278
We also knew that the timeframe
we were given of two years,

03:44:13.658 --> 03:44:17.398
there was no way to create a
compelling PvE experience,

03:44:17.998 --> 03:44:24.958
so we just kinda randomly put dates in a
slide of crawl, walk, run, thinking it was

03:44:25.078 --> 03:44:28.878
aspirational, and really,
we were just trying to save

03:44:28.958 --> 03:44:32.318
ourselves. Like, don't
cancel the, don't cancel

03:44:32.498 --> 03:44:36.218
us. You know, this team can
make something great. The other

03:44:36.298 --> 03:44:39.338
part that we had to talk
to too was, like, a mobile

03:44:39.518 --> 03:44:43.418
strategy. Like, at that time, it
was like, everything has to be

03:44:43.518 --> 03:44:47.588
also on mobile, which I think
is the dumbest thing ever.

03:44:47.618 --> 03:44:51.558
And so literally what we did
is, this was Jeremy's brilliant

03:44:51.658 --> 03:44:55.598
part, we had a picture with
all the boxes and then one of

03:44:55.618 --> 03:44:59.318
them is, like, a tablet
with just a fucking

03:44:59.418 --> 03:45:03.828
Photoshop of, you know, Arnold's
art on it. We're like, "And also-"

03:45:03.858 --> 03:45:03.868
- Mobile

03:45:03.868 --> 03:45:06.058
- "... it'll be on mobile."

03:45:06.118 --> 03:45:07.298
- Brilliant.

03:45:07.318 --> 03:45:11.818
But I think this crawl, walk, run idea
is really nice. So the initial idea

03:45:12.938 --> 03:45:16.818
is you would have basically a shooter with all
these different characters, all these heroes, and

03:45:16.858 --> 03:45:23.798
then the walk would be the PvE
version of that, co-op. And then

03:45:24.738 --> 03:45:28.438
if people really fall in love with the
world, then you build a big MMO around

03:45:28.478 --> 03:45:32.438
it. Quick pause for a
bathroom break. Quick

03:45:32.558 --> 03:45:36.278
30-second thank you to our sponsors.
Check them out in the description. It

03:45:36.338 --> 03:45:38.898
really is the best way to
support this podcast. Go to

03:45:38.918 --> 03:45:42.378
lexfriedman.com/sponsors. We got Fin

03:45:42.678 --> 03:45:46.418
for customer service AI agents,
Blitzy for code generation

03:45:46.458 --> 03:45:50.072
in large code bases, BetterHelp
for mental health-...

03:45:50.072 --> 03:45:53.851
Shopify for selling stuff online,
CodeRabbit for AI-powered

03:45:53.962 --> 03:45:57.062
code review, and Perplexity for

03:45:57.142 --> 03:46:00.982
curiosity-driven knowledge
exploration. Choose wisely, my

03:46:01.002 --> 03:46:04.782
friends. And now, back
to my conversation with

03:46:04.822 --> 03:46:08.752
Jeff Kaplan. And we should also say that

03:46:08.782 --> 03:46:12.642
there's a whole world that was
built around Overwatch. And

03:46:12.682 --> 03:46:16.502
one of the ideas was... So,
Warcraft is a very particular

03:46:16.602 --> 03:46:20.482
kind of world. StarCraft is a particular
kind of world. Diablo is a particular

03:46:20.502 --> 03:46:24.471
kind of world. And you wanted
to bring Overwatch to Earth and

03:46:24.542 --> 03:46:28.362
make it positive. You give
this talk where there was a

03:46:28.422 --> 03:46:35.702
lot of respect paid to the sort of dark,
gritty, post-apocalyptic games on Earth.

03:46:36.322 --> 03:46:40.262
Also gave a lot of respect to the
ultra- realistic first-person shooter

03:46:40.342 --> 03:46:41.692
games like Call of Duty.

03:46:43.042 --> 03:46:47.762
And you wanted to create something more
that paints a vision of a near-term

03:46:48.702 --> 03:46:54.702
hopeful future, and fun,
and more sort of surreal,

03:46:54.742 --> 03:47:00.242
versus like ultra-real. So it's
interesting to talk through

03:47:01.802 --> 03:47:05.322
how a world comes to life. How
you think about that world, how

03:47:05.342 --> 03:47:08.802
you create the tone of the game,
how you think, how you craft

03:47:09.822 --> 03:47:13.722
in this vision. And not just,
like, different characters like

03:47:13.762 --> 03:47:17.562
Tracer and so on, like what the
personality is, but, like, bringing the

03:47:17.622 --> 03:47:22.582
world to life in which they will
be. What was that process like?

03:47:23.102 --> 03:47:26.622
- The, the process was a blast.
And, like, the goal was that

03:47:27.182 --> 03:47:31.062
bright, hopeful future. And the
other phrase we used all the

03:47:31.182 --> 03:47:34.552
time on the team was, "A
future worth fighting for."

03:47:34.562 --> 03:47:35.132
- Mm-hmm, yes.

03:47:35.132 --> 03:47:39.002
- You know, if there's gonna be all this fighting,
like the... it kinda has to be worth it for

03:47:39.072 --> 03:47:43.002
something. Picking the
locations in the world

03:47:43.042 --> 03:47:46.182
was the funnest thing. You know,
there's just a group of us

03:47:47.322 --> 03:47:51.142
who would sit around, and be like,
"Where do you wanna go?" You

03:47:51.202 --> 03:47:54.782
know, "Santorini looks
amazing." And you're looking at

03:47:54.842 --> 03:47:58.802
pictures, and like, "Let's make
that place." You know in a

03:47:58.822 --> 03:48:05.922
video game people are gonna spend hours
and hours in a location. Resist the

03:48:05.982 --> 03:48:09.522
urge to do the common, I call
them the cargo container

03:48:09.602 --> 03:48:13.302
mazes, that you see in every
game. And I know why they

03:48:13.342 --> 03:48:15.482
exist, they're easy to make, but

03:48:16.382 --> 03:48:20.062
we kinda wanted Overwatch to
be this world tour of great

03:48:20.202 --> 03:48:26.942
places that you'd wanna go to. Or in
the case of like Oasis, it's like,

03:48:27.002 --> 03:48:31.782
okay, maybe Iraq, back when we
were making this game, wasn't the

03:48:32.762 --> 03:48:35.922
top of people's list, but
what is the bright, hopeful

03:48:36.602 --> 03:48:40.151
version of what that could look like? Um,

03:48:40.502 --> 03:48:44.072
so we just really tried to
sell this idea of these

03:48:44.072 --> 03:48:48.042
aspirational locations.
One, just to get people

03:48:48.182 --> 03:48:51.902
thinking about different places on
Planet Earth and how awesome they all

03:48:52.002 --> 03:48:55.982
are. But also, from
like a pure game design

03:48:56.062 --> 03:48:59.282
standpoint, you're gonna
spend a lot of time in the

03:48:59.322 --> 03:49:03.642
environment, so the environment should
be pleasing and not oppressive.

03:49:04.322 --> 03:49:08.022
- Can you go through some of the heroes
that you ended up putting in the game?

03:49:08.322 --> 03:49:12.002
Maybe a good way to do it is,
which are your favorites? And

03:49:12.062 --> 03:49:16.302
what's from the best of your
knowledge of the internet, favorites?

03:49:16.362 --> 03:49:22.922
- My favorite... I have a couple
favorite heroes. Obviously, Tracer.

03:49:23.062 --> 03:49:24.262
- She's the OG.

03:49:24.302 --> 03:49:27.552
- The OG, the cornerstone. You know,
we put her on the front of the

03:49:27.642 --> 03:49:32.762
box. She was that moment
of, "We should just take

03:49:33.982 --> 03:49:37.972
the best of the best," and we
know this gameplay is good and

03:49:38.062 --> 03:49:41.862
solid. And it's so simple. Like,
the mechanics are very easy to

03:49:41.902 --> 03:49:45.832
explain to somebody. It's very
easy to pick up. The first

03:49:45.842 --> 03:49:49.782
time anybody hits recall
for the first time and they

03:49:49.802 --> 03:49:53.122
try to wrap their mind around
like, "Wait, does that mean if

03:49:53.262 --> 03:49:56.272
I..." You know, and they're
mapping out the possibilities.

03:49:56.802 --> 03:50:00.642
- And by the way, we should say
that it's a PvP game with six

03:50:00.702 --> 03:50:04.222
versus six at first and
where there's three

03:50:04.302 --> 03:50:07.822
distinct roles that people take on those,

03:50:07.961 --> 03:50:15.662
On a team. And those roles, at first,
I guess were not required. Like, you

03:50:15.702 --> 03:50:18.662
can reallocate those roles
as you wanted. And then

03:50:20.002 --> 03:50:22.882
to maximize the fun, you add a
little bit of structure. You

03:50:22.962 --> 03:50:29.662
enforce two per role, and the role
being tank, support, and damage.

03:50:29.722 --> 03:50:33.702
So, that. And then there's all the kinds of
heroes that are associated with the different

03:50:33.762 --> 03:50:37.702
roles, and people pick and
there's lore. And some people

03:50:37.722 --> 03:50:40.592
are probably like hardcore
just one particular hero.

03:50:40.622 --> 03:50:44.312
And so there's a lot of personality and

03:50:44.402 --> 03:50:48.372
story and community that builds
around each of the heroes. And,

03:50:48.382 --> 03:50:51.482
but at the end of the day,
it is just a fun shooter.

03:50:51.542 --> 03:50:55.422
- Yeah. Our goal was to pay
homage to the shooters before

03:50:55.502 --> 03:50:58.752
us that we loved. There's no way you can

03:50:59.522 --> 03:51:03.662
talk about Overwatch without
talking about Team Fortress 2.

03:51:03.762 --> 03:51:10.552
Uh, Team Fortress started as a Quake
mod which was brilliant, and I played

03:51:10.602 --> 03:51:15.402
tons of. Then there was Team Fortress
Classic that came out with Half-Life 1.

03:51:15.462 --> 03:51:19.382
And then Team Fortress 2, I think
everything about it blew everybody away

03:51:19.422 --> 03:51:23.372
when it came out in 2007.
And there's obviously just

03:51:23.522 --> 03:51:29.182
huge influence there. But the
shooter mechanics of Overwatch

03:51:30.102 --> 03:51:37.851
are... They hearken back to what people
call the arcade or arena shooter

03:51:37.922 --> 03:51:41.742
genre. Which pains me 'cause I never... Back
in the day, I didn't think of Quake as a

03:51:42.402 --> 03:51:47.722
arcade shooter. It was almost an insulting
way of saying it. But just the fast

03:51:48.562 --> 03:51:56.442
movement really epic, over-the-top
weapons. You have a low time to kill, or

03:51:56.622 --> 03:52:00.542
TTK, that players call it. Meaning
you're very survivable, you can take

03:52:00.582 --> 03:52:04.022
a few hits. Where, in a game like Call of

03:52:04.142 --> 03:52:08.022
Duty or Counter-Strike, if you get
shot in the head, you're just dead

03:52:08.122 --> 03:52:14.722
right away. Um, so it was supposed to
be this explosive, larger than life,

03:52:14.782 --> 03:52:20.742
fun, arcade-y shooter- with
a lot of teamwork involved.

03:52:20.812 --> 03:52:25.342
- And so you said Tracer up
there? She's the OG. Who else?

03:52:25.402 --> 03:52:29.132
- McCree. McCree is another,
like, I'm somebody who's

03:52:29.162 --> 03:52:32.982
attracted to the simplicity
and design. And I did not

03:52:33.122 --> 03:52:36.862
design McCree's six shooter. The way that

03:52:36.962 --> 03:52:40.922
gun feels is phenomenal,
and to capture the spirit

03:52:40.962 --> 03:52:44.882
of that, we had a designer named
Mike Heiberg designed the High Noon

03:52:45.082 --> 03:52:48.942
ultimate. And then just all
the care and love the team put

03:52:48.982 --> 03:52:52.922
in, like when he does the ultimate,
we roll a tumbleweed across

03:52:52.982 --> 03:52:59.182
the screen like every time.
It's a very simple hero, but

03:53:00.142 --> 03:53:03.742
the simplicity is what I like
best in design. I'm not a fan of

03:53:04.222 --> 03:53:07.962
when somebody starts explaining, you know,
in any of these games, whether they're

03:53:08.022 --> 03:53:11.802
MOBAs or hero shooters, and
they start, like, "This guy

03:53:11.842 --> 03:53:15.772
throws orbs, and he throws three
orbs, and then he runs out of

03:53:15.782 --> 03:53:19.422
his orb bank, and then he can call the

03:53:19.502 --> 03:53:23.462
orbs back, or he can catch the
orbs." And I'm just, my head

03:53:23.502 --> 03:53:27.932
is spinning, and I'm like, "Just give
me a fucking good gun." You know?

03:53:27.932 --> 03:53:28.622
And I'm done.

03:53:28.662 --> 03:53:32.562
- Simplicity is everything. Uh,
what about Reinhardt, the tank?

03:53:32.622 --> 03:53:36.522
- Reinhardt was actually my
main. So I played the most of

03:53:36.582 --> 03:53:40.382
Reinhardt. That was another
amazing Geoff Goodman

03:53:40.442 --> 03:53:44.382
design of this guy who just has a
shield. As soon as you give somebody

03:53:44.442 --> 03:53:47.562
a shield, they know what to
do. They go into protector

03:53:47.682 --> 03:53:51.542
mode. The shield was designed
to shoot through. The shield

03:53:51.582 --> 03:53:55.382
has since been copied by like
every hero shooter since, and

03:53:55.442 --> 03:53:59.222
even non-hero shooters. And
then he just has a giant

03:53:59.362 --> 03:54:03.202
Rocket Hammer. And he
does a charge ability.

03:54:03.242 --> 03:54:07.042
It's really interesting where
the charge ability came from.

03:54:07.242 --> 03:54:11.082
I was playing a ton of
Left 4 Dead 2, and there

03:54:11.142 --> 03:54:16.782
you could play in versus mode where
you could be the enemy zombie guys.

03:54:16.802 --> 03:54:20.702
And there was an enemy boss
zombie called The Charger who had

03:54:20.802 --> 03:54:24.702
that charge ability. And I thought,
the reason that ability was so cool

03:54:24.762 --> 03:54:29.742
is because it's a commit. Once you press
the button, you're a runaway train.

03:54:29.782 --> 03:54:33.742
And watching Reinhardts charge to
their deaths is kind of hilarious,

03:54:33.782 --> 03:54:37.802
and it's what separates a
great Rein from a shitty one.

03:54:37.922 --> 03:54:41.822
- Uh, you've explained that the
Overwatch matchmaker process

03:54:41.882 --> 03:54:45.702
is designed to keep players at a
50% win rate. I think it's just a

03:54:45.782 --> 03:54:49.442
fascinating topic. Not to get
too philosophical, but you can't

03:54:49.622 --> 03:54:53.482
have the up without the
down, hence the 50%. Can,

03:54:53.522 --> 03:54:57.582
can you speak to the complexity of
like what makes a good matchmaker?

03:54:57.662 --> 03:55:02.462
- The matchmaking systems are
some of the most complex

03:55:02.702 --> 03:55:08.202
design and engineering tasks you're
ever gonna tackle. And they're

03:55:08.222 --> 03:55:11.882
thankless. It's very hard, too,

03:55:11.922 --> 03:55:15.802
because I think most people, and they're
not being disingenuous, like if you ask a

03:55:15.842 --> 03:55:19.972
gamer, "What do you want?" They're like, "I just
want a fair match. Like, just make it even."

03:55:20.822 --> 03:55:24.582
And the reality what they want is
they want a match where they're

03:55:24.702 --> 03:55:27.192
slightly better than the other guy.

03:55:27.242 --> 03:55:31.422
Like, they want it to feel like
it was close but then win.

03:55:32.562 --> 03:55:36.462
And you can't architect
that. Like, there, it's, you

03:55:36.502 --> 03:55:39.402
know, it's a zero sum situation, so

03:55:40.282 --> 03:55:43.832
there's gotta be winners and
there's gotta be losers. The other

03:55:44.182 --> 03:55:47.422
really core problem, and we would study
this all the time when people would

03:55:47.462 --> 03:55:50.662
complain. You know, you see a Reddit post,

03:55:51.222 --> 03:55:54.422
and somebody would say,
"I had a six game losing

03:55:54.582 --> 03:55:58.592
streak. This is so fucked. It's
the worst matchmaker ever."

03:55:58.622 --> 03:56:00.342
- Mm-hmm. Oh, Reddit.

03:56:00.402 --> 03:56:02.402
- Yeah, right? I love Reddit.

03:56:02.422 --> 03:56:06.222
But we would look up that person's account.
I would do that all the time. I love

03:56:06.282 --> 03:56:07.832
looking up people's accounts and seeing-

03:56:07.832 --> 03:56:11.712
... what would happen. It's like, yeah, he had
the six game losing streak. He had an eight game

03:56:11.782 --> 03:56:17.322
winning streak before that. There
was no post about how awesome is

03:56:17.422 --> 03:56:21.722
this. And the human psychology
doesn't allow for that. The

03:56:23.102 --> 03:56:26.792
... One of my hindsight regrets
about Overwatch, and this

03:56:26.862 --> 03:56:30.722
is, I think we did the right
thing in the moment. It's you

03:56:30.782 --> 03:56:34.262
know, like, I wouldn't go
back and redo it, but if I

03:56:34.302 --> 03:56:38.502
was making a hero shooter
from scratch today,

03:56:39.382 --> 03:56:43.342
I would make it less team focused. And we,

03:56:43.382 --> 03:56:48.882
we put all of our eggs in you
noticing if the team won or lost.

03:56:48.922 --> 03:56:52.642
And we downplayed your individual
contribution as much as

03:56:52.682 --> 03:56:56.462
possible. There wasn't a scoreboard.
We had a medal system, but the

03:56:56.502 --> 03:57:00.472
medal system was, in my
opinion, it was not good

03:57:00.802 --> 03:57:08.652
because the losing team got medals and
the winning team got medals. And on the

03:57:08.742 --> 03:57:12.202
losing team, they would use that. They
would weaponize it against their teammate.

03:57:12.212 --> 03:57:16.132
"Well, I'm the top kills, and all
you guys are making us lose." And

03:57:16.142 --> 03:57:20.082
it's like, "Okay, you're the top
kills by like one, and you guys still

03:57:20.162 --> 03:57:27.942
lost." So I would, if I was to redo it
today, or for any aspiring hero shooter

03:57:28.022 --> 03:57:34.822
makers out there, I would actually downplay
the team factor, and try to put more

03:57:34.882 --> 03:57:40.732
focus on individual contribution. Because
that's just how people play. They're

03:57:40.942 --> 03:57:44.442
selfish. And I don't mean
that in a bad way. It's

03:57:44.502 --> 03:57:47.962
just, it's that human
nature, they can't help.

03:57:48.022 --> 03:57:51.862
- And in terms of how they experience the
game, in terms of how they derive joy from

03:57:51.942 --> 03:57:55.802
it, or how they see the challenge of
the game is individual. Even when

03:57:55.842 --> 03:57:57.562
you're on a team, you're still feeling-

03:57:57.842 --> 03:58:01.702
... it's individual, fundamental
individual experience. Uh,

03:58:01.742 --> 03:58:05.442
let me, as a small aside,
before I forget, since we

03:58:05.482 --> 03:58:09.462
mentioned first person shooters so
much, outside of Overwatch, what are

03:58:09.502 --> 03:58:14.458
some of the great shooters?...
of all time that you've played?

03:58:14.518 --> 03:58:16.338
- Quake is the greatest.

03:58:16.398 --> 03:58:17.458
- Quake is GOAT.

03:58:17.538 --> 03:58:23.618
- Yeah. Quake is GOAT. There's
a lot of contenders up there.

03:58:23.638 --> 03:58:27.677
- What have you logged the most
hours in outside of the games?

03:58:27.698 --> 03:58:27.708
- Rust.

03:58:27.738 --> 03:58:32.418
- Okay. Can you... Okay. Uh, a lot of folks

03:58:33.718 --> 03:58:37.518
have written to me that I need to play Rust,
the video game. I have not, have not even

03:58:37.558 --> 03:58:41.358
looked into it. Somebody on Reddit
said it has a steep learning

03:58:41.398 --> 03:58:45.358
curve. I would like to give it a
chance because I've spoke... You have,

03:58:45.398 --> 03:58:48.838
to me, spoken so highly of
it. So can you explain Rust?

03:58:48.898 --> 03:58:52.578
- Yeah. Rust is an open world game.

03:58:52.678 --> 03:58:56.668
It's a procedural map, so it
means that every time it's

03:58:56.718 --> 03:59:02.907
different. You're always on an island,
and it resets every month. So-

03:59:02.938 --> 03:59:03.898
- Is it PvP?

03:59:03.998 --> 03:59:12.418
- It's all PvP. In fact, Rust is
the most PvP thing in all of PvP.

03:59:12.438 --> 03:59:15.477
- Well, I don't know what that means, but-

03:59:15.518 --> 03:59:16.938
- Rust players know what that means.

03:59:16.998 --> 03:59:20.948
- Everybody who plays Rust and loves it
sounds to me like they're in a cult.

03:59:20.978 --> 03:59:24.438
So with all due respect,
please don't write me letters.

03:59:24.478 --> 03:59:28.218
- They're too busy playing Rust. They're too
busy checking on their base, making sure it's

03:59:28.258 --> 03:59:30.728
not raided, to write you letters.

03:59:30.758 --> 03:59:31.298
- Oh, good.

03:59:31.598 --> 03:59:37.578
- Um, it takes place... It's
basically... It's open world.

03:59:37.638 --> 03:59:41.418
You can do whatever you want. There's
not really any directed gameplay to

03:59:41.558 --> 03:59:49.048
it, but at any time, any other player can
kill you and take anything that's on you.

03:59:49.118 --> 03:59:50.408
- Oh, wow.

03:59:50.458 --> 03:59:54.178
- Yeah, and then you build what
Rust players call bases, and you

03:59:54.238 --> 03:59:58.178
upgrade the base, and you try to
make the base as safe as possible to

03:59:58.298 --> 04:00:01.478
store your stuff, and then you can make

04:00:01.518 --> 04:00:05.318
explosives and blow up
other people's walls to

04:00:05.378 --> 04:00:09.198
get into their base where they're
keeping all their best stuff

04:00:09.778 --> 04:00:11.138
and take all their shit.

04:00:11.178 --> 04:00:12.578
- It, like, permanently?

04:00:12.598 --> 04:00:14.458
- Permanently. Like-

04:00:14.578 --> 04:00:15.068
- Oh, I see

04:00:15.068 --> 04:00:19.497
- ... it would be like PvPing in
WoW. Imagine in World of Warcraft-

04:00:19.678 --> 04:00:22.978
... if somebody could not only kill you

04:00:23.518 --> 04:00:27.058
but take everything that's in
your bank and make you level

04:00:27.218 --> 04:00:29.388
one the next time you log in.

04:00:29.418 --> 04:00:32.218
- Wow. That's very stressful.

04:00:32.258 --> 04:00:35.998
- The beauty of Rust, and why it's so good,

04:00:36.058 --> 04:00:41.098
is you can't have the high highs
without the low lows. And-

04:00:41.138 --> 04:00:42.498
- Like, real low lows.

04:00:42.738 --> 04:00:43.938
- Real low lows.

04:00:43.978 --> 04:00:45.227
- Wow. All right.

04:00:45.227 --> 04:00:49.718
- Like, debilitating, like, "Am I
ever gonna play this game?" lows.

04:00:49.727 --> 04:00:49.738
- Right.

04:00:49.758 --> 04:00:53.638
- You know, like, you spend
a week building the

04:00:53.698 --> 04:00:57.488
world's most perfect base and
getting tons of loot, and

04:00:57.538 --> 04:01:01.518
then it... There's what's
called online raiding

04:01:01.558 --> 04:01:05.537
and offline raiding.
Online raiding means that

04:01:06.098 --> 04:01:09.558
my enemy is... I can see that
they're in their base right

04:01:09.618 --> 04:01:14.118
now, and I'm gonna try to attack
them while they're in their base.

04:01:14.218 --> 04:01:18.058
Offlining, which is, like, all
Rust players will say you're the

04:01:18.158 --> 04:01:22.018
scum of the Earth if you
offline someone, and

04:01:22.058 --> 04:01:26.518
then all Rust players also
offline people all the time.

04:01:26.598 --> 04:01:27.038
- Ah.

04:01:27.098 --> 04:01:28.078
- Yeah. It's—

04:01:28.198 --> 04:01:28.308
- Yes

04:01:28.418 --> 04:01:29.558
- ... gamer etiquette.

04:01:29.618 --> 04:01:29.838
- Yes.

04:01:29.898 --> 04:01:33.578
- Um, offline's when, like,
"Hey, I think that my

04:01:33.638 --> 04:01:37.418
neighbor logged off for the night.
You know, they, they just played six

04:01:37.458 --> 04:01:40.798
hours. I've been watching them, and
now there's no activity in their

04:01:40.838 --> 04:01:44.738
base, so I'm gonna, like, blow up their walls
and take up all their stuff when they're not

04:01:44.798 --> 04:01:45.067
here."

04:01:45.078 --> 04:01:50.328
- Mm-hmm. Yeah. So Rust, because real life is
not hard enough, is what it sounds like.

04:01:50.328 --> 04:01:50.768
Just, I want... If I want—

04:01:50.768 --> 04:01:51.838
- That'd be a great tag.

04:01:51.878 --> 04:01:55.818
- If I want more stress in my life, I'll
play Rust. Yeah. I can't wait. So

04:01:55.958 --> 04:01:59.878
okay, so that's one. That, that
sounds like a unique experience

04:02:00.238 --> 04:02:06.318
and a great joy. So quick
number one, Rust is up there.

04:02:06.378 --> 04:02:07.438
- Call of Duty.

04:02:07.478 --> 04:02:08.668
- Call of Duty just has its own-

04:02:08.698 --> 04:02:12.238
- You, you know, there's a lot of
haters. Like, Call of Duty 4

04:02:12.658 --> 04:02:16.058
and Modern Warfare 2 were
the pinnacle of Call of

04:02:16.158 --> 04:02:19.978
Duty, with Black Ops being
a very respectable, you

04:02:20.018 --> 04:02:23.618
know, third. But you're
never gonna get a better

04:02:23.778 --> 04:02:27.658
gun feel from a game
than— Like, just study

04:02:27.798 --> 04:02:31.118
the visual effects, the
animation, the modeling, the

04:02:31.278 --> 04:02:38.958
sounds. Every aspect of shooting a gun in
Call of Duty is so masterfully done. And

04:02:38.998 --> 04:02:42.958
then the maps, like, the flow
of the multiplayer is just

04:02:43.038 --> 04:02:46.658
great. Like, there's... There's
a map called Crash from

04:02:46.998 --> 04:02:50.878
Call of Duty 4 that Erin Keller
and I... Erin's now the game

04:02:50.898 --> 04:02:54.658
director on Overwatch. We just
sat and studied that map, or

04:02:54.738 --> 04:02:58.298
Terminal from Modern
Warfare 2. Just studied the

04:02:58.358 --> 04:03:02.338
maps of just, like, this
map design is off the

04:03:02.398 --> 04:03:05.658
hook. So Call of Duty
is definitely up there.

04:03:05.718 --> 04:03:09.478
- So even though you were not
thinking about it Overwatch

04:03:09.538 --> 04:03:13.138
ended up being a gigantic success. So

04:03:14.098 --> 04:03:18.078
did you start thinking about, in
this framework of crawl, walk,

04:03:18.138 --> 04:03:23.918
run, about the walk, the PvE piece?

04:03:23.958 --> 04:03:31.378
- Yes. So the PvE piece was what
Overwatch 2 was supposed to be.

04:03:31.448 --> 04:03:36.338
And I don't know if people
know this or not, but we

04:03:36.458 --> 04:03:43.098
started working on Overwatch 2 in 2015.

04:03:43.118 --> 04:03:43.128
- ♪ Over- ♪

04:03:43.158 --> 04:03:49.138
- So, Overwatch 1 didn't
ship until 2016. So before

04:03:49.798 --> 04:03:55.558
Overwatch... And it wasn't like work in
earnest. It was like pitching the game.

04:03:56.438 --> 04:04:00.238
Um, I remember I spent a lot
of time... It was myself,

04:04:00.278 --> 04:04:04.178
Chris Metzen, and Michael
Chu sort of brainstorming a

04:04:04.218 --> 04:04:07.678
framework for what, like,
a campaign could look

04:04:07.718 --> 04:04:11.358
like. And we had this idea
of, like, a cooperative

04:04:11.438 --> 04:04:14.854
PvE shooter. And we
actually pitched it to the

04:04:15.234 --> 04:04:19.134
team before we launched because we were
trying to put a bunch of runway in front

04:04:19.194 --> 04:04:24.494
of us. That worked against us, and it's
one of my biggest mistakes I've made

04:04:24.554 --> 04:04:31.294
as a creative leader in my career, was
Overwatch 2. There were two points of failure

04:04:31.594 --> 04:04:37.514
for me. The first was, I
had people on the game team

04:04:38.534 --> 04:04:42.374
who didn't like PvP or
competitive shooters,

04:04:42.894 --> 04:04:46.414
and they really loved the Overwatch
universe and wanted to play these

04:04:46.454 --> 04:04:50.334
characters and heroes, but they wanted
to kind of do it on their own terms

04:04:50.454 --> 04:04:54.414
in like a PvE setting. So even though

04:04:54.423 --> 04:04:58.374
Overwatch is this like runaway success
and everybody's talking about it, they

04:04:58.434 --> 04:05:02.264
felt like they couldn't really engage
with it. And so like people on

04:05:02.294 --> 04:05:09.054
the dev team are like, "Okay, thank God
we, you know, shipped that PvP thing-"

04:05:09.063 --> 04:05:12.894
"... When do we start work on
this other thing?" So that came

04:05:12.994 --> 04:05:19.334
from a genuine place of excitement.
And then the other point of pressure

04:05:20.174 --> 04:05:23.774
was from the executive
team, and this was both the

04:05:24.114 --> 04:05:27.984
Blizzard and more so the
Activision executive

04:05:28.094 --> 04:05:34.374
teams, and they started really putting
the heat on, "Well, you said Overwatch

04:05:35.814 --> 04:05:39.594
2 was gonna be out in 2019."
And they're referring back to

04:05:39.654 --> 04:05:42.424
these slides that were
just crazy dates. Like-

04:05:42.424 --> 04:05:46.294
... it was... You never want
to put a PowerPoint deck

04:05:46.334 --> 04:05:50.214
in front of a corporate executive.
Like, you might as well

04:05:50.334 --> 04:05:52.854
etch it in stone and come
down from the mountain on it.

04:05:53.194 --> 04:05:56.274
- So you just threw some dates
because the layout looked good.

04:05:56.374 --> 04:05:58.754
- Yeah. This is just all bullshit.

04:05:59.894 --> 04:06:03.374
This is just... In the same way we
put, like, the tablet, you know?

04:06:03.394 --> 04:06:07.374
We just put Overwatch, like put
Tracer on a tablet and say we have a

04:06:07.414 --> 04:06:09.234
mobile strategy.

04:06:09.374 --> 04:06:16.074
So the executives started getting really
angry at us that Overwatch 2 was slipping,

04:06:16.114 --> 04:06:22.634
slipping. And so when Overwatch 1 took off,
I remember very early, we were in like

04:06:22.894 --> 04:06:30.774
May of 2016, and that year the
Olympics were gonna be in Rio, I

04:06:30.834 --> 04:06:36.954
think. Um, and, you know, I always
like to pay respects to, like, when a

04:06:37.014 --> 04:06:40.934
big event is happening, I'm like,
"Hey, we should do, like, an

04:06:41.014 --> 04:06:44.854
event for the Olympics." You can't call it
the Olympics or else they sue you, so you

04:06:45.094 --> 04:06:47.514
just... Even though you're
advertising for them

04:06:48.394 --> 04:06:52.594
to a bunch of kids who want to play video
games and not watch the Olympics. But

04:06:54.554 --> 04:06:58.074
we also had like these two
developers, Mike Heiberg and Dave

04:06:58.174 --> 04:07:01.374
Adams, like worked on this
quirky... Like, they made

04:07:01.434 --> 04:07:05.924
soccer in Overwatch. We
called it Lúcioball.

04:07:05.924 --> 04:07:09.734
Like, they made a map and they
made these mechanics. We're like,

04:07:09.754 --> 04:07:13.034
"Yeah, we... Let's do an event
called the Summer Games."

04:07:13.074 --> 04:07:16.874
And we do a live patch
that's the Summer Games.

04:07:16.934 --> 04:07:20.814
It's extremely successful. And then after

04:07:20.874 --> 04:07:24.594
that, we're like, "Yeah, let's
do... Halloween's coming up.

04:07:24.634 --> 04:07:31.394
Let's do a Halloween event. How cool will
that be?" And our fans just loved these

04:07:31.414 --> 04:07:35.034
events, but there were two
groups that were struggling with

04:07:35.094 --> 04:07:38.834
it. One was that group I told you on the

04:07:38.874 --> 04:07:42.314
dev team who was like,
"Oh my God, you guys are

04:07:42.434 --> 04:07:46.114
over-scoping the patches.
Why are we doing this

04:07:46.174 --> 04:07:49.894
Halloween event? We should be doing... We

04:07:49.954 --> 04:07:53.924
should start work on Overwatch 2.
We shouldn't be this focused on

04:07:53.954 --> 04:07:57.254
the live game," which was fucking

04:07:57.274 --> 04:08:01.014
nuts. Like, that was just
crazy. There's this phrase of

04:08:01.074 --> 04:08:04.874
catch the wave, ride the wave. Most
games fall off the back of the

04:08:04.914 --> 04:08:08.794
wave. They don't catch the wave. No
one plays it or plays it for two

04:08:08.834 --> 04:08:15.074
weeks. If you're lucky enough to have
caught the wave- ... ride it till the end.

04:08:15.134 --> 04:08:20.343
And my instincts at that point were like,
"Let's just keep... How many more of these

04:08:20.394 --> 04:08:22.444
live events can we do?"

04:08:22.474 --> 04:08:26.134
- So yeah. So now there's
this wave in the live game

04:08:26.654 --> 04:08:31.534
and events, but the pressure on
creating Overwatch 2 was building.

04:08:31.854 --> 04:08:35.794
- Yeah. We had a coalition on the
team that was... Really wanted

04:08:35.894 --> 04:08:39.774
Overwatch 2 built instead of the
live events. And then the executive

04:08:39.894 --> 04:08:47.794
pressure became monumental. And what
would have been correct was to do more

04:08:47.874 --> 04:08:55.394
world events, like keep it going, but
the major derail was Overwatch League.

04:08:55.454 --> 04:09:00.414
And we really like... The
weirdest part about Overwatch

04:09:00.514 --> 04:09:04.374
League is I believe in it.
You know, I helped pitch

04:09:04.434 --> 04:09:08.154
it along with some other
people. We thought it

04:09:08.214 --> 04:09:11.614
was like the future of esports
and doing regional based

04:09:11.894 --> 04:09:15.534
teams, ensuring minimum
player salaries and player

04:09:15.614 --> 04:09:19.654
protections. Like, there was a lot
of very good about Overwatch League.

04:09:20.054 --> 04:09:22.914
- And there would be teams
associated with particular cities.

04:09:22.934 --> 04:09:23.004
- Yes.

04:09:23.014 --> 04:09:26.974
- And it would be international. It would
be real competition. So the dream,

04:09:26.984 --> 04:09:28.874
the ambition was really huge there.

04:09:29.014 --> 04:09:32.784
- Yeah. The teams part of the
dream was more of like regional

04:09:32.914 --> 04:09:36.454
based, player protection, try to make

04:09:36.634 --> 04:09:40.534
esports more of a first class citizen,
because there were all these stories about

04:09:40.594 --> 04:09:43.954
like shady teams, you know,
screwing their players over.

04:09:45.514 --> 04:09:51.254
Where it got away from us was there was a
lot of excitement about Overwatch League,

04:09:52.074 --> 04:09:55.914
like too much so, and then
it got over marketed to the

04:09:55.994 --> 04:09:59.794
people buying the teams. They went on

04:09:59.834 --> 04:10:03.744
this road show where they
had a deck basically, and

04:10:03.774 --> 04:10:07.214
like you could put anything in a
deck and sell anything, and they

04:10:07.254 --> 04:10:10.934
were pretty much selling
the Brooklyn Bridge,

04:10:11.014 --> 04:10:15.724
that Overwatch League was going
to be more popular than the NFL.

04:10:15.754 --> 04:10:23.190
And we got a bunch of......
billionaire investors in these teams.

04:10:23.270 --> 04:10:29.410
And when 2018 started, like
for example the day I got

04:10:29.550 --> 04:10:34.170
back, they said, "We signed
this huge deal with Twitch

04:10:35.210 --> 04:10:39.070
for streaming of Overwatch League,"
like a media rights deal. And

04:10:39.610 --> 04:10:43.550
that means that here's all
these commitments we made

04:10:43.610 --> 04:10:47.560
for Overwatch League of like in-game
stuff that had to exist. Like a lot

04:10:47.590 --> 04:10:50.930
of it was integration
with Twitch and camera

04:10:50.990 --> 04:10:54.990
control and that kind of stuff. The
other part of it was a bunch of skins

04:10:55.870 --> 04:10:58.980
and you know, uniforms for all the

04:10:58.990 --> 04:11:02.790
teams, which was not just getting
the art in the game, but there was

04:11:02.850 --> 04:11:06.770
huge technical challenges to,
like, how all that worked

04:11:06.810 --> 04:11:10.779
and was efficient and hit the right,
you know, memory footprint and all of

04:11:10.830 --> 04:11:14.630
that kind of stuff. And so all of

04:11:14.670 --> 04:11:18.610
your plans at that point kind
of go out the window. Like

04:11:18.620 --> 04:11:21.850
you're not gonna work on new world
events. You're not really even focused

04:11:21.929 --> 04:11:27.440
on Overwatch 2, you're just
kind of treading water.

04:11:27.470 --> 04:11:32.950
There was a lot of talk of like,
"Oh God, you know, the deal, like,

04:11:33.850 --> 04:11:37.750
the deal didn't go well and we've got to
do make goods to make the deal better

04:11:37.790 --> 04:11:41.670
for them." I'm like, "Just give them
some money back, you know?" Like, if

04:11:41.730 --> 04:11:48.610
you... The deal isn't what people wanted,
like, putting it on us, the Overwatch

04:11:48.630 --> 04:11:56.970
team, to, like, support this beast.
And it was a great idea that

04:11:57.970 --> 04:12:04.410
the wrong instincts and sort of, I
don't know how to phrase this in a way

04:12:04.450 --> 04:12:08.310
that's not damning, but there was too

04:12:08.330 --> 04:12:11.560
much focus on, "Let's
make lots of money really

04:12:11.710 --> 04:12:18.980
fast." And a lot of people got dragged into
it. And while Overwatch League was great

04:12:19.090 --> 04:12:22.810
for Overwatch in terms of
the players that it brought

04:12:22.910 --> 04:12:26.850
in, like and the Overwatch League players,

04:12:26.910 --> 04:12:30.730
they were awesome. I love them.
The Overwatch League staff

04:12:30.750 --> 04:12:36.120
at Blizzard, some of the nicest, most
motivated, great creative people-

04:12:36.120 --> 04:12:39.990
... like all of these organizations
got built and they were all

04:12:40.000 --> 04:12:43.320
great, but it was a house
of cards waiting to fall.

04:12:43.330 --> 04:12:46.980
- And when it became more
about the money versus,

04:12:47.130 --> 04:12:50.810
The quality of the experience of the
different teams playing together and

04:12:50.890 --> 04:12:55.050
actually building this
ecosystem of esports.

04:12:55.060 --> 04:13:02.179
- The financial reality kicked in,
where these teams now, we didn't just

04:13:02.230 --> 04:13:06.150
have, you know, executives at
Activision and Blizzard who cared

04:13:06.230 --> 04:13:11.150
about the bottom line of Overwatch.
We had all these people who

04:13:11.990 --> 04:13:15.920
basically invested in the game, and

04:13:15.950 --> 04:13:19.750
then they started to express
their opinions. Originally, the

04:13:19.790 --> 04:13:24.330
business model was going to be that
they were going to do in-person

04:13:25.170 --> 04:13:29.030
events and there's going to
be big ticket sales and then

04:13:29.110 --> 04:13:30.950
merch, you know, and all of that.

04:13:31.970 --> 04:13:35.850
And I think really quickly
everybody learned like, yeah, we

04:13:35.910 --> 04:13:39.750
can't do in-game events when you have
a London team and a Shanghai team

04:13:39.810 --> 04:13:47.690
and, like, how does this work? So that
fell apart super quickly. The merch was

04:13:47.750 --> 04:13:51.490
good, but it wasn't going to
be making NFL level money-

04:13:51.500 --> 04:13:54.190
... whatever insanity anybody
thought that was going to be.

04:13:55.030 --> 04:13:58.950
So everybody quickly
defaulted back to, "Hey,

04:13:59.590 --> 04:14:03.330
didn't Overwatch make like $500 million

04:14:03.530 --> 04:14:07.450
just in the live game last year?
What can we sell and what can you

04:14:07.490 --> 04:14:10.710
give us?" That pressure
comes onto the team,

04:14:12.070 --> 04:14:20.170
and then the pressure to ship Overwatch
2 and all care and love that we had

04:14:20.910 --> 04:14:24.580
for, like, the live game and the live
server, "Let's just make events and new

04:14:24.630 --> 04:14:32.239
heroes and new maps," we're losing all
these resources. And it got to the

04:14:32.330 --> 04:14:36.269
point, you know, my exit at

04:14:36.290 --> 04:14:40.230
Blizzard, I believed in Overwatch
2. I think we could have made

04:14:40.270 --> 04:14:44.250
a great game. I have a lot of hindsight of,
like, how I would have designed that game

04:14:44.310 --> 04:14:48.010
differently with what I know now versus

04:14:48.090 --> 04:14:51.870
what ultimately we didn't ship.
And there's Overwatch 2 is out

04:14:51.970 --> 04:14:57.090
now, but it's not the Overwatch
2 that we planned and announced.

04:14:57.130 --> 04:15:00.770
- So when you're referring to Overwatch 2 in
this conversation, you're referring to the PvE

04:15:00.870 --> 04:15:01.280
version?

04:15:01.310 --> 04:15:02.750
- The PvE version.

04:15:02.770 --> 04:15:04.290
- Which, by the way, I
would have loved to play.

04:15:04.310 --> 04:15:07.490
I'm one of the people that were...
Overwatch is great, but the

04:15:07.530 --> 04:15:12.130
PvP, but I would have loved
to play the PvE version.

04:15:12.210 --> 04:15:15.170
- I think everybody would have loved
to have played it. And there's a

04:15:15.230 --> 04:15:22.950
misconception online that all I cared
about was PvE and I didn't care about PvP.

04:15:22.990 --> 04:15:28.210
All of the Overwatch 2 PvP maps were

04:15:28.990 --> 04:15:32.830
something that I said to the team
over and over, "We have a PvP

04:15:32.840 --> 04:15:36.790
audience. If we get anything right,
it has to be the PvP." We would

04:15:36.830 --> 04:15:41.380
be lucky to welcome these PvE
players, but that's not guaranteed.

04:15:42.210 --> 04:15:46.790
So it was never a PvE only focus.

04:15:46.810 --> 04:15:50.170
- It's just almost expanding
it to also the E.

04:15:50.230 --> 04:15:58.010
- Yeah. And what eventually broke me was it
used to be like in 2016 and 2017, I felt

04:15:58.070 --> 04:16:01.910
very in control of the Overwatch

04:16:02.070 --> 04:16:05.970
team and the direction of the
game as a game director, you

04:16:06.010 --> 04:16:09.850
know, working with Ray Gresko as the production
director, it felt like we were running

04:16:09.990 --> 04:16:15.240
Overwatch. And we were very, very
successful and doing a good job.

04:16:15.250 --> 04:16:18.510
And I think the fans were
happy. And then as we

04:16:18.810 --> 04:16:22.790
transitioned, you know,
Overwatch League was

04:16:22.830 --> 04:16:26.570
the best intention. You know, my parents always
say, "The road to hell is paved with good

04:16:26.630 --> 04:16:30.490
intentions." That was the Overwatch
League, and it ended up being an

04:16:30.570 --> 04:16:34.154
albatross. And then
Overwatch 2 is the same

04:16:34.234 --> 04:16:38.274
thing. And what it boiled down
for me, like what sort of

04:16:39.494 --> 04:16:47.394
ultimately broke me in my Blizzard career
was I got called into the CFO's office,

04:16:47.514 --> 04:16:57.644
and he sits me down and he says, it, he
gives me a date, which at the time was

04:16:57.834 --> 04:17:01.754
2020 and was going to
slip to 2021, but at the

04:17:01.814 --> 04:17:06.294
time, it was 2020. And he
said, "Overwatch has to make

04:17:07.954 --> 04:17:13.674
in 2020, and then every year after
that, it needs a recurring revenue of

04:17:13.734 --> 04:17:22.234
." And then he says to me,
"If it doesn't do dollars,

04:17:23.754 --> 04:17:27.114
we're gonna lay off a thousand
people, and that's gonna be on

04:17:27.214 --> 04:17:33.254
you." And that was just the biggest
fuck you moment I had in my

04:17:33.314 --> 04:17:40.964
career. It felt surreal to be in that
condition. And as somebody who's worked on a

04:17:40.994 --> 04:17:42.874
lot of games, made a lot of games,

04:17:43.954 --> 04:17:47.634
you get in these meetings where they're
like, "There's Fortnite has 1,400

04:17:47.674 --> 04:17:50.794
people working on it. If you just hire

04:17:51.794 --> 04:17:55.674
1,400 people and make it
free-to-play, we'll make that

04:17:55.734 --> 04:17:58.864
money, right?" And that was, I had

04:17:59.974 --> 04:18:03.954
believed I would never work
any place but Blizzard.

04:18:04.014 --> 04:18:06.314
I loved it. It was a part of who I was,

04:18:07.254 --> 04:18:11.194
And I felt I was a part of it,
and I literally thought I would

04:18:11.254 --> 04:18:15.624
retire from the place. I never
thought the day would come, and

04:18:16.434 --> 04:18:20.634
that was it. I was like, it's,

04:18:21.494 --> 04:18:25.334
we're done here. Luckily for Blizzard,
that CFO is no longer there.

04:18:25.374 --> 04:18:30.864
- I mean, Blizzard is one of the greatest
companies in the history of Earth. They've

04:18:30.914 --> 04:18:34.174
created so many incredible
video games. It's so

04:18:34.194 --> 04:18:37.894
difficult to create so many
hits, and they were done

04:18:37.994 --> 04:18:44.614
not by chasing money. They're
done by small incredible teams,

04:18:45.454 --> 04:18:49.154
the hodgepodge that you describe

04:18:49.194 --> 04:18:53.174
taking big risks and falling in love
with the thing they do and then

04:18:53.234 --> 04:18:55.564
just chasing it, working
extremely hard. And

04:18:56.434 --> 04:19:00.134
just because you figured out a way how
to make a lot of money doesn't mean it's

04:19:00.214 --> 04:19:07.094
not, at the core this
incredible creative journey

04:19:07.394 --> 04:19:11.304
that's incredibly difficult
to pull off. And just

04:19:11.374 --> 04:19:15.154
because you got a bunch of
really smart creative people who

04:19:15.214 --> 04:19:19.163
have somehow figured out how to pull
it off multiple times in a row doesn't

04:19:19.194 --> 04:19:23.184
mean you can just treat it like
a machine. Every single time,

04:19:23.214 --> 04:19:29.214
it's this beautiful journey of a hodgepodge
of weirdos working together, and

04:19:29.274 --> 04:19:33.074
weirdos have to run that thing. If you

04:19:33.134 --> 04:19:36.774
have, ever have a chance to create
something special, you have to have

04:19:36.854 --> 04:19:40.794
weirdos at the helm. And it, it,
the degree to which you don't have

04:19:40.834 --> 04:19:44.134
weirdos at the helm,
creative minds at the helm,

04:19:45.274 --> 04:19:48.714
And you're a businessperson
at the helm, get out of their

04:19:48.754 --> 04:19:52.564
way, right? You can't, you cannot
have the meetings like you're

04:19:52.614 --> 04:19:56.354
describing. And I don't just
speak about this particular

04:19:56.454 --> 04:19:59.994
company. It's just the
entire industry. I just,

04:20:00.774 --> 04:20:04.214
there's so much joy to be had
if we keep creating great

04:20:04.294 --> 04:20:08.814
games, and I just hope we get
to see those great games.

04:20:09.374 --> 04:20:12.974
- I think there's a message to
creative people out there and

04:20:13.094 --> 04:20:20.074
people who make stuff. We're generally,
we're so focused on the love of the craft

04:20:21.074 --> 04:20:27.054
that we get lost in it and we love
doing it, and we're not cutthroat

04:20:28.174 --> 04:20:32.414
and we don't have that kind of ambition.
We have a different kind of ambition.

04:20:33.854 --> 04:20:37.574
But there's this whole world, especially
as soon as you're lucky enough to have

04:20:37.634 --> 04:20:44.734
success, that are very cutthroat and
very ambitious. And for whatever reason,

04:20:44.794 --> 04:20:52.854
we keep giving ourselves to them,
and we need to stop giving our

04:20:52.914 --> 04:20:56.674
so... World of Warcraft, when
we made it, there was no

04:20:56.714 --> 04:21:00.634
CFO at Blizzard. You
don't need a CFO to make

04:21:00.654 --> 04:21:04.574
World of Warcraft. You need
artists, engineers, designers,

04:21:04.754 --> 04:21:07.474
producers, and an audio team.

04:21:07.494 --> 04:21:11.354
- You don't need to bring in... Just because you're
making a lot of money doesn't mean you need to

04:21:11.414 --> 04:21:16.474
now start adulting by bringing
in a CFO. You can figure it out.

04:21:16.494 --> 04:21:20.344
- And there are great finance guys. Like
I've worked with finance guys who get

04:21:20.414 --> 04:21:24.134
it and get out of the way and
respect, and they're gamers,

04:21:24.614 --> 04:21:27.374
and they sort of understand, but like,

04:21:29.254 --> 04:21:34.214
I wish developers would
understand their own value more

04:21:35.114 --> 04:21:39.694
and stop handing the golden goose
to people who don't deserve it.

04:21:40.994 --> 04:21:43.974
- How painful was it to say goodbye?

04:21:44.054 --> 04:21:50.414
- Uh, it broke me. I think after you've
been at a place like Blizzard, which

04:21:50.654 --> 04:21:54.534
I love Blizzard. To this day, I

04:21:54.574 --> 04:21:57.974
have nothing but warm, fond
memories. I mean, there's those

04:21:58.074 --> 04:22:01.114
moments where you're like, "I
wish that hadn't happened," but

04:22:01.994 --> 04:22:08.454
on the whole, that place is mecca for
game development, and everything I have

04:22:10.514 --> 04:22:18.094
is due to Blizzard. They provided for me
and my family, made me the person I am, so

04:22:18.474 --> 04:22:21.954
separating from Blizzard was one
of the most painful things. And

04:22:22.014 --> 04:22:28.794
I was very sad when I resigned,
and I didn't realize how broken I

04:22:28.854 --> 04:22:34.794
was until recently, like the mourning,
grieving I had gone through of

04:22:34.874 --> 04:22:38.858
like...I think I'm a little
fucked in the head for not being

04:22:38.898 --> 04:22:42.878
there any... How could I give that up?
How could I not be there anymore? It

04:22:42.938 --> 04:22:48.438
It was really, really painful leaving.

04:22:48.478 --> 04:22:49.748
- Can we just speak to,

04:22:50.778 --> 04:22:54.158
I don't know, I don't think we can
give enough love to Blizzard. It's a

04:22:54.258 --> 04:22:55.838
legendary company.

04:22:57.438 --> 04:23:01.228
For me personally, for everybody, for
millions of people, created some of the

04:23:01.298 --> 04:23:05.278
greatest games ever, Warcraft,
StarCraft Universe, Diablo, WoW,

04:23:05.378 --> 04:23:09.358
Overwatch. What made it such a
legendary game company? Just

04:23:09.418 --> 04:23:11.818
looking back at the whole of it?

04:23:11.898 --> 04:23:17.578
- The start is Mike, Allen, and
Frank. It was run by three

04:23:17.678 --> 04:23:24.798
gamers. They were, all three of them,
programmers. They made the games before

04:23:24.818 --> 04:23:28.798
they just ran the company,
so they knew what each

04:23:28.878 --> 04:23:34.128
of us as developers beneath them were
going through, and they protected us.

04:23:34.128 --> 04:23:38.058
They shielded us from all of the nonsense,

04:23:38.078 --> 04:23:41.538
and even when they would align
with a businessperson, they had a

04:23:41.618 --> 04:23:47.328
COO in the early days named Paul
Sams, and Paul protected us.

04:23:47.758 --> 04:23:51.638
You know, they just, they found
great people who got it. The

04:23:51.718 --> 04:23:59.178
company when I joined was, like, 95%
developers and, like, 5% operations. It's,

04:23:59.478 --> 04:24:07.258
when I left, it was, you know, 50/50, and
that's like a 4,500-person company. That

04:24:08.078 --> 04:24:14.658
love of the games and the respect and
good treatment for game developers

04:24:15.558 --> 04:24:20.138
really turned it into the place that it
was, just the commitment to excellence,

04:24:20.978 --> 04:24:28.158
the high-quality bar and then finding
these passionate people like Chris

04:24:28.258 --> 04:24:32.198
Metzen or Sam Didier, they were, like,

04:24:32.238 --> 04:24:35.938
the visionaries of early
Blizzard, Allen Adham, of

04:24:36.018 --> 04:24:42.198
just these worlds that we're still
making and we're still playing in today.

04:24:43.478 --> 04:24:50.498
it was infectious and it was inspirational,
and you wore the Blizzard blue with an

04:24:50.558 --> 04:24:54.238
esprit de corps. Like, you
felt proud to be part of it

04:24:54.278 --> 04:24:57.508
and you felt like you
had made it to be there,

04:24:57.598 --> 04:25:01.538
and everything you did, you did wanting to

04:25:01.558 --> 04:25:05.198
respect and honor those
who had come before you.

04:25:05.318 --> 04:25:09.308
I know that sounds almost
cheesy saying it that way,

04:25:09.318 --> 04:25:13.047
but it really had that sense of reverence,
like you knew you were part of something

04:25:13.138 --> 04:25:15.238
special. You didn't take it for granted.

04:25:15.298 --> 04:25:19.178
- Yeah. That's the sense. Reading everything, that's
the sense I got. Everybody there was a part of it

04:25:19.778 --> 04:25:26.748
that truly, truly, truly honored that time.
Just to take a small slice, what were

04:25:26.758 --> 04:25:30.538
some of the brain... So you mentioned Chris
Metzen. You gave so much love to so many

04:25:31.138 --> 04:25:35.038
people on the team, but I gotta ask about
Chris Metzen, who I would, by the way, love to

04:25:35.058 --> 04:25:38.868
do a podcast with at some point.
What were the brainstorming

04:25:38.938 --> 04:25:44.438
sessions with him like? It seems
like those are pretty like, awesome.

04:25:44.478 --> 04:25:48.458
- They were the best. Like, you could walk

04:25:48.498 --> 04:25:52.278
into a room. Like, the way
I would work with Chris

04:25:52.638 --> 04:25:56.478
is early on when I was more
junior, it was just sort

04:25:56.518 --> 04:26:00.358
of getting creative direction from him.
"Hey, Chris, I'm about to work on this zone

04:26:00.398 --> 04:26:04.207
called Westfall. What are
your ideas? You know,

04:26:04.238 --> 04:26:08.108
how could I capture them in gameplay? Well, that won't
quite work. How about like this?" It was more like

04:26:08.158 --> 04:26:16.008
that. Later on, like, I still remember,
the first discussion I ever had

04:26:16.018 --> 04:26:19.958
with Chris about Wrath of the Lich
King, I went up to his office like,

04:26:19.968 --> 04:26:23.558
"Hey, we're finally doing it. We're
doing the Northrend expansion.

04:26:24.238 --> 04:26:27.218
You know, what excites
you about Northrend?"

04:26:28.058 --> 04:26:32.898
And that's all you had to
say. And he would draw a map

04:26:33.758 --> 04:26:37.368
and he'd start pulling up
old, like, Warcraft II and

04:26:37.378 --> 04:26:41.288
Warcraft I manuals and, you know,
showing you, like, pictures

04:26:41.418 --> 04:26:45.168
he and Sammy had drawn and, like, maps and

04:26:45.238 --> 04:26:49.158
he, all of it, he would just go on
for an hour and then I would sort of

04:26:49.218 --> 04:26:52.517
digest. I'd just listen, taking constant

04:26:52.578 --> 04:26:55.938
notes. I'm photographing
his whiteboards all the

04:26:55.998 --> 04:26:59.758
time, and then I go back and start to put

04:26:59.818 --> 04:27:03.778
those into design flow of, like,
"Okay. What's a zone? What's

04:27:03.838 --> 04:27:07.078
a dungeon? What could be cool? What
should come first? What should come

04:27:07.158 --> 04:27:11.098
last?" You know, Lich King, for example,
we wanted to try a very specific

04:27:11.118 --> 04:27:15.018
design to counter a problem we had in
Burning Crusade, which is everybody

04:27:15.078 --> 04:27:18.988
entered through the Dark Portal
through Hellfire Peninsula, all

04:27:19.018 --> 04:27:22.538
the server programmers hate you
because everybody loads into the same

04:27:22.558 --> 04:27:26.338
zone at the same time. Lich
King, we split them up for

04:27:26.458 --> 04:27:30.258
better player flow. Plus, it's more
interesting the more choice you have.

04:27:30.338 --> 04:27:34.258
You know, Sid Meier says, "Games are a
series of interesting choices," so we

04:27:34.278 --> 04:27:35.438
give them two starting zones, but

04:27:36.358 --> 04:27:40.338
that was the flow with Chris.
And so often we would just,

04:27:40.358 --> 04:27:44.138
like, okay, in that first meeting,
Chris had put a zone called

04:27:44.178 --> 04:27:49.278
Grizzly Hills on the board. Well, I
don't know anything about Grizzly Hills.

04:27:49.298 --> 04:27:54.658
"Hey, Chris? Talk about
Grizzly Hills." If you

04:27:54.698 --> 04:27:57.898
didn't interrupt him, he'd just go for an

04:27:57.998 --> 04:28:01.778
hour. And you have no idea
how much of it, like, he

04:28:01.818 --> 04:28:05.418
had pre-thought about or had
existed in previous lore

04:28:05.978 --> 04:28:10.998
and how much of it he was
just making up on the spot.

04:28:11.038 --> 04:28:14.158
He's just that charismatic
and captivating.

04:28:14.238 --> 04:28:16.108
- Creating these worlds and being able to-

04:28:16.108 --> 04:28:20.058
... brainstorm through them and together,
I mean, that is what you're doing.

04:28:20.098 --> 04:28:23.058
As a consumer of those worlds,
you kind of take it for granted

04:28:24.298 --> 04:28:28.198
that they're incredible, but,
like, you're crafting them.

04:28:28.238 --> 04:28:32.688
Like, you're looking at a blank sheet
of paper and then together coming up...

04:28:32.878 --> 04:28:36.818
- My job, as I saw it
working with Chris, was I

04:28:36.878 --> 04:28:40.398
had to on World of Warcraft
specifically working with Chris,

04:28:40.878 --> 04:28:44.718
is I was like the
translator into gameplay of

04:28:44.778 --> 04:28:48.718
what Chris wanted, how to get it
to play like how Chris wanted.

04:28:48.778 --> 04:28:52.758
So my favorite story is we're
working on Burning Crusade and

04:28:52.798 --> 04:28:56.094
we're in this meeting and
Chris is like...He's the

04:28:56.474 --> 04:29:00.394
gentlest, sweetest guy, but because he
carries himself with such confidence

04:29:00.634 --> 04:29:03.874
and everybody's in awe of him, the junior

04:29:03.954 --> 04:29:07.654
developers get kind of intimidated
by him. So we're in this

04:29:07.714 --> 04:29:11.054
meeting and we're talking about Silvermoon
City because we're introducing the blood

04:29:11.134 --> 04:29:14.834
elves, and Chris is like, "And Silvermoon

04:29:14.954 --> 04:29:18.634
City's got the tallest fucking
tower in all of Azeroth. I

04:29:18.694 --> 04:29:22.414
mean, it is the tallest
thing. You know, it's

04:29:22.494 --> 04:29:25.974
mind-blowing, the awe of it.
Only the blood elves could build

04:29:26.034 --> 04:29:30.014
it." Fast-forward like two weeks
later. I'm walking through

04:29:30.024 --> 04:29:33.844
the hall and I see a bunch of level
designers and artists are all like

04:29:33.894 --> 04:29:40.304
crowded around the screen, and on the screen
they've dragged Blackrock Mountain and

04:29:40.514 --> 04:29:46.274
Karazhan and the Stormwind Cathedral.
I'm like, "What the fuck are

04:29:46.334 --> 04:29:50.074
you guys doing?" And they're
like, "Well, Chris said that the

04:29:50.154 --> 04:29:56.094
Silvermoon Tower had to be the
tallest thing in World of Warcraft-"

04:29:56.104 --> 04:29:59.984
"... and so we're measuring how
tall all of these other things

04:30:00.074 --> 04:30:04.664
are so we can make the tower
taller." And I'm like,

04:30:04.664 --> 04:30:11.934
"Guys, Chris doesn't know how
tall the Burning Steppes, you

04:30:11.974 --> 04:30:16.064
know- ... and the cathedral in Stormwind-

04:30:16.064 --> 04:30:20.044
... is. What Chris means is just
make the tower really fucking tall."

04:30:20.044 --> 04:30:23.594
"You don't need to measure it." And
they're like, "Oh, okay. That's okay?"

04:30:23.614 --> 04:30:27.414
Like are you willing to take
the heat if he- I'm like, "I'm

04:30:27.434 --> 04:30:29.774
willing to take the heat
on this one, guys."

04:30:29.854 --> 04:30:32.464
- Yeah. It's just a feeling.
It's a vibe. It's-

04:30:32.464 --> 04:30:33.024
- It's a vibe.

04:30:33.074 --> 04:30:38.794
- Yeah. And I also just personally have
to give all the love in the world

04:30:38.934 --> 04:30:42.754
for the current Diablo IV team, because

04:30:42.834 --> 04:30:46.764
I've spent most recently out of
the Blizzard games, I've spent a

04:30:46.794 --> 04:30:50.654
huge amount of time in Diablo, and
they've created some... And it's not

04:30:50.714 --> 04:30:54.564
just the loot, all right? It's the
whole experience, the art, everything

04:30:54.654 --> 04:30:58.384
together. And the seasons they've created,
they've created a really wonderful world.

04:30:58.434 --> 04:31:02.884
So I can, I could see, I could feel
how much effort goes into that.

04:31:02.894 --> 04:31:06.854
- They're crushing it. And I
think Diablo IV in like modern

04:31:06.954 --> 04:31:10.674
times is one of the best worlds
that they've built. And they know,

04:31:11.374 --> 04:31:13.994
they understand Diablo players.

04:31:14.014 --> 04:31:20.934
Like that community is so hard and so
demanding, and that team is amazing.

04:31:20.974 --> 04:31:24.794
- Yeah, there's a lot of richness. It's like
there's this really... I mean, I don't know how

04:31:24.874 --> 04:31:28.134
often you get that, but it's really the
perfect Diablo game. They've really

04:31:28.534 --> 04:31:32.134
like evolved a lot, grew a
lot. So there's this whole

04:31:32.194 --> 04:31:36.024
mathematical component
of just so many numbers

04:31:36.024 --> 04:31:39.943
everywhere and it's all balanced
really masterfully. And then

04:31:39.994 --> 04:31:43.943
all, of course you have to come up with new
content with the seasons and they figure out

04:31:43.974 --> 04:31:50.794
ways to do that, so and, and, and a
crazy pace. And still make it super fun.

04:31:50.834 --> 04:31:52.694
- They're a great live team, yeah.

04:31:52.714 --> 04:31:56.344
- And for me personally, like I said, the co-op,
the couch co-op experience have been really

04:31:56.554 --> 04:32:00.514
like that aspect of it is really
great, just all of it. It's one, one

04:32:00.554 --> 04:32:04.494
of the greatest games in recent
history. One of the things I

04:32:04.534 --> 04:32:08.454
wanted to mention, 'cause
this is a powerful speech

04:32:08.574 --> 04:32:12.354
is sort of instead of doing
some kind of a corporate

04:32:12.434 --> 04:32:14.234
goodbye as you were leaving Blizzard,

04:32:15.734 --> 04:32:19.294
you allegedly shared with your
team a video of David Bowie giving

04:32:19.354 --> 04:32:23.334
advice. And people should go watch
this clip. But if I may read

04:32:23.414 --> 04:32:27.114
it, Bowie says, "Never play to the

04:32:27.154 --> 04:32:30.954
gallery. Always remember that
the reason that you initially

04:32:31.014 --> 04:32:34.994
started working was that there was
something inside yourself that you

04:32:35.034 --> 04:32:38.824
felt that if you could manifest in
some way, you would understand more

04:32:38.874 --> 04:32:41.774
about yourself and how you
co-exist with the rest of

04:32:41.794 --> 04:32:45.574
society. I think it's terribly
dangerous for an artist to fulfill

04:32:45.654 --> 04:32:49.514
other peoples' expectations. I
think they generally produce their

04:32:49.554 --> 04:32:53.494
worst work when they do that.
And the other thing I would say

04:32:54.014 --> 04:32:57.874
is that if you feel safe in the area that
you're working in, you're not working in the

04:32:57.914 --> 04:33:01.154
right area. Always go a
little further into the

04:33:01.194 --> 04:33:04.804
water than you feel you're
capable of being in.

04:33:05.134 --> 04:33:08.954
Go a little bit out of your depth. And
when you don't feel that your feet are

04:33:09.034 --> 04:33:12.914
quite touching the bottom, you're
just about in the right place to

04:33:13.054 --> 04:33:18.714
do something exciting."
Speaking of which, you are

04:33:20.394 --> 04:33:25.694
just about in a place to do something
exciting. After leaving Blizzard,

04:33:27.014 --> 04:33:32.774
uh, you told me that you tried to take
some time off. How did that work out for

04:33:32.834 --> 04:33:34.334
you?

04:33:34.394 --> 04:33:37.154
- Not so well. My wife, who is

04:33:37.354 --> 04:33:41.234
wonderful, told me I needed
to take at least a year off

04:33:41.294 --> 04:33:47.134
and just, you know, I'd been going really
hard. I'd gone 19 years barely taking

04:33:47.174 --> 04:33:54.414
vacation and I let Blizzard
consume me. And, you know, I was

04:33:54.474 --> 04:33:59.844
crushed by leaving because
I loved the place, and

04:34:01.514 --> 04:34:06.114
I didn't know what to do with myself.
I was pulling weeds in the backyard.

04:34:06.194 --> 04:34:07.354
- Literally. Gardening.

04:34:07.414 --> 04:34:11.264
- Yeah. Well, she won't let me garden
in the garden 'cause that's hers-

04:34:11.354 --> 04:34:16.374
... but I'm allowed to pull the weeds.
So I got very good at that. I was very

04:34:16.414 --> 04:34:20.374
proficient. And then of all
things, I cracked out on Call of

04:34:20.454 --> 04:34:24.154
Duty Black Ops Cold War
and I unlocked Dark

04:34:24.254 --> 04:34:29.614
Matter Ultra, which I'd- that's like a
crazy achievement to do in that game.

04:34:29.654 --> 04:34:31.774
So I did that, and then I just,

04:34:32.834 --> 04:34:36.734
I couldn't help it, like it's
how I'm programmed. It was

04:34:36.794 --> 04:34:40.694
like at this point it's late
spring, early summer and I'm just

04:34:40.754 --> 04:34:46.394
sitting in the backyard and I just
started writing with Notepad about

04:34:47.454 --> 04:34:51.634
here's a game I want to make.
And it was so terrifying

04:34:52.554 --> 04:34:58.694
because for 19 years I had worked with the
greatest developers, I thought, in the

04:34:58.754 --> 04:35:02.682
industry. And, you know, there'd be

04:35:02.691 --> 04:35:06.412
moments where it's like, "Okay, I
wanna do like a game world map."

04:35:06.462 --> 04:35:10.262
Like, "Hey, Erin, you're amazing at
making game world maps. Like, you

04:35:10.322 --> 04:35:14.142
do that." And you know,
I, like, "I need some

04:35:14.242 --> 04:35:17.852
story hooks. Hey, Chris, what do
you think would be cool here?"

04:35:17.852 --> 04:35:21.812
Like, you know, it's so collaborative and I
was surrounded by the best of the best, and

04:35:21.842 --> 04:35:30.222
there I was by myself. And I was
out there again, and I loved it.

04:35:30.242 --> 04:35:33.962
It brought all the joy of game
making. I thought games were no

04:35:34.042 --> 04:35:37.742
longer fun to make because
it was only about business,

04:35:38.342 --> 04:35:41.742
and somebody's asking me for
unreasonable amounts of money and

04:35:41.822 --> 04:35:43.742
unreasonable amounts of time.

04:35:44.722 --> 04:35:50.712
And I had forgotten the pure joy
of the craft of making games, and

04:35:51.642 --> 04:35:55.542
I was designing, I was going on,
I was watching YouTube videos

04:35:55.602 --> 04:35:59.522
to learn Unreal and Adobe
Illustrator and all

04:35:59.572 --> 04:36:05.822
these things to like help me make games,
whatever, Blender. Um, I had no right to

04:36:05.862 --> 04:36:09.702
be doing any of that, and
it just felt so amazing to

04:36:09.722 --> 04:36:16.002
do it. And I sort of realized, I
came to two realizations. One,

04:36:17.182 --> 04:36:20.082
I never wanna work for someone
else again. I never wanna

04:36:21.602 --> 04:36:25.222
create something and then have
somebody take my baby away from

04:36:25.262 --> 04:36:28.982
me, you know? That's really
hard when- when that

04:36:29.062 --> 04:36:32.982
happens, and it's sort of happened a
few times now, you know, where you

04:36:33.022 --> 04:36:36.342
have to just let something
go that you created.

04:36:37.362 --> 04:36:44.202
And I wanted it all to be focused
on the craft of making games, the

04:36:44.262 --> 04:36:48.182
art, programming, design, audio, you

04:36:48.262 --> 04:36:52.192
know? Like, just not about the
bullshit of the games industry.

04:36:52.242 --> 04:36:56.122
I'm not interested in the games
industry. I'm not interested in

04:36:56.162 --> 04:37:03.682
the business of games. I'm not interested
in the entertainment industry. It's just

04:37:03.742 --> 04:37:11.662
game jamming, making stuff that we're
gonna play together. And around that

04:37:11.742 --> 04:37:19.942
time, my I call him my development soulmate.
There's a programmer named Tim Ford.

04:37:20.002 --> 04:37:23.851
He reached out and he's
like, "Hey, man..." He was

04:37:23.882 --> 04:37:27.102
like an associate tech
director on Overwatch at the

04:37:27.142 --> 04:37:30.782
time. And he's like, "Yeah,
I don't think I can do this

04:37:30.842 --> 04:37:38.502
anymore. It's just not like it was,
you know, I just handed in my notice."

04:37:38.522 --> 04:37:42.362
And I'm like, "Whoa, you
know, well, if you wanna do

04:37:42.402 --> 04:37:46.382
something together, like fuck
it. Let's take a stab and, you

04:37:46.442 --> 04:37:53.652
know, just see what happens." And
Tim came over to my house, and well,

04:37:53.682 --> 04:37:57.441
before that, he says, "My
last day's on Friday."

04:37:57.522 --> 04:38:01.462
"And my exit interview's at like 1:00. I'm

04:38:01.482 --> 04:38:05.462
gonna be over to your house
at like 2:00 that afternoon."

04:38:05.482 --> 04:38:09.422
And I'm like, "Well, don't you think
you should take some time off, Tim,

04:38:09.462 --> 04:38:13.022
you know, before whatever's next
for you? Take a month off, you

04:38:13.082 --> 04:38:16.592
know? Meg, his wife, will
appreciate it, you know?

04:38:16.622 --> 04:38:20.372
Just go pull weeds in
the garden for a while."

04:38:20.422 --> 04:38:26.682
And he's like, "I'm a programmer. All
I'm gonna do is program for a month if

04:38:26.762 --> 04:38:32.322
I take a month off. I might as well
start programming our game." Which-

04:38:32.382 --> 04:38:32.722
- Brilliant

04:38:32.962 --> 04:38:34.762
- ... it was so awesome when he said that.

04:38:34.782 --> 04:38:35.402
- Brilliant.

04:38:35.422 --> 04:38:39.362
- He came over and I pitched
him this idea for a game, and

04:38:39.462 --> 04:38:46.542
I pitched him, "Let's start a company."
And that was it. Like, that was the birth

04:38:46.702 --> 04:38:49.562
of us making a studio.

04:38:49.602 --> 04:38:52.282
- Now, meanwhile, as far
as the outside world is

04:38:52.322 --> 04:38:55.522
concerned, you've disappeared
off the face of the

04:38:55.562 --> 04:38:58.882
Earth, but you were
actually working on a game.

04:38:58.962 --> 04:39:05.682
- Yeah, I needed to be away from
the world. I needed to not

04:39:05.862 --> 04:39:09.142
have... I wanted to not get attention from

04:39:09.222 --> 04:39:16.962
anyone. I needed to not read my name
on Reddit or... you know, any internet

04:39:17.142 --> 04:39:21.912
site. I wanted to not come up, let some
other Jeff Kaplan bubble to the top-

04:39:21.912 --> 04:39:25.442
... of the Google, you know, search list.

04:39:25.502 --> 04:39:29.382
- You know our man Dinoflask is gonna
be all over this conversation, right?

04:39:29.442 --> 04:39:33.222
- Oh, God, well, there's, yeah, this-
this one's gonna set him back some

04:39:33.262 --> 04:39:35.102
time. But, yeah, I needed-

04:39:35.112 --> 04:39:36.382
- You know what to do.

04:39:36.392 --> 04:39:40.362
- Uh, I needed for none of that to
happen. I just needed to be able to,

04:39:40.402 --> 04:39:46.822
like, mourn the loss of Blizzard- ...
and create on my own so it was great.

04:39:46.862 --> 04:39:50.792
And at that time, like as soon as
it was announced that I was leaving

04:39:50.822 --> 04:39:57.982
Blizzard, I had like 60 people reach out
to me. It was, this was April of 2021

04:39:58.062 --> 04:40:02.162
and investment money was
nuts, both like the VC money

04:40:03.082 --> 04:40:08.842
and the strategic money was
crazy, like the, especially the

04:40:08.902 --> 04:40:12.692
Chinese companies, because
apparently they weren't getting,

04:40:12.782 --> 04:40:16.682
publishing numbers in China or
something. The whole economy

04:40:16.722 --> 04:40:20.682
was crazy, and so just
everybody was trying to throw

04:40:20.722 --> 04:40:28.122
money at me, which was a very good position
to sort of be at to start a company. So

04:40:28.162 --> 04:40:31.882
what Tim and I did was say,
"We're not doing this for

04:40:31.922 --> 04:40:35.831
money, but here's the game
we wanna make, and it's

04:40:35.842 --> 04:40:39.732
gonna take this many developers, and we think
it's gonna take this length of time, and

04:40:39.762 --> 04:40:43.732
that means the budget
is this. And we need,

04:40:43.782 --> 04:40:47.582
for any of these people who
wanna invest in us, we gotta hit

04:40:47.662 --> 04:40:51.562
that number, but after that, we're
not gonna go for more money. It's

04:40:51.602 --> 04:40:59.632
not an auction to raise as high as we can
go. We're gonna optimize for control."

04:40:59.662 --> 04:41:03.622
- I don't know if this is something
that you can talk about, but I

04:41:03.642 --> 04:41:05.622
got a chance to see the
game for a few hours,

04:41:06.602 --> 04:41:09.766
and I have to say it's
incredible.... Jeff. Like, it's

04:41:09.826 --> 04:41:13.686
incredible. But I almost immediately
fell in love with the world

04:41:13.726 --> 04:41:17.476
and everything I saw. See, I'm
tempted to say some of the things I

04:41:17.506 --> 04:41:21.406
saw but it's just an incredible
game. So how much can you talk

04:41:21.466 --> 04:41:25.446
about it? Do you know what it's going to be
called? Can you talk about that? Do you know about

04:41:25.506 --> 04:41:27.846
the company? Are you
allowed to say any of that?

04:41:27.966 --> 04:41:31.806
- Sure. The most unconventional way to
talk about this stuff for the first

04:41:31.866 --> 04:41:38.186
time. So, our company name is Kintsugiyama,
which most people will struggle to

04:41:38.286 --> 04:41:39.246
pronounce.

04:41:39.286 --> 04:41:39.586
- Nice.

04:41:39.606 --> 04:41:43.586
- And the company name has a deep meaning
to me, which I'm happy to explain

04:41:43.626 --> 04:41:50.186
later if you're interested. And the
game name that we're working on,

04:41:51.586 --> 04:41:55.546
it's called The Legend
of California, and it's

04:41:55.606 --> 04:41:59.566
an open world game. People
are gonna call it a survival

04:42:00.166 --> 04:42:03.926
crafting game. People
like to compartmentalize

04:42:03.946 --> 04:42:07.846
these. I think it's an
action game. It's a game

04:42:07.926 --> 04:42:11.786
that takes place on a mythical
island of California.

04:42:11.806 --> 04:42:14.286
- Mm-hmm. In the 1800s.

04:42:14.386 --> 04:42:16.526
- In the gold rush. If you're trying to-

04:42:16.546 --> 04:42:16.556
- In the gold rush.

04:42:16.556 --> 04:42:20.206
- ... if you're trying to nail the most
important time in California history,

04:42:21.026 --> 04:42:23.166
it's gotta be that gold rush.

04:42:23.226 --> 04:42:27.016
- So, it's this beautiful,
almost ultra-realistic

04:42:27.086 --> 04:42:30.926
version of California, but it's in an
alternate history, alternate version of

04:42:30.966 --> 04:42:35.126
California- ...where it's an island,
almost like an Atlantis type

04:42:35.186 --> 04:42:42.686
of ethereal island, but still very realistic
to what the California terrain is-

04:42:42.706 --> 04:42:45.666
... and that time period.
So it's this weird like

04:42:46.106 --> 04:42:50.226
amalgamation of this
ultra-realistic and the surreal.

04:42:50.236 --> 04:42:54.086
- The theme of the game is very weird.
We're not trying to make a historical

04:42:54.126 --> 04:42:57.866
game. There's no historical
accuracy to this. In fact, the

04:42:57.926 --> 04:43:01.546
island when first discovered
is uninhabited. That's

04:43:01.626 --> 04:43:05.366
already not true. As we
know, there were lots of

04:43:05.426 --> 04:43:08.776
people in California. It's an
island, which we know is not

04:43:08.846 --> 04:43:12.706
true. We want it to feel authentic to

04:43:12.766 --> 04:43:15.736
that time period because we
think that time period is cool.

04:43:15.736 --> 04:43:19.386
Prospectors, you know, cowboys.

04:43:19.425 --> 04:43:23.346
Like, it's a really fun
thing for us to explore, all

04:43:23.406 --> 04:43:27.226
of those themes people
in mines. We wanna build

04:43:27.326 --> 04:43:31.146
mines and we just wanna
create a world that you can

04:43:31.306 --> 04:43:35.176
live in. I love creating
worlds. Everything that

04:43:35.266 --> 04:43:39.246
I've worked on before,
from World of Warcraft

04:43:39.256 --> 04:43:42.886
to Overwatch, it's always been,
how do you create this place for

04:43:42.986 --> 04:43:45.426
players to escape to, so.

04:43:45.486 --> 04:43:49.406
- So, it's an online, multiplayer game.
I should say the experience of it

04:43:49.466 --> 04:43:53.306
is just gorgeous, and then
the music is wonderful.

04:43:53.346 --> 04:43:54.626
- I'm glad you like it.

04:43:54.666 --> 04:43:58.626
- And one of my favorite things is just
going down to the mine and digging.

04:43:58.646 --> 04:44:00.566
I mean, that's done ex- extremely well.

04:44:01.406 --> 04:44:04.966
And as you described, the
whole world is voxels,

04:44:05.086 --> 04:44:09.306
so it's generated. Can you
explain how that works?

04:44:09.366 --> 04:44:13.286
- Yeah. As a world, we handcrafted
the world, so like the shape

04:44:13.366 --> 04:44:17.046
of California is always the familiar
shape of California, except it's an

04:44:17.126 --> 04:44:20.866
island. So, you know, there's
no Nevada on, on the eastern

04:44:20.986 --> 04:44:24.866
side. We handcrafted all
of that. It looks gorgeous

04:44:24.966 --> 04:44:28.746
and places like Yosemite
are where you would expect

04:44:28.826 --> 04:44:32.126
Yosemite to be. And so
all of those familiar

04:44:32.286 --> 04:44:39.866
landmarks are there, but then we have
like dozens of points of interest, and

04:44:39.946 --> 04:44:43.726
those move around the map
in, depending on the map

04:44:43.846 --> 04:44:47.526
seed. And the map is also
tiered in, in terms of

04:44:47.566 --> 04:44:51.266
difficulty. We don't really have
levels in this game. We have

04:44:51.366 --> 04:44:55.326
tiers, and there's only four tiers
right now. Maybe, maybe that will

04:44:55.366 --> 04:45:02.756
change. But the way that the map tiers
itself each time changes with every

04:45:02.786 --> 04:45:06.466
world seed. So not only... Any
server that you join will have a

04:45:06.506 --> 04:45:10.406
different seed in terms of
how the tiers play out.

04:45:10.466 --> 04:45:14.026
So, Mojave might be the
easiest newbie area

04:45:14.666 --> 04:45:19.756
on your server, but on my server
it's endgame, tier four area.

04:45:20.346 --> 04:45:28.166
But all of our notable points of interest
also move around. So, we have a really

04:45:28.206 --> 04:45:31.816
amazing point of interest that we
call Dread Rock that's inspired by

04:45:31.886 --> 04:45:35.736
Alcatraz. And like, sure,
sometimes it's in San Francisco,

04:45:35.746 --> 04:45:39.606
but sometimes it can be sitting in
the middle of the Mojave Desert also.

04:45:39.616 --> 04:45:45.346
- Mm-hmm. It integrates it into the
environment, to where it makes sense-

04:45:45.356 --> 04:45:49.186
... to be in that environment. And
like you said, so much of what

04:45:49.206 --> 04:45:56.066
makes a world is sound and lighting.
And that's definitely a thing that I've

04:45:56.726 --> 04:46:00.536
noticed. I mean, it's probably the

04:46:00.586 --> 04:46:04.066
most beautiful sunset and
sunrise I've seen in a game.

04:46:04.106 --> 04:46:07.906
- We have a great lighting artist
who's this amazing guy named Mike

04:46:07.966 --> 04:46:11.646
Marra, and some of the
inspiration for the game

04:46:11.706 --> 04:46:15.546
like... There's a lot of inspirations for
this game, but there's a painter named

04:46:15.626 --> 04:46:19.466
Albert Bierstadt, who I
discovered while researching

04:46:19.606 --> 04:46:26.586
California, and he painted these just epic
landscape pieces of, you know, Yosemite

04:46:26.626 --> 04:46:29.016
and a lot of other, the gorgeous parts of-

04:46:29.016 --> 04:46:31.826
- Yeah, we're looking at one photo of his.

04:46:31.886 --> 04:46:35.826
- Yeah, it's just amazing, and his
paintings were huge, too. Um, I'd

04:46:35.866 --> 04:46:38.396
love to see one in person.

04:46:38.406 --> 04:46:42.596
- And so you see a painting like that and
you're saying, "We wanna create that world."

04:46:42.906 --> 04:46:46.886
- Yeah. I mean, when I see that
painting, this is, this is what

04:46:46.966 --> 04:46:50.866
video games brings to the
table. So, every art form that

04:46:50.946 --> 04:46:55.606
evolves after another gets to
incorporate previous art forms.

04:46:55.666 --> 04:46:59.486
Movies got to take sound
and, you know fine

04:46:59.546 --> 04:47:03.466
art. We get to take everything,
including movies. So, you

04:47:03.526 --> 04:47:10.230
know, it's, it's Katamari Damacy, the
art form. But like...I see a Bierstadt

04:47:10.250 --> 04:47:14.190
painting, and I wanna
walk around that world. I

04:47:14.230 --> 04:47:18.150
wanna see what's around the corner.
And our lighting artist, Mike,

04:47:18.210 --> 04:47:21.290
he, you know, he sees these
pictures, and he's like,

04:47:22.310 --> 04:47:26.190
"Okay. Yeah. Hold my beer." Like, "I'll
make it look like that." And he, and

04:47:26.310 --> 04:47:29.830
he... We are all blown away by

04:47:29.870 --> 04:47:33.630
the, like, how much impact just
the lighting. And I'm not an

04:47:33.690 --> 04:47:37.050
artist, so I don't think about things
like the color theory, the lights, the

04:47:37.110 --> 04:47:41.070
clouds, what all of that's bringing
to this. I just know I want

04:47:41.090 --> 04:47:44.910
to live in that world, and these are the
types of worlds that we want to make.

04:47:45.450 --> 04:47:50.470
- So, what do you want the tone of the
game to be, the feeling of the game?

04:47:50.490 --> 04:47:53.870
- This is really different. It's,
it's been hard for people.

04:47:54.410 --> 04:47:58.190
When people were talking to us
about, you know, they know me and

04:47:58.250 --> 04:48:01.770
Tim, and they're, "Oh, the Blizzard
guys, the Overwatch guys. You, you're

04:48:01.830 --> 04:48:04.980
making, like, a bright,
aspirational future

04:48:05.250 --> 04:48:09.100
team-based hero shooter,
right?" And I'm like,

04:48:09.100 --> 04:48:16.170
"Why would I want to do that?" I felt
like, first of all, respects to Blizzard,

04:48:16.270 --> 04:48:20.000
and I don't want to try
to crib Blizzard and

04:48:20.090 --> 04:48:23.890
make a pseudo-Blizzard
game, you know? This

04:48:23.970 --> 04:48:30.650
is... I want to make a Kintsugiyama game,
you know? Me and Tim and this crack

04:48:30.730 --> 04:48:34.200
team, you know, we're only 34 people.

04:48:34.290 --> 04:48:38.080
We want to define what a
Kintsugiyama game is, and

04:48:38.770 --> 04:48:42.550
this world seemed so inspiring
to us, you know? The

04:48:42.630 --> 04:48:46.620
setting is really interesting.
You know, I think California can

04:48:46.630 --> 04:48:50.110
be a game world. I think we can make it

04:48:50.150 --> 04:48:53.810
beautiful and interesting.
We don't have to follow

04:48:53.850 --> 04:48:57.570
history or geography. We can kind of do a

04:48:57.630 --> 04:49:01.330
spin where, you know, it
feels authentic. We can

04:49:01.390 --> 04:49:04.810
have guns that feel like they're
kind of from that time period,

04:49:04.850 --> 04:49:08.500
but we're not spaceships
and aliens and steampunk.

04:49:08.570 --> 04:49:11.710
That's what we would have done at Blizzard.
We're gonna be a little different here.

04:49:11.750 --> 04:49:15.730
So, the tone of this
game, you know... Metzen

04:49:15.770 --> 04:49:19.370
would describe Blizzard as the
hero factory. You know, we

04:49:19.510 --> 04:49:23.400
make... And what he means by that is not
only are we making heroes, but we make the

04:49:23.510 --> 04:49:25.610
players into heroes.

04:49:25.630 --> 04:49:29.550
This game is gonna have an edgier
tone. You're gonna enter this world.

04:49:29.570 --> 04:49:33.550
It's gonna feel lonelier.
It's gonna feel mysterious,

04:49:34.570 --> 04:49:38.410
larger than you. You're gonna
feel small until you earn the

04:49:38.450 --> 04:49:42.290
right to feel big. It's
gonna feel really dangerous.

04:49:42.350 --> 04:49:45.590
You're gonna want to see what's over
that next hill, but if the sun is

04:49:45.670 --> 04:49:49.419
setting, like, get to
shelter. Can't wait to get

04:49:49.450 --> 04:49:53.330
back to my ranch and put my
cozy fireplace on and wait

04:49:53.390 --> 04:49:57.759
till morning, you know? We
want more of that vibe.

04:49:58.450 --> 04:50:05.900
- It's more solitary, almost
scary, but beautiful.

04:50:06.170 --> 04:50:10.230
That mix, that tension. I hate
to ask this question, but

04:50:11.510 --> 04:50:14.490
given our previous discussion
about a timeline slide,

04:50:15.970 --> 04:50:19.670
but what do you think a timeline looks
like? When do you think it's possible

04:50:19.790 --> 04:50:22.970
for somebody in the world to
be able to play this game?

04:50:23.390 --> 04:50:27.340
- So, this is the beauty of
me and Tim kind of getting

04:50:27.390 --> 04:50:31.130
to run the show and why
we're excited about it. Um,

04:50:31.670 --> 04:50:35.430
we can kinda do whatever we
want- ... within reason.

04:50:35.490 --> 04:50:43.630
Um, so we're just gonna kinda quietly
put it up on Steam and see what happens.

04:50:43.710 --> 04:50:43.770
- Nice.

04:50:43.810 --> 04:50:47.670
- You know, no, like, big
corporate marketing group

04:50:47.750 --> 04:50:49.940
would ever think to do
that in a million years-

04:50:49.940 --> 04:50:53.790
... without, like, some, you know,
$10 million announce or whatever.

04:50:54.630 --> 04:50:56.930
We'll just kinda put it on Steam and

04:50:57.850 --> 04:51:01.350
be cool if people wishlisted
it. There's my plug. And

04:51:01.410 --> 04:51:08.550
then I think we are shooting to
have some sort of public-ish alpha

04:51:09.530 --> 04:51:15.230
in March. And then our plan, and
something I'm really excited

04:51:15.290 --> 04:51:19.210
about, 'cause I've never gotten to do
this before, we wanna put the game in

04:51:19.270 --> 04:51:23.050
early access. Some people
hate early access and won't

04:51:23.110 --> 04:51:27.019
touch it, and I understand it, and then
some people are like, "I wanna be in on the

04:51:27.090 --> 04:51:30.590
ground floor and see the thing
from day one and watch it

04:51:30.630 --> 04:51:35.140
evolve." So, we'll put it into early
access, and we'll just run that until

04:51:36.570 --> 04:51:37.280
who knows, you know?

04:51:37.310 --> 04:51:41.270
- Is it scary to you to have a
sort of game with some rough

04:51:41.330 --> 04:51:45.760
edges out there in the wild where people
are interacting with it through the alpha-

04:51:45.760 --> 04:51:47.290
... through the beta?

04:51:47.350 --> 04:51:51.170
- Yes, and this game has more
rough edges, like, the

04:51:51.210 --> 04:51:55.160
most rough edges we would have at Blizzard
is, like, showing it at BlizzCon, which was

04:51:55.190 --> 04:51:59.070
heavily polished and
controlled. This is gonna be

04:51:59.190 --> 04:52:03.070
more, you know, like, in development

04:52:03.110 --> 04:52:06.250
than anything else I've
ever worked on. But that's-

04:52:06.290 --> 04:52:06.730
- I love it.

04:52:07.010 --> 04:52:10.590
- ... part of the excitement too,
you know? It's kinda like this

04:52:10.650 --> 04:52:16.330
is, this is how the sausage gets made.
I mean, you're gonna see it front row.

04:52:16.990 --> 04:52:20.740
- I'm gonna try to get myself
into the alpha somehow. Anybody

04:52:20.850 --> 04:52:24.770
who is listening to this, I highly recommend
this game. You will not be disappointed.

04:52:24.790 --> 04:52:28.770
The world itself is just beautiful. So,
whoever's behind it, you and Tim and

04:52:28.810 --> 04:52:32.730
the team, are just doing an
incredible job. And thank you for

04:52:32.770 --> 04:52:35.390
putting out rough versions
of it so we get to-

04:52:35.399 --> 04:52:38.790
... not wait forever
for the perfect thing.

04:52:39.390 --> 04:52:42.930
And because you feel in... You feel
like you're a part of it if you get the

04:52:42.990 --> 04:52:46.800
imperfect thing. I'm one of the people
who like the imperfect. We get to see

04:52:47.950 --> 04:52:51.730
the rough versions develop,
and we- and get to be a

04:52:51.790 --> 04:52:58.810
part of the it developing. I saw the
logo. It's a mountain. Can you explain

04:52:58.820 --> 04:53:01.050
the meaning behind the name?

04:53:01.190 --> 04:53:08.170
- So, Kintsugi is a Japanese
craft of repairing broken

04:53:08.270 --> 04:53:11.998
pottery. So there's a lot
of philosophy that goes

04:53:12.058 --> 04:53:15.608
into it as well. And you know,
I wanna do a good job of

04:53:15.658 --> 04:53:19.538
explaining it, but basically,
like, you take a broken piece of

04:53:19.578 --> 04:53:24.138
pottery, and then they
would use golden joinery-

04:53:24.218 --> 04:53:28.018
Um, like golden lacquer to put the piece

04:53:28.058 --> 04:53:31.928
back together. And the thought
was rather than hiding the

04:53:32.038 --> 04:53:35.297
scars, you make them
more beautiful. And the

04:53:35.338 --> 04:53:39.038
philosophical parts that
sort of appealed to me with

04:53:39.118 --> 04:53:46.138
that is there's a lot of me and Tim in
that, of... We're so appreciative for

04:53:46.178 --> 04:53:49.938
our time at Blizzard, but we
didn't come away unscarred.

04:53:50.558 --> 04:53:54.168
And there's also a
philosophy in Kintsugi that

04:53:54.198 --> 04:53:58.127
nothing's ever perfect, and the
pursuit of perfection is actually a

04:53:58.158 --> 04:54:04.578
mistake, and that there's beauty
in imperfection. And so I relate

04:54:04.588 --> 04:54:11.398
that to myself personally. That's how I
feel in an aspirational way. I'm not saying

04:54:11.898 --> 04:54:15.808
I've achieved it, but in an aspirational
way, I want to be that way. And I think

04:54:15.858 --> 04:54:23.418
it's also an analogy for the making of
games. Like, it's a... Making of games

04:54:23.838 --> 04:54:27.648
is a constant, pursuit of

04:54:27.798 --> 04:54:31.768
imperfection. Game is never
gonna be perfect. Just ask the

04:54:31.838 --> 04:54:35.798
players. They're very vocal
about it. And seeing the beauty

04:54:35.838 --> 04:54:43.138
and the imperfections and the strength in
something that's been broken that can be

04:54:43.318 --> 04:54:44.618
stronger.

04:54:44.778 --> 04:54:48.138
- You had a heck of a difficult couple years

04:54:48.198 --> 04:54:52.158
here. And so in some sense,
it represents that beauty

04:54:52.498 --> 04:54:56.418
in imperfection. So everybody
listening to this I hope, I

04:54:56.458 --> 04:55:00.158
hope you do have it out on
Steam. Go check out Legend of

04:55:00.238 --> 04:55:04.148
California. Truly a beautiful
world. I'm so glad you are actually

04:55:04.218 --> 04:55:10.018
creating this, low-key, quietly creating
this beautiful, incredible world.

04:55:10.138 --> 04:55:19.958
Ridiculous question, but can we talk about
some of the greatest games of all time?

04:55:20.618 --> 04:55:24.218
What... I mean, I know this is a bit
of a nerding-out kind of thing, and

04:55:24.438 --> 04:55:27.978
I, outside of the games you've
been part of creating, I

04:55:27.998 --> 04:55:31.958
think Blizzard has created some of
the greatest games of all time.

04:55:32.038 --> 04:55:35.858
Outside of those, what do
you think are in the list?

04:55:35.918 --> 04:55:39.518
- So there's one that's
the best. It's Legend of

04:55:39.618 --> 04:55:42.638
Zelda: Breath of the Wild.
And then there's this list

04:55:42.698 --> 04:55:47.588
of greatest games, Zork, Ultima, uh-

04:55:47.588 --> 04:55:49.568
- So Breath of the Wild is the best, yeah?

04:55:49.578 --> 04:55:51.018
- The greatest game ever made.

04:55:51.078 --> 04:55:53.398
- What makes it the greatest
game ever made for you?

04:55:53.658 --> 04:55:57.538
- Every aspect is so
thoughtful, so well designed.

04:55:57.578 --> 04:56:00.778
The art matches the
design and the tech, and

04:56:01.558 --> 04:56:05.478
even integrating with the
Switch in the way it does. How

04:56:05.518 --> 04:56:09.268
do you keep making Zelda better?
How can Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of

04:56:09.358 --> 04:56:13.558
Time exist and somebody make
an even better Zelda game?

04:56:13.578 --> 04:56:18.078
The way you can chop down a tree
and float in a river, and, like,

04:56:18.938 --> 04:56:25.458
the world is a toy and everything works
as you wished and hoped it would work.

04:56:25.478 --> 04:56:29.418
And there's a narrative aspect
to it, and there's really fun

04:56:30.338 --> 04:56:34.278
combat and action and itemization.
There's so many things

04:56:34.318 --> 04:56:38.048
that that game gets right that
other games are lucky if they

04:56:38.078 --> 04:56:41.687
get one of those things right, and are...

04:56:41.698 --> 04:56:45.598
Become best in their genre just
for getting that one thing right.

04:56:45.618 --> 04:56:49.558
And Breath of the Wild does
them all right and the best.

04:56:50.038 --> 04:56:53.618
- There's a certain kinda lightness
to the way the world feels, the

04:56:53.698 --> 04:56:57.238
openness of the world feels. That's
unlike any other game, right? That's

04:56:57.458 --> 04:57:00.058
uniquely that company, uniquely that-

04:57:00.078 --> 04:57:01.058
- Yeah. No one else-

04:57:01.078 --> 04:57:04.498
- Because nobody else creates that. You're
right. Under the pressure of having

04:57:04.578 --> 04:57:06.978
created a bunch of Zeldas that are, like,

04:57:07.798 --> 04:57:11.238
really great games, to be
able to deliver once again.

04:57:11.278 --> 04:57:14.598
- Nintendo is, like, the
Mecca. Like, they're the

04:57:14.678 --> 04:57:17.438
best, you know? That's all there is to it.

04:57:17.478 --> 04:57:20.038
- Do you understand how that company works?

04:57:20.118 --> 04:57:20.187
- No.

04:57:20.218 --> 04:57:21.588
- That they're not...

04:57:21.618 --> 04:57:23.158
- I don't at all.

04:57:23.198 --> 04:57:26.998
- Like, because, I mean, they've been around for
a long time and still to be able to deliver.

04:57:27.078 --> 04:57:32.538
- I kind of rationally or irrationally
just worship. It's just sort of,

04:57:32.618 --> 04:57:35.638
if it's from Nintendo,
it's gonna be great.

04:57:35.648 --> 04:57:39.318
And even if my first impression is
like, "Wow, they're doing what weird

04:57:39.458 --> 04:57:43.358
thing with the controller
this time," and then you get

04:57:43.398 --> 04:57:50.518
your hands on it and you're like, "God."
My son and I, we both played Legend

04:57:50.558 --> 04:57:52.758
of Zelda: Breath of the Wild,

04:57:53.858 --> 04:57:57.818
and he makes games also. And we had
this moment where he's like, "I'm so

04:57:57.958 --> 04:58:01.478
sad after I played it." And he's
like, "I know I'll never make

04:58:01.578 --> 04:58:05.238
anything like this." And it's that
weird, like, you honor it so much

04:58:05.298 --> 04:58:09.218
and think it's so great. Red
Dead was like that for me. Red

04:58:09.258 --> 04:58:13.248
Dead Redemption 2 is... That's a game

04:58:13.338 --> 04:58:17.198
I put on a shrine. Not just how
brilliant the game itself is,

04:58:17.218 --> 04:58:21.058
but as a game maker, as
a craftsperson who makes

04:58:21.098 --> 04:58:28.198
games, how the hell do you make that?
Like, only Rockstar with all the

04:58:28.278 --> 04:58:33.798
years of making those types of game.
No one else can come in entry level-

04:58:33.838 --> 04:58:36.848
... and compete with that. So that's-

04:58:36.848 --> 04:58:40.638
- Purely single player,
narrative driven. So you also

04:58:40.678 --> 04:58:42.878
respect that kind of, like, pure-

04:58:42.958 --> 04:58:46.458
- Yeah. I don't give anyone a
pass. I feel like a lot of

04:58:46.498 --> 04:58:50.438
gamers and game developers, like, if it
has writing, they're, they're like, "The

04:58:50.478 --> 04:58:54.278
story's so good." I'm like,
actually, very few games have

04:58:54.318 --> 04:58:58.088
great story. But Red Dead has
a great story. It's got great

04:58:58.118 --> 04:59:04.948
character development. It's got
a good plot. And the dialogue is

04:59:04.998 --> 04:59:08.888
like... It's like Tarantino-level-

04:59:08.888 --> 04:59:16.602
... high-quality dialogue. So...Red Dead's
up there. I have my other games that

04:59:16.722 --> 04:59:20.612
make the list for me, and
these are... Both these games

04:59:20.682 --> 04:59:25.782
are... I would never tell you to
play them. EverQuest and Rust are

04:59:27.242 --> 04:59:31.042
two of the most defining games to me and

04:59:31.122 --> 04:59:35.052
my career and my life.
And Rust, I would never

04:59:35.142 --> 04:59:38.842
recommend somebody go and play
it. Rust will come calling to

04:59:39.022 --> 04:59:42.162
you if you are up to play it.

04:59:42.242 --> 04:59:46.022
- It is a cult. It's 100% a cult.

04:59:46.062 --> 04:59:46.622
- That's-

04:59:46.642 --> 04:59:48.322
- It... When you are ready,
it will come down.

04:59:48.362 --> 04:59:51.982
- It will come down. It will let you know.

04:59:51.992 --> 04:59:52.202
- The sky will part. Okay.

04:59:52.222 --> 04:59:55.742
- In Rust, you are considered a complete

04:59:55.862 --> 04:59:59.622
noob that doesn't know what he's
doing- ... if you don't have a

04:59:59.722 --> 05:00:01.812
thousand hours. Even a thousand hours-

05:00:01.822 --> 05:00:05.242
... people would be like, "Oh, you only
have a thousand hours-" "... in that game."

05:00:05.282 --> 05:00:08.591
Yeah. But Rust and a
lot of inspiration for

05:00:08.682 --> 05:00:12.522
me in the game I'm
working on now, it... My

05:00:12.542 --> 05:00:19.542
game is not like Rust in that it's not a
PvP-centric game, but it will have PvP.

05:00:20.122 --> 05:00:23.812
- What aspect of Rust do you
draw inspiration from? Just...

05:00:23.862 --> 05:00:26.472
- I love the resetting world. It's a-

05:00:26.472 --> 05:00:34.422
... great game mechanic and it's one
that I want to evolve and work upon.

05:00:34.482 --> 05:00:38.762
- How often is the world reset do you
think, in Legend of California?

05:00:39.042 --> 05:00:42.522
- I don't know yet. Probably
every month. We want it to be

05:00:42.942 --> 05:00:46.702
fast enough that you're not too
attached, but we wanna make it

05:00:46.742 --> 05:00:50.712
rewarding. Like, the trick
is coming up with not

05:00:50.762 --> 05:00:54.792
why am I upset that the world resets,
but why am I excited that the world-

05:00:54.882 --> 05:00:58.322
... resets? And we know players
can get very angry about

05:00:58.362 --> 05:01:05.822
resetting worlds, but anybody who's played
5,000 hours of Rust, like some of us the

05:01:05.882 --> 05:01:13.402
resetting world is the magic. It's I
can't wait for the next reset because the

05:01:13.422 --> 05:01:17.362
adventure starts all over again.
And if you wanna play the first

05:01:17.422 --> 05:01:20.952
time with me, like, if we wanna
play World of Warcraft, and

05:01:21.702 --> 05:01:25.142
I'm level 80 and you're level
one, there's no meaningful

05:01:25.222 --> 05:01:29.002
experience we can have together,
but in Rust, we just wait for a

05:01:29.042 --> 05:01:34.522
reset and we're both naked on the
beach, you know, from minute one.

05:01:34.562 --> 05:01:38.362
- What about the experience of Rust
where you can have everything

05:01:38.422 --> 05:01:41.202
taken away from you?
So that part that you-

05:01:41.242 --> 05:01:42.131
- We're not doing that.

05:01:42.131 --> 05:01:44.902
- Great, great. Because that
feels awfully stressful.

05:01:44.922 --> 05:01:48.612
- See... I just lost the entire Rust
audience when I said we're not doing that

05:01:48.802 --> 05:01:49.282
because-

05:01:49.682 --> 05:01:53.332
... if you're a Rust player, you're not
thinking you're gonna lose everything you have.

05:01:53.362 --> 05:01:56.672
You're thinking, "I'm gonna take
everything somebody else has." But-

05:01:56.682 --> 05:02:00.602
- See, my perception of the Rust audience is
there's, like, three people, they're in a castle

05:02:00.682 --> 05:02:03.962
somewhere. It's very exclusive group.

05:02:04.042 --> 05:02:07.792
- They are highly skilled,
highly passionate... highly

05:02:07.862 --> 05:02:11.742
knowledgeable, um... but yeah,
it's an inspiration for me.

05:02:11.802 --> 05:02:15.502
That and EverQuest were define...
And I've... The amount of hours I've

05:02:15.542 --> 05:02:18.162
logged in both those games are insane.

05:02:18.302 --> 05:02:22.882
- What do you think has more hours
from Jeff Kaplan, EverQuest or Rust?

05:02:22.922 --> 05:02:30.602
- Well, you said I was 6K on EQ, so
that puts me at... I'm at 5K in Rust.

05:02:30.742 --> 05:02:33.842
- And, and also in that collection is Zork.

05:02:33.902 --> 05:02:37.702
- Zork was... I mean, Zork, it
just brings me back to that old

05:02:37.782 --> 05:02:42.742
IBM PC with my mom and my brother,
trying to figure out, you know,

05:02:43.762 --> 05:02:47.442
like, how to keep the lights on or
else Agrue's gonna eat us, you know?

05:02:47.582 --> 05:02:50.542
- Yeah. So certain games just capture
your heart and they stay with you

05:02:50.602 --> 05:02:54.462
forever. What do you think is
the future of video games? So

05:02:54.502 --> 05:03:01.342
there's a lot of conversations
about AI helping expand maybe the

05:03:01.352 --> 05:03:05.122
storytelling aspects, the world
creation aspects, becoming a tool that

05:03:05.162 --> 05:03:08.922
people can use more so.
Maybe creating more

05:03:09.182 --> 05:03:15.322
believable NPCs, that kind of thing. But
also there's, as, as we've talked about,

05:03:16.242 --> 05:03:20.082
the video game industry is changing
and evolving and trying to figure out,

05:03:20.122 --> 05:03:26.602
well, there's the indie game makers that
will have more power of... Or these

05:03:26.742 --> 05:03:30.642
larger game makers will have more
power, so what do you think the

05:03:30.721 --> 05:03:32.541
future of games looks like?

05:03:32.622 --> 05:03:36.502
- I think with AI in mind
in particular, I think

05:03:36.562 --> 05:03:40.372
the current state of AI,
trying to integrate it into

05:03:40.702 --> 05:03:44.842
development is mostly a hot mess.

05:03:44.902 --> 05:03:52.682
But I do think that, you know,
games are a technology-driven art

05:03:52.802 --> 05:03:59.942
form. And somebody much smarter than me
once described it, and I'm paraphrasing,

05:04:00.722 --> 05:04:04.432
making a game is like making a movie
if you had to invent the camera every

05:04:04.542 --> 05:04:08.442
time, because you're kind of inventing
the technology of your specific

05:04:08.562 --> 05:04:13.702
game. And I think AI can play a role
in that, and it would be silly not to

05:04:14.522 --> 05:04:21.202
look at it as an option. The
problem with AI right now is it's

05:04:21.322 --> 05:04:27.242
overconfident in what it tries
to deliver. Like, it fooled

05:04:27.322 --> 05:04:30.512
around, obviously like
everybody, like, you mess around

05:04:30.562 --> 05:04:34.542
with, you know, ChatGPT and Gemini and

05:04:34.602 --> 05:04:38.242
you fool around with some of the
art generation, and it's fun for

05:04:38.282 --> 05:04:45.082
non-artists to fool around on Midjourney.
But it's mostly weird and shitty. And

05:04:45.222 --> 05:04:53.562
even, like, when trying to have AI answer
for me... Like, I don't normally make UI

05:04:53.602 --> 05:04:57.082
in a game, and so I'm trying
to figure out, like, UMG and

05:04:57.302 --> 05:05:01.282
Unreal Engine and I'm asking
ChatGPT to how to, how

05:05:01.302 --> 05:05:04.942
to fix, like, a simple problem, like,
how do I make the chat wrap, you

05:05:05.022 --> 05:05:08.842
know? And it, like,
overconfidently gives me the wrong

05:05:08.962 --> 05:05:16.484
answer. And it's, like, right one in 10
times. So its hit rate has to be a lot

05:05:16.514 --> 05:05:23.704
better. Um, I think there's a lot of
moral concerns around AI when it comes to

05:05:23.754 --> 05:05:30.593
creative pursuits as well, like no one's
creative work should ever be used by

05:05:30.714 --> 05:05:37.154
AI without their permission. You know,
voice actors and artists, it can't

05:05:37.194 --> 05:05:40.954
be lifting from them without
their permission. That's just

05:05:41.514 --> 05:05:48.084
immoral. It's no different than just
sort of stealing. So that's wrong. I

05:05:48.134 --> 05:05:52.074
think. I'm curious, like
especially as somebody who runs

05:05:52.114 --> 05:05:55.834
a small studio with 34 people, it's

05:05:55.854 --> 05:05:59.714
like, what are the points
of tedium that maybe AI

05:05:59.734 --> 05:06:03.554
could help out with that I
don't wanna do, and I'm not

05:06:03.574 --> 05:06:07.694
gonna hire someone to do? So I
have, like a really dumb example,

05:06:09.154 --> 05:06:12.374
I'm making a bunch of
images, I size them all

05:06:12.414 --> 05:06:16.174
incorrectly 'cause I'm dumb and I'm
not an artist, and I did it all in

05:06:16.234 --> 05:06:20.194
Photoshop, and I have like
2,000 images that are the wrong

05:06:20.254 --> 05:06:23.894
size. I can have ChatGPT resize

05:06:23.974 --> 05:06:27.894
those and zip it in a file for
me, and it literally takes

05:06:27.974 --> 05:06:31.094
it like a minute to do that.

05:06:31.154 --> 05:06:34.934
I wasn't gonna hire an intern to do
it. I was just gonna work an hour

05:06:35.014 --> 05:06:38.774
later or two hours later that
night to do it. Like, it made

05:06:38.814 --> 05:06:45.994
my life easier. It didn't take a job.
That seems okay. As long as that ethical

05:06:46.114 --> 05:06:49.474
line stays in place, what
I- what I don't worry about

05:06:50.294 --> 05:06:53.834
is, no matter how good AI
gets, never gonna draw a

05:06:53.954 --> 05:06:57.674
picture like Arnold Tsang. It's
never gonna tell a story like Chris

05:06:57.734 --> 05:07:03.134
Metzen. You know, that human
spirit is irreplaceable.

05:07:03.194 --> 05:07:07.064
- Yeah, it's hard to put into words what
is that magic that humans produce, but

05:07:07.114 --> 05:07:09.994
they do. Truly great creative

05:07:10.054 --> 05:07:13.754
minds, truly great creative
teams, they create something

05:07:13.854 --> 05:07:17.774
special. It's hard to really
articulate exactly what's

05:07:17.814 --> 05:07:21.854
missing with with AI, you know,
what people call AI slop.

05:07:23.073 --> 05:07:26.854
'Cause it creates really beautiful
imagery and beautiful stories, and very

05:07:26.954 --> 05:07:34.934
believable text. But it's not quite...
It doesn't have that, I don't

05:07:34.954 --> 05:07:40.914
know what it is, the edge that's
human. Maybe it's the imperfections.

05:07:41.414 --> 05:07:45.374
- Yeah, I think so. Like AI to
me right now currently, it's

05:07:45.414 --> 05:07:48.164
it's like an interesting
fever dream, you know?

05:07:48.174 --> 05:07:49.314
- Yeah. Yeah.

05:07:49.354 --> 05:07:52.074
- That's at the point I'm at with it.

05:07:52.134 --> 05:07:55.054
- And a useful tool for the
mundane tasks, like you said.

05:07:55.064 --> 05:08:00.714
But do you think the small studios
have hope in the future of gaming?

05:08:00.774 --> 05:08:04.143
- Small studios are the future
of gaming. The big studios

05:08:04.294 --> 05:08:07.814
basically acquire the small
studios for new IP and

05:08:07.894 --> 05:08:10.583
ideas, and the small studios grow in. The

05:08:11.954 --> 05:08:17.834
really compelling, new, innovative ideas
are gonna come out of small studios.

05:08:17.894 --> 05:08:20.114
- What advice would you give to video game

05:08:20.154 --> 05:08:25.914
creators, small teams, if they
wanna create a truly special game?

05:08:25.934 --> 05:08:29.854
- Well, they know how to do it.
I mean, if they're doing it,

05:08:29.874 --> 05:08:34.674
they know how to do it. It's
more to video game developers in

05:08:34.814 --> 05:08:42.574
general, own the craft. Own our art
form. Stop giving it to these fucking

05:08:42.714 --> 05:08:49.604
corporate jackals. You are the
golden goose. Keep your eggs.

05:08:51.734 --> 05:08:55.534
- Jeff, formerly from the
Overwatch team, I have to

05:08:55.574 --> 05:08:59.114
say from the bottom of my heart,
and I think I speak for millions of

05:08:59.154 --> 05:09:03.054
people, thank you for everything
you've created in this world. Now

05:09:03.074 --> 05:09:06.874
that I've gotten the chance to see the
new game, I can't tell you how excited I

05:09:06.934 --> 05:09:10.614
am to try it. Thank you for everything
you've created. Thank you for everything you

05:09:10.654 --> 05:09:15.874
represent. Thank you for
remaining and fighting

05:09:16.954 --> 05:09:24.454
for us as one of us. So thank you,
and thank you for talking today.

05:09:24.514 --> 05:09:25.294
- Thank you, Lex.

05:09:26.634 --> 05:09:30.594
- Thanks for listening to this conversation with
Jeff Kaplan. To support this podcast, please

05:09:30.613 --> 05:09:34.514
check out our sponsors in the description,
where you can also find links to

05:09:34.553 --> 05:09:38.014
contact me, ask questions,
give feedback, and so

05:09:38.114 --> 05:09:42.394
on. And now, let me leave you
with some words from Franz Kafka,

05:09:43.434 --> 05:09:47.154
"Don't bend. Don't water it
down. Don't try to make it

05:09:47.234 --> 05:09:50.574
logical. Don't edit your
own soul according to the

05:09:50.634 --> 05:09:57.754
fashion. Rather, follow your most intense
obsessions mercilessly." Thank you for

05:09:57.774 --> 05:10:02.834
listening, and hope to see you next time.

